DayInLife: The Long household is a very active one with three teenage girls. We live in a suburban single-family two-story home with a fenced in backyard and a nice park across the street.    Typically it's a push to get everyone out by 7:45am to schools and work. Mom stays at home but has enjoyed some free-lance work predominately in her home office. School is dismissed at 3, so the kids return by 3:30, but different days have different kids home at different times depending on the sports season. Basically count on 2:30-8pm being a carpool extracurricular extravaganza with some kids left at home to mind supper and do homework. It is a rare night that anyone but Dad is out after 8. Dad works hard, and often late.    Julianna, 15, is a ballerina with classes T & Th 5-7pm at the school at the end of our street. She is also active in her school's theater department so in the spring there will be one "Tech-Week" where all hands are on deck and we don't see her until 10pm. She is a serious student who really looks forward to a companion to be with her and her laptop during those long study sessions.    Katie, 13, had knee surgery this fall. She no longer needs a brace and can bend her knee. She will use crutches for only one to two more weeks.  She has physical therapy on T/Th for 1 hour, but the doctor has told her no sports this spring. He has given her the green light to get a puppy -- as long as it's not a "big" puppy. Already, the whole prospect of raising a puppy has brightened her outlook tremendously. She can walk the dog on sidewalks, but won't be doing any off-roading in the woods of our neighborhood park anytime soon.    Lauren, 11, is over scheduled -- especially in the winter months.  She does year round swimming with practices 5-6pm M & W; is on the school basketball team with practices on Th nights 5:30-6:30 and games on Sunday afternoons and a few Sat nights; and is also on the White Tail Ski Team which involves one parent driving her up and back on both Saturdays and Sundays. We leave at 7am and get back around 3pm.  Some weekends we don't go both days -- especially if it is raining and too warm. The other girls don't participate in this, so they will be home during this time. Even though Lauren is the busiest schedule-wise, she is the youngest, most affectionate, and most playful.  I have witnessed her taking the neighbor's dogs out for walks in the rain, and I know she will be loyal beyond belief to this dog. She doesn't realize this, but she really does need to be older than somebody (anybody!) else in the house. This is her opportunity to be a big sister, and I know she can't wait.    My daughters are all very excited about doing this. They were raised to be social-minded and believe in giving back. They just didn't realize it could be so much fun! I think there will be some over-zealousness in the beginning, but given the realities of our hectic schedules, things will settle down. They are going to cover each other when needed and divvy up the chores and pleasures of having a pet in a chart so that they can share the responsibilities and the love.    Upon further reflection, we think we would prefer to have a female dog -- after all we do specialize in girls!  As you know, our previous GEB dog was a Golden, so a GLAB would be welcome as much as a Lab. We know all about the hair getting EVERYWHERE, so with that in mind, yellow is our preference but not an absolute requirement. (Vacuuming is going to be an item on that chore chart!)    Re:vacations - we take two weeks off in the summer typically in August. One with each set of Grand Parents. Often, we do vacation rental by owner, and there is a possibility of getting a dog-friendly house if it is ok with GEB to bring the puppy with us to the beach/mountains in NC or maybe even the Eastern Shore. We are happy to host other dogs for puppy swaps as well as when other raisers have trips planned.      Since the high school schedule does not match the elementary school schedule, we will not be going away for spring break.  Instead there is a 4-day weekend in Feb for President's Day, and Daddy is in dire need of a vacation with his family.  Nothing is set in stone yet, but we would like to raise a flag that we are likely to need coverage for that time.    I am really looking forward to being a part of the GEB community again. Things have changed quite a bit, so the girls will be on top of me as to what the current methods are and correct my old habits. Already I have enjoyed watching my daughters take this responsibility with such seriousness and vigor. They spur each other on to do the readings, to puppy-proof not only their rooms but the whole house, and to campaign their Dad into getting the puppy in January instead of "who-knows-when!" later in the year.  It has been heart warming, and the dog isn't even here yet! Thank you for giving the Longs such happiness already.

DayInLife: I am a full time college student with a demand of school work. My typical class schedule is 4 or less classes a day which amount to 1 to 6 hours of class with varying amounts of breaks depending on the day. I live on campus in a dorm room with a roommate. Each dorm floor has about 30 rooms with 5 floors in the building. During the school week (Monday-Friday) I do not work at a secondary job, my primary job is school work.  A puppy who is more quiet is preferable. On the weekends (Saturday-Sunday) I work at a dollar store away from school which entails me to stay at my house (Orchard Park) for those days and off campus. On average I can work from 4-6 hours on those days. Though I will be away from the puppy for those times, my mother, who has been taking the pre-placement classes with me, does not work and is home all weekend. I have been at the dollar store for 3+ years and usually have no problem working around my schedule for any reason. I do own 2 other older dogs at my house. The eldest is a 5 year old Coonhound. Though she is older, she can keep up with a little pup! The other is a 2 year old Cocker Spaniel/Pug mix who is a ball full of energy any time of day! I have worked out a plan with my roommate ( Brigitte Carrier-Auger) and my neighbor across the hallway (Jessie Burgess another GEB puppy raiser) for "get busy" breaks when I am unable to do so. Jessie and I have also arranged daily play dates to ensure the puppy will get the proper amount of physical and mental stimulation. My school's guidelines (Medaille College) is that the puppy must be 12 weeks of age and fully vaccinated before he can be on campus. Taking this into consideration, I would like to discuss the possibility of getting an older puppy (12 weeks of age) to expedite my raising experience. Thank you for this opportunity and I look forward to meeting my puppy.

DayInLife: I am a property  manger of a large estate. A typical day consists of out the door around 630 across the drive way to the brake room where I will assign tasks to the 5 employees that work with me. I will than go about my business answering emails and check on progress on various projects. There are time where I will be  working in a wood shop. I do a lot of walking around the estate. I also do spend a lot of time in a normal week driving place to place to pick up supplies.  Every other weekend I spend with my 8 year old daughter. I also have her 3 days during the week. She is kind of low key kid not into sports or really running around a lot but there are times. I do like to get out and do some hiking during the summer, as well as camping.   One thing to note I am in the Coast Guard Reserves, which consist of going in to drill 2 days a month and 2 weeks a year. I am stationed in Suagerties NY so I am home nightly during my drill days. The average Coast guard day is form 7am to 1Pm most days but there will be a few days where i would be gone for up to 9 Hours. On that occasion I have would have one of the employees here at my everyday job let out the pup.   On most  evenings I spend either help do  home work or hanging out at home. On occasion i will go out for dinner. My house is a typical cape style. 2 floors. I have two out door fenced in dog runs that are very large. Those runs are occupied during the day with 2 Labs and 2 jack Russel tarrier until 3pm. Another spot on the property has a hound barn witch there are some walkers and Black and tans. All the dogs are Male with the exception of a few females. So my preference would  be Male, As for the color I don't mind either way.      Thanks   Matt

DayInLife: My typical day prior to becoming a puppy raiser consists of getting up in the morning, preparing myself for work and walking the eighth mile to work. I have a 1 hour lunch break, which I spend at home and am finished with work at 5. I return home after that time and run any errands (usually on foot) or participate in martial arts classes.   Once I have become a puppy raiser, I plan to rise at least an hour earlier to let the dog eliminate and then go on a long morning walk. My friend Lauren will also walk the dog  after I have gone to work and practice training exercises before my lunch break. During lunch the dog will be out of the crate again. After work, I plan to bring the dog on most errands (particularly once we have established basic behaviors). I live alone and intend training to be a constant and consistent endeavor. Once the dog can effectively Settle, I plan (and have received permission to) bring the dog to the office with me, for gradually increased amounts of time. Burlington is generally a dog-friendly city where the pup will undoubtedly be exposed to numerous other dogs, people, noises, surfaces and fast moving objects. I also happen to live in a part of the city in which many refugees are settled and a number of elementary schools are located. This will give the dog the opportunity to experience people from numerous nationalities as well as small children. Lauren works with children and hopes to bring the dog on visits to her after school program once the pup is ready to handle that amount of stimulation. I am open and eager to work with the Regional Manager to establish a relationship which allows for open communication and constructive feedback. I am looking forward to the opportunity to be involved in the mission of this organization and the chance to train a puppy with a purpose.

DayInLife: I live in a small brownstone building on Manhattan's Upper West Side.  It is a co-op and I am the Treasurer of the Board of the Corporation which, in my building, means I do everything from paying the bills to escorting the exterminator around the building every month, to scheduling inspections and repairs of the boiler and elevator and. . . . well, you name it and in my building the Treasurer does it all!    My husband, Michael, will be raising the puppy with me.  Our neighbors, especially a teenage boy upstairs, all support our raising of a GEB puppy and help with the process.  We have five adult children between the two of us, none of whom live with us but we do visit each other when we can and the "kids" always love playing with whatever puppy we happen to have.  The actual raising of the dog, however, will be done by us.   Our apartment is on two floors and has an internal spiral staircase so early  on our puppy will learn how to walk up and down those stairs.   We have a large terrace which is a great space for grooming and playing as well. Michael has a full-time (9 - 5 )job whereas I teach flute lessons outside our home around 8 hours/week.  My teaching hours are flexible so clearly I am at home during the day more than Michael is.  I have rehearsals one evening most weeks and Michael will be taking classes at NYU two evenings/week.  We are planning to cover for each other during those times.  My day typically revolves around straightening up the house (laundry, dishwasher, making the bed), checking never-ending e-mail, dealing with endless co-op business (I am the Treasurer, remember?), my teaching schedule, practicing, rehearsals (and performances) and my commitment to going to my local YMCA for an hour's exercise every weekday.  I raised one other GEB dog and found it extremely useful to take him with me everywhere I could: the bank, Eileen Fisher (they love dogs there), the Gap, Gracious Homes, the Post Office, the subway, buses - basically everyplace except places that serve or sell food.  However, we even found an outdoor restaurant in Cold Spring, NY where we could take him right to the table with us.  Both of us will make a point to take the pup with us wherever we go.  We live near both Central Park and Riverside Park and anticipate many walks with puppy there as well.    Finally, we have a home in the Poconos, Pa which provides an entirely different experience for our puppy.  We have found that all dogs (we have sat a few in addition to raising Saxon) love to explore a new, much larger house and - the best of all - learning to swim in the lake that is about 100' or so from the back of the house.  Also, it gives us a chance to take the dog on a ride in the car (1 1/2 to 2 hours), something we city-folk don't tend to do as much as our suburban counterparts.    We understand the challenges of incorporating the care of a young puppy into our lives that are already busy with work, family and housekeeping commitments, but we both love dogs (we both grew up with dogs as pets) and look forward to integrating our new, very special, puppy into our lives.  As for me, I find it nothing short of an honor and privilege to be part of the process that will enable a dog to open the world to a visually impaired person.  Ever since I was in seventh grade, I was fascinated with "Seeing Eye Dogs" and seriously considered a career working with Seeing Eye in Morristown, NJ.  Now, several years (only several :-)) and several careers later, I am not surprised to find myself still fascinated by the intelligence and almost magical ability of guide dogs to perform their jobs.  I am grateful to enjoy my life as it is right now:  with my new husband, teaching & playing music, managing my small apartment building in NYC, and raising a dog for GEB.  I will do the best I can to enable our next GEB puppy to be the best guide dog he can be.

ExerciseType: Walking downtown, lots of running after and fetching ball and toys, loves to play tug, and recently began responding very well to "out." He plays well with other dogs, no aggression or biting. In the office, he is great most of the time settling and enter
ExericeAmount: 90+ minutes of active play and going on walks
KennelCommandComments: Knows what to do, but sometimes wants to be lured.
HousemannersComments: Still likes to steal shoes and towels but now responds consistantly to "Out"
LeftUnattendedComments: Not quite ready to be fully trusted, but he's getting there.
EliminationHouseComments: He has to go down a long hallway, down 9 floors on the elevator, across the lobby (sometimes having to pause when people don't realize he "needs" to go outside, across the courtyard and to the grass to "get busy.". Very rare "mistakes" are mostly my fault letting too much time pass if I get hung up in a meeting. He actually tries to hurry outside when I get back late. Most of the time, he makes it without incident. At home, he was housebroken and barked at the door once to let me know, on the second day I had him.
PlaybiteComments: In over-excitement with other dogs around, he will get mouthy, but doesn't really bite like he used to. When playing tug, he is careful not to bite fingers.
StealFoodComments: He hasn't had interest because he doesn't get any, but not sure he wouldn't if left unattended.
BarksExcessivelyComments: He's great, responds to "No bark" except when around other dogs.
RaidsGarbageComments: Loves to steal paper and tissues, but drops them now on "Out"
JumpsComments: Never did it a lot, but when he's very excited, he will occassionally jump on people, wanting to play.
FriendlyWAnimalsComments: Loves my horses, doesn't hurt the chickens, but gets way over excited with other dogs...wants to play. Not aggressive to them at all.
StrangerComments: He loves everybody!
WalkingComments: So often, he's so good on a loose lead that it's exhilarating. He can be amazingly good!
EliminateRouteComments: He sometimes poos on the sidewalk or when crossing the road, but it's my fault for not taking the time in the morning to wait for him to do it.
ChaseComment: Doesn't chase my chickens, squirrels, rabbits, but wants to get to other dogs to play. Will follow my cats, but they discourage him and he will stop and bark until I tell him "No bark."
NoiseComments: I would say he's curious and takes notice, but shows no fear other than perhaps a small reaction if it is close.
StairsComments: 9 flights during a fire drill with tons of people in the stairwell with us...no problem!
SitComments: If he's focused or not distracted by other dogs, he's a 4. With other dogs, it takes me awhile to get his attention, but then he does sit momentarily.
DownComments: Again, if not distracted by dogs, he's a 4.
StayComments: He is perfect, even when playing hide and seek at lunch in a crowded, busy lobby at work and when playing fetch...a 5, unless distracted by other dogs.
ComeOnLeashComments: Most of the time, he's great, but sometimes he's more interested in sniffing outside. Does respond to "This way" changes most of the time, tho.
ComeOffLeashComments: Most of time, he's got great recall, but sometimes inconsistant, and just stands there and looks at me.
PillsComments: I've never given him pills, so I don't know. I anticipate that it wouldn't be much of a problem at all.
NailsComments: Working very hard on this. Have had to get creative with "Shake" so it is his idea to let me handle his paws, and "Paw Cookies" so he will learn to keep feet still while I put cookie on them and make him wait to eat them. He learned that extremely fast! Just a few days ago, I got all nails on all 4 feet clipped in one session, with help from second person. Big improvement!!
GeneralComments: Troy is very willing, can focus wonderfully, walks in the city on a loose lead, places on grates, "stays" in high foot traffic areas inside and out, recalls quickly when focused, is not barking in the office much at all any more, is staying focused on me much more now in the office with other people all around, checks in with me a lot during walks, can correct his own position on walks, spits out pieces of bark and sidewalk stuff he picks up-without me telling him to now, can play outside - with the chickens and horses loose in the pasture and not pay them any mind , has never tried to leave the yard (he would tho, if another dog came around), and has had really good walks in Colonial Williamsburg with other dogs on leashes, but just as often has "bad" days when other dogs are just too much for him to handle well. He's brilliant when he's good and yet has to be removed from class or other dogs when he can't control his excitement. "Approach and retreat" seems to work to help him handle these times, and I'm highly hopeful it will help him get over his emotional response when dogs are around. Our new outside classroom should give us the room for approach and retreat. It's not about the task when he is over-excited...it's about having the patience and several strategies to help him through the behavior with his dignity and confidence intact. Troy is amazing...he's a very quick, smart, willing, affectionate, friendly pup with some challenging inconsistancies and over-excited reactions to other dogs, but we will work hard to get past those so he can put his talents to the best use.

HealthComments: He has had problems with possible allergies and he is still getting over a recent bout of diarrhea and vomiting but, other than that he has been very healthy
StoolComments: He has only had bad diarrhea twice, both times he ate something.
ExerciseType: Many walks a day, frequent playdates with other Guiding Eyes dogs, fetch
ExericeAmount: At least an hour a day
EliminationCrateComments: Hates to get his crate dirty
CrateQuietComments: Most of the time he is good about this, but, recently he became ill and, since I couldn't take him with me to class,  I all of the sudden had to put him in his crate much more frequently and for much longer time periods than he is used to. At first, he was very good but the last time I put him in his crate he barked and scratched at the door for the first minute or two. I simply think that I increased his crate time too quickly and I plan on starting from the beginning again with shorter crate time and working our way back up.
ChewingComments: Normally very good about this
OnFurnitureComments: For the most part, he stays off the furniture but when he goes to a new place he likes to test you and see if he is allowed on the couch. Once you tell him to get off though, he usually stays off
BarksExcessivelyComments: A few times (maybe 3 or 4 times) since I've gotten him he has barked when seeing another dog. I have realized though, that it is not just seeing another dog, it is seeing another dog that he knows well. He used to have the same reaction when he saw me for the first time after being away, but he has since gotten over this. He hasn't barked at another dog for a while now and, as long as I have high value treats when he sees a dog that he knows he seems to be fine.
CountersDoorsComments: He used to really like to steal gloves off of the counter but he has not done this in a long time
JumpsComments: He is very good during people greetings but sometimes when he is outside of the format of people greetings he will jump. For instance, if I come home after being gone for a long time occasionally he will jump. He also occasionally has trouble with a couple of people that he really loves but I believe that he is improving in this area and, again, when doing people greetings, even for the most part with people he loves, he has not been jumping
EliminateRouteComments: He will occasionally go when we get to one of his pee spots before I have told him to go; however, he has not been peeing anywhere else
ChaseComment: There is one spot at Cornell where, if he sees a squirrel he will try and chase it but it's just on that one street corner and other than that he doesn't try to chase animals
ComeOffLeashComments: He is very good at coming, unless there are other dogs involved, then he has a lot more trouble

HealthComments: occasional ear debri (left ear)
StoolComments: yes-end of defecation sometimes soft
EliminationCrateComments: no potty accidents
ChewingComments: sometimes chews softer toys- never furniture or other
HousemannersComments: likes socks, but will bring them to you, likes bed- but improving, much less now; still needs work on "go place" when people arrive
LeftUnattendedComments: improving- not so worried
PlaybiteComments: sometimes tries to hold arms when excited- improving and very responsive to redirecting
OnFurnitureComments: working on staying off of bed
BarksExcessivelyComments: sometimes will alert bark (excessively)
JumpsComments: rarely
FriendlyWAnimalsComments: has had a few occasions recently with growling at other dogs (either on leash or behind kennel doors), has strong instinct to chase birds and small critters- but we are working on this- getting a little better
KidsComments: she is still unsure of children, especially if they approach her- doing a little better with repeat exposure to same child, does better if she approaches child, beginning to work more confidently with slight distance- shows inconsistent behavior, sometimes urinates when she sees kids
StrangerComments: occasionally becomes overwhelmed with a stranger, especially groups of people- better with one on one greeting, better with her approaching person vs person approaching her
WalkingComments: good most of the time- still needs work with distraction and especially in windy conditions
GetBusyComments: needs work with distractions- sometimes takes a long time or repeated commands
ChaseComment: strong instinct to chase critters in open areas- rarely chases house cat
TrafficComments: doing better- still nervous around fast moving or loud vehicles- need to work more on same direction traffic
NoiseComments: doing better- still is unsure of loud sustained noises (close, loud Sirens and loud music) does better further away
StairsComments: a little unsure if railing is open- but we seem to be working through it
SitComments: needs work with distractions
ComeOnLeashComments: needs work with distractions
ComeOffLeashComments: needs more work with distractions- comes if the reward is higher
NailsComments: sometimes is leary when she sees the grooming bin- but usually is ok with actual clipping
GeneralComments: Wind and blowing objects are a challenge for Karen- but we are working on them.  She also seems to still need a lot of reinforcement for sustained attention.   She still needs more confidence when challenged with new environments and "close", tight spaces.

FoodType: Iams Vet Formula - Intestinal Plus + Pumpkin
HealthComments: Inflamatory Bowel Disease
StoolComments: Now with special food generally firm
WalkingComments: Time in vet kennel was big setback
StairsComments: Want to race up and down
NailsComments: Does not like feet handled
GeneralComments: Seaver's illness has been a setback for us.  His loose lead walking was great at 8 months, but the time without training took a toll.  He still knows his basic commands and his house manner are excellent, but he is far less attentive and pulls far more than before.  Seaver has a lovely personality and he is a joy to have around.  I am still very concerned about his health - he is doing well on the special food, but is still very thin and not filling out normally.
DayInLife: I live in a rural area without sidewalks so much of our walking and training is done from work or by driving somewhere.  I work as the fiscal officer for a public library system - I have my own office within the larger administrative office on the lower level of the library - most of my office mates are very fond of dogs.  My children are all grown so the puppy get most of his child socialization at work or on occasional visits from my grandchildren.  Working at the library allows socialization with all types of people.  We generally take a walk at lunchtime - the area around the library provides all types of opportunities - a church and preschool next door -a small park on the lake, a police and fire station next to the park, numerous shopping areas, heavy busy traffic areas and quiet residential streets.  The puppy and I arrive at work at 9:00 and on good day leave by 6:00.  Our home environment is quiet, just my husband and me and sadly now just one 10 year old lab.  We have a large fenced yard  with a big doggie pool in the summer and children's play equipment which allows for fun outdoor activities and exercise.  Our evening exercise is frequently in the yard.  I attend several out of town training session each year and my puppies have had an opportunity to stay in hotels and attend large conference sessions.  We have also enjoyed their company on our vacations.  Our weekends are usually quiet and relatively unscheduled.  Our puppy accompanies us on lots of errands, usually a walk in a local park if the weather is reasonable and hanging out in the kitchen while we cook.  I am planning to retire soon - probably in about 18 months.  I have a good deal of flexibility at work, but I also have many responsibilities - I need a dog who can adjust to the office situation - because I have a 35 to 45 minute commute each way, I cannot leave the puppy at home unless my husband is available.

HealthComments: Although his eyes tend to run a bit.
ExerciseType: 1. Running in yard with other dog 2. going on walks
KennelCommandComments: occasionally stares with a blank face but follows order after
ChewingComments: mostly chews on his toys
HousemannersComments: still steals random items around the house but gives them right back with command of "out"
PlaybiteComments: good with toys but bites the hands gentle if he gets too rough
StealFoodComments: doesn't steal human food but steals other dog(sams) food if given the chance
OnFurnitureComments: trys to jump on furniture to reach a toy sometimes
BarksExcessivelyComments: when he wants attention he barks
JumpsComments: if he gets too excited
WalkingComments: the gentle lead is REALLY helping!
ChaseComment: only looks at them and gets distracted but doesn't run after them
ComeOffLeashComments: very energetic when off lead and will run freely but will not listen to come back with just our voices, needs a treat or a dog to get him back
NailsComments: havent done it ourselves; needs to become comfortable with it
DayInLife: Hope & Cathy's schedule: During the school year ~ I go to school from 8 am to 3 pm and my mom has the same schedule most of the time (9am to 3:20pm) My dad works everyday on the weekdays from 8:30am to about 5:30pm and also takes business trips. My sister Carly has a schedule for collage that is different every day but also has work and other obligations. On the weekends we all have off so we either relax at home or go out shopping for various things, hang out with friends and family, or even go on a short trip (not likely) Also on Sundays we go to church in the mornings or at night. During holidays and breaks we usually stay home unless there is a planned vacation or a suprise vacation (also not likely)Summer schedule ~ Hope, Cathy, Carly have off from school and work and dad does not, yet takes off many weeks for vacation time. We all stay home for most of the summer, hanging out with friends and family, enjoying sports like softball(adult league), going to a variety of celebrations, going to church and church events, relaxing. The only planned vacation that should be worried about this year is our trip to camp hickory hill with friends, it is occuring in the 2nd week of August for about a week (don't know specific dates yet but will be arranged). We live in a medium sized house with a very large back yard and front yard. The back yard is where we spend majority of our time also includes an above ground pool. We have one house behind us and one house right next to us on one side and a church blocked by trees on the other. Live on a busy street but our house is far from the road. Neighbors are close by(no sidewalk though on street) Since our schedule is busy with sports and other events we have a busy life sometimes and other times we have nothing to do. Personally i would like to have a lab but the choice is up to you based on our description. Thanks a bunch and can't wait!!!(:                 Hope & Cathy(:

ExerciseType: Walks, plays in yard with raiser, plays with other dog
CrateQuietComments: Very quiet at home, mostly quiet in other places, but will bark or whine a little.
ChewingComments: Chews on pencils, plastic, wood if he finds it on the ground, chews on people's clothes if stimulated while playing.
HousemannersComments: Good manners when he knows he being watched, not when he feels like there is no one watching him.
LeftUnattendedComments: Yes if tired, no otherwise.
PlaybiteComments: Will play bite during excited play, especially with my children if they are sitting on the ground with him.
BarksExcessivelyComments: Barks at other dogs, will sometimes bark at people if excited.
RaidsGarbageComments: Will stay out if on a leash or if someone is watching.  Will get in garbage if he feels he is unattended.
JumpsComments: Not often, but will jump up if excited.
WalkingComments: He can be very good, but cannot walk past other dogs without being distracted.  He is also distracted (but less so) by people on the street.
GetBusyComments: He is a 5 for going #1, but # 2 sometimes requires a little walking around.
EliminateRouteComments: Never pees on walks, but will have bowel movement if you don't wait for him to go at home.
ChaseComment: Chases our cat, is alerted to squirrels and birds, but doesn't chase them.
SitComments: Has trouble responding in the presence of other dogs.
DownComments: Same as above, down takes longer.
ComeOffLeashComments: He will come in my yard if I am close enough to get his attention.  WIl also come in other environments off lead if there are minimal distractions.
NailsComments: He doesn't like it, but he tolerates it and is much better than before.
DayInLife: I am a school teacher with 2 teenage children.  In July and August I will be home all day to work with the puppy.  In Sept., I usually wake up early (by 5AM) and can work/play/feed the puppy until about 8AM.  I can come home at lunch from 12:10-12:40 to feed/play with puppy.  My children will be home from school at 3:30 and I will be home at 4:30.  Our weekends are usually spent here at home and there will be 4 people who can play and work with the puppy.  I have an 11 year old male lab and a cat who has lived with the dog for 10 years.  We are pretty physically active.

HealthComments: Generally good -- some issues with her ears (infection) and a sensitive stomach
ExerciseType: fetch, walks, playing with other dogs when possible
KennelCommandComments: Sometimes takes some convincing at night when she needs to get up from her bed and go into her crate
ChewingComments: Sometimes chews rugs when left unattended, but never when I am around
LeftUnattendedComments: Very good with this, but as mentioned, sometimes will chew a rug
BarksExcessivelyComments: Good, but when trying to play with other dogs she will bark, sometimes obnoxiously.  Otherwise, never barks.
FriendlyWAnimalsComments: Good, but probably "too" friendly!  Needs to get better with her self-control
KidsComments: Again, probably too friendly.  Gets extremely excited with children
StrangerComments: Same as above
WalkingComments: Still pulls to sniff but is improving.
GetBusyComments: Generally very good except when she gets caught up in sniffing
ChaseComment: If given the chance, would certainly dart at an animal.
TrafficComments: More distracted by people than by cars.
NoiseComments: This has improved tremendously
StairsComments: She gets worried on stairs sometimes and will rush them
DownComments: Good but often waits for hand signal
ComeOnLeashComments: Skill has regressed lately and needs work
ComeOffLeashComments: Needs work -- ignores me completely when off lead
EarsComments: Due to ear infection and a lot of pain during that time, she not only hates her ears being cleaned, she fears it and will try to hide.  She is OK with me touching ears and looking in them but not good about cleaning them.
NailsComments: We work on this frequently but it just is not improving.  She just does not like her nails clipped
GeneralComments: Wind is a sweet pup and is really well behaved/confident in both familiar and unfamiliar places.  Her biggest challenges at this point in time is staying calm when seeing other dogs/animals and when strangers approach her.  She is easily excited in these situations.  Also, her "come" skills have regressed and she blows me off completely.  The BIGGEST challenge for Wind is the sniffing -- her sniffing often seems uncontrollable and she cannot focus on anything else.  Also, her busy nose also sometimes interferes with her ability to walk places -- if someone is smoking near a door, she will not walk into the door, if the elevator in our building was just cleaned and it has a strong odor, she won't get in the elevator (without some convincing).    Health wise -- she has been vomiting recently in the middle of the night (checked with vet and will continue to monitor).  Also, her ears seem to be a bother for her.  She had a nasty double ear infection a couple months ago and since then, she tends to shake her head a lot and prefers not to have her ears petted (although there doesn't seem to be evidence of another infection at this time).
DayInLife: As a student, my daily schedule tends to vary depending on my class schedule. Some days I have class for up to 4 hours whereas others I may only have 2 hours of class. My weekend schedule varies, and sometimes I go out of town to visit my boyfriend or my family, both of which are places the puppy can come along with me. Starting in the fall, I will begin seeing patients at my school's clinic as well as doing an externship at an assisted living in washington, DC. Whether or not the puppy can attend these two activities with me is still unsure. Either way, I have the flexibility to come home every few hours since I live locally to school and my externship. The most important thing to know about my lifestyle is that I live in an apartment building. A patient (and QUIET) puppy will be best for me (if possible!) since I will have to travel a little farther out of my building for the pup to get busy. My only major life change will be that my schedule is going to shift in the fall (as I mentioned with patients and my externship). I will be going on two separate vacations this summer that I may need to send the puppy on a puppy sit (dates are still not definite). I leave to go home to NJ over major holidays and around Christmas for a couple of weeks, but the dog will be able to come with me at that time (I just won't be able to attend classes at that time).

HealthComments: has had ear infections
ExerciseType: daily walks, play with other dogs, comes with me almost everywhere I go
ExericeAmount: at least an hour of walking per day, small amounts of dog playtime throughout the day, will start coming to school with me everyday at the end of the month.

PlaybiteComments: no play biting, but will "hold" hand or clothes in mouth VERY gently
OnFurnitureComments: will put paws on bed when first excited in the morning after first coming out of kennel, has gotten better at refraining from that and will put paws down as soon as you ask her to

JumpsComments: only when VERY excited
FriendlyWAnimalsComments: loves other dogs, wants to play with cats but leaves them alone if they hiss or growl

StrangerComments: loves everyone

ComeOffLeashComments: occasionally gets distracted, usually does very well
PillsComments: I haven't given her any pills other than HeartGuard, but she allows me to look in her mouth, so I assume pills would be easy
EarsComments: sits very patiently during this

DayInLife: I teach high school in an agricultural program where I see dogs throughout the week for our doggie daycare and grooming program.  I wake up at 4:30 am, leave work between 2:30-4:00 everyday (except Friday).  I would be able to bring the dog with me to school daily.  I have weekends free most of the time.

My son lives up at University of Delaware but usually stops home some weekends.

HealthComments: None so far!
ExerciseType: walks, playing with other dogs, fetch
CrateQuietComments: May whine a little but settles quickly. Whines a little in the morning upon first waking up.
KennelCommandComments: Very good.
ChewingComments: Generally good
HousemannersComments: Generally good - I don't leave a lot out for her to get into at this point. Counter surfed maybe twice at around 4 months but hasn't since.
LeftUnattendedComments: Has been left unattended outside crate for about 5 minutes while I do laundry in the garage - waits by door until I get back.
EliminationHouseComments: Goes outside every 3-4 hours. Occasionally eliminates outside when not told.
PlaybiteComments: If very excited, she may do this.
StealFoodComments: Hasn't had many opportunities. Currently working on leaving pet dogs food alone while they eat.
OnFurnitureComments: Frequently puts front paws up on furniture or your legs while you are sitting on the furniture.
BarksExcessivelyComments: Almost never barks - only time I've heard her bark is during play.
RaidsGarbageComments: Only bathroom garbage is left out. Sniffs it sometimes but hasn't grabbed anything from it.
JumpsComments: If someone is being really excited when greeting her, she may jump.
FriendlyWAnimalsComments: Friendly with my two pet dogs and GEB brood and my cat. Seems somewhat worried when meeting new dogs (tongue flicking & licking their mouths)
KidsComments: puppy sitter said Frost was great with their grandkids
StrangerComments: Perhaps too friendly - always wants to go and greet them especially if they make eye contact with her.
WalkingComments: Generally yes.  Needs work in more distracting situations.
EliminateRouteComments: Will occasionally urinate without being told.
ChaseComment: Doesn't chase cat or small dogs. Hasn't really seen animals outside so not sure if she would chase them.
TrafficComments: Aware of noise of traffic, especially if there are louder trucks, buses, etc. I notice more tongue flicking with more intense traffic but she will continue working with me.
NoiseComments: Seems sensitive to noises but typically recovers fairly quickly after sudden noises and is typically able to continue working with me
StairsComments: MUCH improved from when she was a puppy. Now working on having her stop on the stairs when I stop.
StayComments: Working on - short duration at this point.
ComeOffLeashComments: 90% of the time
PillsComments: Eats her heartworm pill in under 2 seconds
EarsComments: Have not tried yet but seems a bit unsure when I look inside ears
NailsComments: Generally okay - I am treating her after each nail clipped to make it a fun experience. I cut her nails once a week.
GeneralComments: Overall, Frost is a sweet little puppy. I read her as having average confidence as she does lots of tongue flicking, especially in new situations, and has had some reactions to novel objects. With repeat exposure, she definitely improves so there is lots of room for her to gain confidence if I take it slow with her. Would like another person's perspective to make sure I'm reading her correctly.

DayInLife: Family is mother, father, daughter (16) and son (19).  Son will be home from college for the summer on 5/10.  Daughter will be home during the summer and then in high school.  Mother works as a waitress on a variable schedule.  When father works he is very close to the house so that the pup can have busy breaks when no one is home.  We have 2 cats, 1 ferret, 2 birds and 1 guinea pig.  All pets are treated to be loved and allowed to be in all parts of the house.  We live on a 1 acre lot in a 2 story single family house with a basement.  There is no fencing in the yard.  We live in a country setting with shopping close by.  Daughter does gymnastics 3 times a week as well as meets.  Schedules are very flexible to meet the needs of the puppy as there is usually someone around every 3 or so hours.  We often pass each other on the way to the next thing that is going on.

GeneralComments: Belva is a smart, quite sensitive dog. She is very attuned to the emotions of the people around her and offers her support when she senses that something is not quite right. She is of lower energy and lower drive than most of the other dogs I have had. This makes her easier to work with and take places because she stays in think and learn mode more easily. Her socialization is going very well. One challenge I have with her is to keep her motivated and enthusiastic about her work. You can see this in class when she is much less cooperative at the end of class. Her severe food allergies make using high value treats difficult. A 40 minute walk is about all she is up for, even less on a day where the temperature is above 70 which she considers very hot. Lol  She is a very thorough, thoughtful sniffer û especially around dog smells. It seems like if she were left to her own devices that she would get lost in the smells and sniff endlessly. This is not much of a problem inside, but can be a problem outside. I have found that giving her clear direction about the sniffing is a good approach to take with her. Her mode of choice when we walk in the neighborhood is to walk to the extreme left of the sidewalk with her nose hovered about three inches above the grass. She has learned that IÆm not pleased with her stopping frequently to get a good long sniff anywhere, but this is her compromise so she can still enjoy the lovely smells but keep moving. I have taken to having her walk in the middle of the sidewalk where she will keep her head up better.  Nail clipping continues to be very challenging. She hates it so much. When I get the clippers out she tries to sweet talk her way out of it with wags and kisses. She will lay down for me and I can usually get one done (not always though). Occasionally, I can do another one, but more often than not, after cutting one nail, we have to backtrack almost to the beginning in the desensitizing small steps that lead to the actual cut. Many times she is just too nervous and will get to the point of not wanting to lay down any more. Again, without high value treats it is hard to find something very rewarding for her after getting a nail cut. Her best reward is to put away the clippers which usually gets a very enthusiastic response from her.  I have a note about her eliminating on command. Belva can go for a very long period without needing to get busy. With the dew on the grass and the sprinkler system going during the summer we learned that she does not like to walk on the wet grass. First thing in the morning taking her out I find that if the grass is wet she wonÆt leave the deck. If pick her up and take her out in the yard she stands there looking miserable and may even pick her feet up and shake them like dogs do when the pavement is too hot. The good news is that she can hold it just fine so I donÆt worry that this will lead to accidents in the house. She may, however, wait until the afternoon until she will go. Her record is not going until 3:00. Under normal circumstances, if I take her out any sooner than 6 hours, she wonÆt go. She may just lay down and look at me. So in answer to the question, does she eliminate on command, I have a mixed response in that she will go û if she feels like she has to - you have to be aware of how often she really needs to go out.  BelvaÆs food allergies are severe. I have emailed Dr. Sandler and got permission to feed her a food that is sold both at PetSmart and Petco. Luckily, I have found something that she tolerates pretty well. The huge problem with her is that almost all grain free foods use white potatoes in the formula. Belva is highly allergic to white potatoes (itching, chin acne, blood in her stool). I have been adding various foods that are ingredients in dog foods as a single ingredient added to her regular food to see exactly what she will react to. The choice of dog foods that she can tolerate is very limited and usually very expensive. I plan to continue to experiment with ingredients so I can give Dr. Sandler as much information as possible when she goes up for her IFT since this could be an issue for her as a guide.  All in all we are enjoying Belva immensely. She is a very nice, sweet personality to have in our home.

HealthComments: had an ear infection when we got him one month ago
ExerciseType: walks, playing ball/running fenced in yard
ChewingComments: will chew leash in car, seems driven to rip toys ie plastic frisbee, rope, toys etc  Has taken items and destroyed them but has not chewed furniture.
LeftUnattendedComments: will jump up and take items off the table or counter, must be watched
OnFurnitureComments: attempted to climb on sofa, must be watched
RaidsGarbageComments: goes right for the trash or the paper recycle bin
CountersDoorsComments: has destroyed items left on the counter or table when not monitored
JumpsComments: he wants to jump but usually responds to the sit command
WalkingComments: improving, but pulls, is unmanageable when he sees other dogs on a walk
ChaseComment: if he sees another dog on a walk he attempts to go after it even if we have turned the other way, he continues to turn back will even attempt to walk backwards, have not noticed the need to chase squirrels, can be overly interested in birds
GeneralComments: We have had Opa about one month.  He is a very loving dog.  He enjoys walks and playing ball in the yard.  He has a good energy level and sleeps all night.        We are working very hard with him on LLW.  He tends to walk in front and wants to pull.  He has made some improvement.  He has a horrible time if he sees another dog on a walk. We generally go the other direction to avoid the dog if possible.  If he sees another dog within about 10 ft. he jumps, leaps, barks and carries on until the dog is out of sight.  We will continue to work on this in hopes that the high value treats in combination with him getting older will calm him down.       Opa can not be left unattended with items on the counter or table.  He has taken glasses, a wallet, gloves etc..and chewed them. (Needless to say he has trained us to put everything away.) Opa has a bin of chew toys, bones, toys etc.  We continue to remind him where his toys are and praise him when he takes his own toys.     We have already seen some improvement in these behaviors in the last few days.

GeneralComments: Recently Gerta has returned (somewhat) to habit of pulling grass when on walks.  At home she is comfortable and cooperative.  When visiting others Gerta gets rather hyper at first but usually "settles" fairly quickly.  She is most uncomfortable and anxious in the weekly class, as evidenced by her frequent need to urinate and circumstantial barking.  She is normally quiet, content, and responsive.
DayInLife: Recently Retired - just me  We live in a private (unfenced) home in the city but a suburban environment with a forest right behind the house.  In addition to attending puppy raising classes, I also have guitar and arthritis classes each week. Each calls for roughly 3 hours absence from home.  Weather permitting, I play golf (9 holes) twice a week.  Presently I go to the gym twice a week; in the winter it will be three or four.   Two to four times a month we attend musical or theatrical performances - requiring a 4 to 5 hour absence.  Once or twice a week I do volunteer driving to take elderly persons and others without transport to medical appointments.  A couple of times a month we visit my mother in Bloomfield - near Hartford.  Usually twice a year we take an out-of-country vacation for about 2 weeks each.  In the last 6 months I've developed a number of medical conditions/issues with feet and knees:  * arthroscopic surgery on left knee  * mild arthritis in left knee  * osteoarthritis in right knee  * broken accessory cuboid bone in left foot  * partial tendon tear in left foot  * tendonitis in both feet  * very recent onset on sciatica  The above conditions (some of which are improving) limit my ability to bend and twist.

HealthComments: Has been itchy since we got him.  Is now on Temaril-P for the itching.  Has had one UTI and ear infection.  Has had an itchy area on his muzzle which has required ointment and now he is on an antibiotic.  Has weekly baths with Comfort shampoo.  Is now on a limited ingredient diet for possible food allergies. Has been on solely Duck and Potato Diet since October 10.
EliminationCrateComments: On steroid has urinated once overnight--did have water somewhat late
CrateQuietComments: have heard him barking when left during day in crate while I am leaving in car
ChewingComments: still wants to get at stuffed animals and occasionally socks or shoes left out
LeftUnattendedComments: for very short period if no toys or food are in sight
EliminationHouseComments: on steroids so has has some urinating accidents in house.  He is drinking and  urinating more
PlaybiteComments: Has gotten much better since he has lost his baby teeth but sometimes will still h
StealFoodComments: will steal off kitchen table if food is left out
OnFurnitureComments: when excited he can still jump on furniture
BarksExcessivelyComments: demand barking for my attention on and off will occur while I am seated at computer or making food in kitchen or has happened while driving
CountersDoorsComments: will still jump up for food sometimes
JumpsComments: when first meeting he has the tendency to jump up still and needs much supervision
WalkingComments: Very good in familiar areas.  Has more trouble with other dogs walking by or wanting to greet everyone who walks by
EliminateRouteComments: still will go during walk
ChaseComment: Most of the time watches squirrels but occasionally will  lurch towards one
StayComments: Stays fairly well for short periods
DayInLife: Our lifestyle changes depending on the season.  In the fall we aren't as busy.  I'll have kids in school (one in preschool 3 days a week, mornings only),  We have occasional afterschool activities.  Winter and spring are a bit busier with basketball and baseball/softball and holiday events and school.  Summer the kids are around and our schedule changes more on a weekly basis, depending on camps, vacations etc.  I am flexible to be home when needed.

LeftUnattendedComments: Still needs to watched around food
WalkingComments: Until I get his attention he will pull...Needs time to explore surroundings
StayComments: Still working on this...He is doing better
GeneralComments: Benton is starting to feel his oats, so he will pull while on lead and occasionally misbehave.  I am finding that if I get his attention, after he becomes comfortable in his surroundings, he responds very well.  I still need to reward him for his attention.He is learning new things pretty well and likes to explore new environments and objects.  Overall I think he is doing pretty well.

HealthComments: He had an ear infection in both ears back in January
CrateQuietComments: He barks in his crate when I put him in there and he thinks there is no reason to be in there and when I come home from school and he is in his crate he barks.
HousemannersComments: He gets into the garbage, jumps on the counters and the kitchen table, grabs papers off of the desk. I am asking my instructors what to do and other raisers what to do and am trying what they suggest.
LeftUnattendedComments: He will grab something off the table or counters and run away with it to get your attention.
StealFoodComments: He doesn't steal it but he does lick it.
OnFurnitureComments: We have been working on this and he's not getting on it all the way any more just part of the way.
BarksExcessivelyComments: He's quiet when he's out of the crate unless you try to keep him from doing what he wants to do.
RaidsGarbageComments: Some times he walks by it and then other times he sticks his head in and grabs something. The time he just walks by it I reward him for it.
CountersDoorsComments: He has a very good nose and can smell anything you put on the counter so he jumps up to try to get it.
JumpsComments: I only allow him to say hi to people who know what the rules for greeting him are for now. Once he's learned he's not supposed to jump then I'll work on letting him say hi to strangers.
WalkingComments: Sometimes he is really good and stays with me and other times he pulls.
GetBusyComments: For the most part he does but recently he has started not going (sometimes) when told and will try to go walk around the yard instead.
EliminateRouteComments: I will take him out to get busy before a walk and will wait 20 minutes for him to go and he won't go then we will start on the walk and not even half a block from home he will go. Our walks are on roads that are empty most of the time so I walk him down the middle of the road so he cannot sniff the grass so he doesn't go and he goes anyway. He has such a good nose it doesn't matter that we are walking in the middle of the road he can smell everything from there anyway.
TrafficComments: For about a two week period he would try to chase cars but then I started having him sit when a car went by and it stopped.
ComeOffLeashComments: Sometimes he does and sometimes he doesn't. Depends on the level of distraction.
PillsComments: N/A
NailsComments: We are still working on it but it has come a very long way. I am able to actually put the clippers on his nails and apply pressure without him pulling away.
GeneralComments: I am working on all of the things that have low scores on them. I am asking my instructors what to do and also other raisers what to do and am trying what they suggest. For eliminating on walks I will stand outside for 20 minutes telling him to get busy and he won't go so I think he doesn't have to go and we start walking and we get half a black from the house and he goes. Like I said up in the section for comments the streets I walk him on are empty the majority of the time so I walk him down the middle of the road so he cannot sniff anything but he still goes. And he goes because he can smell everything from there anyway. He has a fabulous nose. I put him in his crate in my room and then go out to the kitchen and open a jar of peanut butter and not two seconds later he is barking because he can smell it and he wants it. When we play hide and seek I don't call his name anymore because he smells something of mine and then he tracks me. I did not teach him that he taught himself that.

FoodType: Purina One Sensitive System Salmon & Rice
HealthComments: His diarrhea finally cleared after switching to Purina One
ExerciseType: 3-5 mile walks, play, off leash running in approved areas
ExericeAmount: Approx 1 hr daily for walking. 0-2 additional hrs (accumulated) in exercise-type of play.
ChewingComments: He is an aggressive chewer and will destroy anything that is destructible - but he only chews his things.
LeftUnattendedComments: I'm not sure. He follows his people closely everywhere at all times (somewhat underfoot), so unless in crate, never completely unattended. Unattended as in "unwatched" he's very well behaved.
PlaybiteComments: Never, except when tug gets too exciting, he'll go right up to the hand.
StealFoodComments: He stole food from a table he's just now able to reach while my back was turned. Hasn't happened since, but he hasn't been given the opportunity. I suspect he would steal food again if left in his reach (his reach is his muzzle w/all 4 on the ground - he has never jumped or tried to jump to reach for food).
CountersDoorsComments: He doesn't paw at or jump for counters, but will sniff around tables at nose level. He's outgrown taking things from the table tops he can reach (clothing, paper, etc.) with the possible exception of food (see above).
JumpsComments: Never.
FriendlyWAnimalsComments: Too friendly and way too excited
KidsComments: very excited and overjoyed
StrangerComments: interested and friendly
WalkingComments: He's generally pretty good. He gets ahead of me frequently, but is easy to get back. He still sniffs a lot but stops less and less - fire hydrants and the like are his biggest obstacles right now. He doesn't scavenge or show much interest at all in items along his path (we've finally conquered fast food wrappers, dog poop, and road kill). If he does pick something up, he generally drops it on his own. He doesn't chase blowing/moving things like leaves, but animals get his attention with some pulling if they're really close. If we encounter another dog (anywhere in sight), he will pull wildly at the lead. He is most distracted by smell. Garbage day is tough as are streets close to Lake Erie and its beach full of rotting fish. Sound, however, doesn't phase him at all. Overall, Sidney is good, not great on our walks. Of course there are days he surprises me with excellent, near-perfect behavior and other days it's as if he's never had a single day of training. Most days are good, not great.
GetBusyComments: He pees on command but usually needs to walk a while to poop. He also pees frequently on walks (assume this is marking behavior).
EliminateRouteComments: Always pees 4-5 times on walks, regardless of the length of the walk. He's been doing this for nearly 5 mos despite me working on it with him every day.
ComeOffLeashComments: Depends on what distractions are between us when I call. He's generally good.
NailsComments: N/A. I had no problem clipping his nails as a puppy. Now that we walk longer, other than the dew claws, his nails are too short to cut.
GeneralComments: He's doing great. There was a week in late Feb when he was so bad it was like he was a different dog. He was humping everything, destroying everything in sight, digging, barking, acting out and generally giving me his best Alpha impression. It passed as quickly as it came on and he's back to being the sweet, well-behaved puppy he's always been. I'm hoping it was just a one time thing and not a sign of the hormonal changes to come. The main issue Sidney has is his ability to be alone and entertain himself. His response to commands is also a little unpredictable lately.
DayInLife: During week, I work from home (writing) w/open schedule, many days completely free. I go to physical therapy 2-3 days/week (afternoons 1 hour). Misc errands some days. Weekends, I'm typically home in my garden out entertaining friends. I live in large house in quiet suburb w/lots of neighborhood kids and other pets. I live close to the lake and many parks. I lived in NYC for past 10 years and still have many friends there... opportunity to take much older puppy into city for a few weekends to explore parks, subway, apartment life, etc. if class leader thinks puppy can handle it.

ExerciseType: fetch, play with other dogs, tug
BarksExcessivelyComments: Cobey has a difficult time settling. He becomes wrestless and will start to bark after a few minutes.  He always seems to be looking to be on the go.
NailsComments: Is average with nail clipping as he tends to want to be silly (roll on back) during body handling.
GeneralComments: Cobey is a pleasure to have around for the most part and is a pleasure during his social outings as long as I keep his settle brief.      Cobey is extremely attached to me which leads me to believe that that is why his demand barking  escalates when I am talking with another person or paying no attention to him but to other people.

BarksExcessivelyComments: sometimes, especially when we can't read body language and the hours betw 7:30-9pm
RaidsGarbageComments: only because he is attended

GeneralComments: looking forward to reviewing this with our regional manager on our walk and talk.
DayInLife: I generally work 4 days/week, about 7 hours/day (usually 8:30-4pm).   There are some days when I work later in the evening but have flexibility to come and go throughout the day.  My husband works at home most of the time and our schedules can often complement each other.  I am a social worker in a not for profit agency and there can be occasions, when the puppy is a bit older, to bring him to work with me for brief periods of time.  We live in a private home with opportunities for the puppy to walk on various surfaces; meet canine and human neighbors and practice skills in various settings.  For exercise, we also like to walk in a variety of places (parks, urban, other neighborhoods) and will happily bring the pup along.  We like to go to Maine and Maryland to see our children every couple of months, on weekends when possible, and would like to take the puppy with us, if permitted.  We are somewhat social and enjoy having friends over for dinner or to hang out.  In addition, we host family and friends for several holidays, and some parties throughout the year.    We vacation in Maine several weeks throughout the year and hope to be able to bring the puppy there, too.  Having never raised a female dog, I would like to request, if possible, to have a male dog placed with us.  We are unfamiliar with the care of a female dog's menstrual cycle.  Please feel free to ask for more detailed information if I have not provided what you are looking for here.

GeneralComments: Liesel has been a challenge for me. She is not a confident dog at all.  She can be pet and touched in any way with no problem but the second you ask her to wear something she melts.  We've been battling diarrhea and demadex the last month or so. I don't know how to help her gain confidence because she is not very motivated. she has no toy drive other than fetching a tennis ball which she will not do if she is stressed or somewhere new. she will take food but its not enough most cases.  Ive done several 1 on 1's trying to help her best I can. Shes a great dog and is a joy to have in the house if there is no pressure.

FoodType: Iams adult food, lamb and rice flavor
CrateQuietComments: Brett is very comfortable in his crate.
ChewingComments: Brett only chews on his own toys.
HousemannersComments: Brett doesn't get into anything in the house, which is especially impressive given that most of our stuff is now in easily accessible boxes on the floor.
PlaybiteComments: Brett sometimes gets a little overzealous when playing, but he stops playing immediately if he accidentally grabs your hand instead of the toy.
StealFoodComments: Brett has a pretty good success rate with ignoring dropped treats.
OnFurnitureComments: Brett never tries to climb onto the furniture.
BarksExcessivelyComments: Brett only barks when he really wants something and doesn't know how else to express himself: for example, when he really wants to play with another dog in class.
RaidsGarbageComments: Sometimes he will briefly sniff an unfamiliar trash can but never tries to take anything.
JumpsComments: Brett will sometimes jump if he is very excited, but he is easily corrected. He leaps into the air next to you rather than jumping on you.
ChaseComment: Brett would like to chase squirrels and pigeons, but he realizes this is not appropriate and he is usually able to resist the impulse.
TrafficComments: Normally, Brett is totally comfortable walking on city sidewalks with heavy traffic. Since his incident on the plane, he has not been confident with traffic noises.
NoiseComments: Same as above--this is not normally an issue, except after a negative experience (thunder, plane).
EarsComments: Brett tries to sneak away if he sees a cotton ball, but he will sit still for you to clean his ears.
NailsComments: Brett is very cooperative at nail-clipping time.
GeneralComments: Brett is a sweet and obedient dog who is eager to please. He is very attentive to his people and wants to do what we ask. Our main concern with him right now is his fearful reaction on our recent plane trip and subsequent noise anxiety. We are definitely concerned about Brett's noise anxiety, but otherwise, we think he is doing very well. He is a wonderful dog.

CrateQuietComments: Quiet at all times except if we put her in the kennel during dinner, then she serenades us.
BarksExcessivelyComments: Mostly at class.  Sometimes if anxious to get moving or sees another dog.  Getting less all the time.
JumpsComments: Still forgets when over stimulates.  But most of the time she remembers.
KidsComments: Only twice have I seen her get confused.  But she has quickly overcome her reservation and then happily greeted the children.
StrangerComments: Maybe a bit too friendly.  We are working on not getting too excited.
WalkingComments: Still pulls and sniffs sometimes,  About 80-90 % of time she does not pull.
GetBusyComments: She is ADHD.  She has to find just the right spot and if something distracts her she will stop and then I have difficulty refocusing her.  In a.m. she usually poops within 2-3 minutes.  If it goes over 5 then I take her back inside, crate her and then take her back out again 15 minutes later.  Afternoon is still the poop that is unreliable and takes time.
EliminateRouteComments: Very occasionally she ail poop on walk.
TrafficComments: Still building confidence but doing better all the time.
NoiseComments: Most noises fine.  Still shows some concern over loud traffic noises/fire trucks.
StairsComments: Still bunny hopes, and races up the stairs.  She is beginning to respond to stopping on stairs and waiting for a treat.
SitComments: 98% of the time.  But occasionally sometimes I get a refusal to immediately sit.
ComeOnLeashComments: Yes, but still wants to immediately return to the heal position.
ComeOffLeashComments: Most of the time, except if she still wants to play outside. this only happens about 5-10 % of time.
EarsComments: She has been very good, but with the most recent ear infection is now actively avoiding ear drops and ear cleaning.
GeneralComments: She is getting more confident all the time.  She is maturing nicely and starting to resist some of the puppy antics like chasing leaves.  She loves working.
DayInLife: Betker Family Life    Weekday Timetable: (FYI. James, Rosie and Mairead are all Homeschooled)    5:30 a.m. Dellie (the Papillion) wakes Bob (Dad Betker) to go out to go potty.  6:00 a.m. Bob gets up for work  7:15 a.m. Bob leaves for work  7:30-ish Colleen (Mom Betker) gets up. Let's dogs Dellie and Jessie (the pound hound) outside again. Mostly to check for squirrels.  8:00-ish James, Rosie and Mairead are woken up.  8:30-ish Kids come down and start getting breakfast.  9:00-ish Kids should be heading upstairs to shower and change.  9:30-ish Kids should be heading down to start schoolwork.  10:00-ish Kids are finally downstairs and starting on schoolwork.  11:30-ish Kids take a break and if they haven't already they will often take the dogs for a quick walk.  12:00 to 4:00 Kids work on schoolwork and take small breaks as necessary and get lunch when hungry.  4:00 p.m. Kids can use electronics for leisure  6:00-ish Bob gets home from work and family dinner is served. After family dinner dogs are fed.  Somewhere between end of dinner and 8:00p.m. Family gets together for prayers.  9:00 p.m. Mairead and Rosie get ready for bed.  10:00 p.m. Girls finally settled down and go to sleep.   10:00 p.m. James gets first call for bed, which means he goes downstairs for a snack  10:00-ish Colleen goes to sleep  11:00 p.m. James get lights out call (if still awake.) Bob let's dogs out for final time and comes up for bed.  11:30 Bob goes to sleep    Jessie and Dellie are let out periodically throughout the day on an as needed basis. (They let us know when they want/need to go out.) Mostly they go out to check the yard for invading squirrels or such.  Dogs sleep most of the day just waking periodically to check out what is going on in the house.    •	Jessie is our calm, happy, laid back 45 lb. All American Dog.  We got her from the Animal Welfare League of Alexandria, when she was about a year.  She is now about 11 years old, but does not show any significant signs of aging.  She loves attention and is a real Daddies girl. (When Bob went to Iraq poor Jessie became very sad and melancholy, pining for her Dad. Thankfully she recovered once he returned. She loves to follow him all over the house as he does his chores on the weekends.) During the school day Jessie usually sleeps upstairs on whatever kid blankets have been left on the floor, or sometimes in the open kennel in the kitchen. Jessie mostly likes to snuggle on the floor with James at night. (Yes, James sleeps on the floor.  I think he does it now, just to get around the rule of, "No dogs on the beds.") Even though she loves to be with James, she does make her rounds to each bedroom at some point during the night.  Jessie is what most people would die for in family dog.  She loves having her head and neck scratched, and when happy (which is most of the time) her tail wags a million miles a minute.  She also loves carrying the kid’s stuffed animals around the house.  She never chews on them or destroys them, just sweetly carries them around.  She also rarely barks.  In fact, she didn’t bark at all for the first few years, but now occasionally barks at critters in the yard.  She has also been know to hide behind trees waiting for the squirrels to come down so she can chase them off again.    •	Dellie, our hefty 13 lb. Papillion, on the other hand is feistier. She affectionately goes by the nickname, fuzz-ball and suffers from the typical small dog mentality; I'm really a Great Dane in disguise. Dellie generally stays downstairs during the school day with Mom and kids or goes to her post on the stairs where she can monitor anyone passing in front of the house while still keeping an eye on the family. (Dellie has delusions of grandeur and fancies herself the great family protector.) Dellie tends to bark a little, mostly when she sees someone walking their dog down the street or when someone comes to the door.  Dellie, although not hyper, is more active than Jessie, especially in the yard.  Rosie is Dellie's favorite person. They bonded early when Dellie figured out that Rosie typically left a trail of food wherever she goes.  Dellie, although not aggressive, does not warm up to other dogs instantaneously. Even though we have had a number of “foster” dogs through our house in the past few years, it still takes her a few days for her to get used to the idea of a new invader.  Once she is satisfied that the new dog knows she is top dog in the house she settles down.    Scheduled Activities:    •	Monday, Tuesday and Thursday we try (emphasis on try) to reserve exclusively for schoolwork. (But would also be flexible during this time to incorporate puppy needs.)  o	James has Boy Scouts on Monday evenings from 7:00 to 8:15.  (To accommodate this, one of the kids and Colleen will drive Bob to work in the morning. We will leave about 7:15 and be back around 8:30 a.m. Then at 4:30 one of the kids and Colleen will go back and pick up Bob from work so Bob has time to have dinner before taking James to Boy Scouts.)  o	Rosie and Mairead will take a Pottery class though Fairfax County Recreation from 2:30 to 4:00 on Mondays, from March 31 through June 2, 2014. James will stay home. (Might be an opportunity here for socializing.)    •	Wednesdays are our activities day and go generally as follows:  o	9:20 - Rosie, Mairead and Colleen leave for horseback riding lessons. James stays home to work on schoolwork.  o	11:20 - We swing by the house to pick up James and karate gear and head off for karate lessons.  o	2:00-ish - We swing by the house to drop off the girls and James and I head over to Fort Belvoir for his teen group meeting.  o	4:20 - James and I leave Fort Belvoir to go home.   o	(However, once or twice a month on Wednesday Bob and I go out for "Life Counseling." On those Wednesday's, once James and I leave Fort Belvoir, we will head to downtown D.C. to go pick up Bob from work. If it is one of the weeks to pick up Bob, we will then head home to drop-off James and then Bob and I go out. Kids fend for themselves for dinner, James takes care of the dogs and Bob and I return around 8:30.).    •	On Friday's the kids and Mom attend an educational co-op with other homeschoolers at Good Shepherd Church in Mount Vernon.  We leave the house around 8:30 a.m. and return around 1:00 p.m. The spring program ends May 2, 2014 and doesn’t resume until fall 2014.    •	Weekends are unpredictable. We do not currently have any regularly scheduled activities. So, on weekends we try to get the house cleaned up (or relatively so) and do any running around and errands that need to be done. Anything that will help reduce the strain on the weekdays. Dellie still wakes Bob up around 5:30 to go potty and check the yard, Mom still gets up around 7:00-7:30, but Bob and kids grab a few extra winks and tend to get up on their own somewhere between 8:30 and 9:00, 10:00 at the very latest. Bedtime tend to remain the same as weekdays.    •	Summer is also unpredictable.  In the past we have done swim team or other activities or camps during the summer, along with a quick excursion to the beach at some point.  In the past, we have also typically taken a family vacation to Vermont the third week in July.  This summer the only thing on the schedule thus far is Boy Scout Camp for James the second week in July. Kids seem to prefer the unstructured, low-key summer to those of the past.  (Bob’s father died over the winter and Bob used a good bit of his leave.  So we currently are unsure if we will be able to take a family vacation this summer.)    In the past I would have described our house as loud and active, but somewhere in the past year or so as the kids have gotten more into their electronics and started to headed towards their teens, both the activity level and noise level have dropped significantly.  So although Bob and I often feel like we are being pulled in several directions, overall house has slowed down.     Lastly, we have one daughter away at college.  She is 23 years old and is finishing her Bachelors in Sign Language Interpretation at Towson University in Maryland.  She has her own apartment and works full-time in addition to going to school.  Because of her busy schedule she doesn’t get to stop by the house as often as she would like.  Her visits tend to be two or three quick stops by the house during the week and then no visits for two or three weeks.  She is expected to graduate from Towson in the Spring of 2015 but will probably not return to the house to live after graduation.    Sorry about the length, being brief has never been my strong suit.  And you said, … “leave a novel.”
