ExerciseType: short walks, playing fetch, playing with other dog
ChewingComments: easily redirected
LeftUnattendedComments: in crate
PlaybiteComments: easily redirected
RaidsGarbageComments: hasn't had the opportunity -
WalkingComments: working on it - take it slow  wait for check in
GetBusyComments: can be slow to go -
StayComments: just starting to work on this -
PillsComments: N/A
GeneralComments: Garland is an amazing pup. So happy to have her and co-raise with Danielle Slover.

HealthComments: some on-again, off-again diarrhea, have been managing it following vet protocol; sensitive stomach, only using low res/puppy chow, ie no additions, no training treats yet, no stuffed bones, etc
EliminationCrateComments: has never had an accident in crate
CrateQuietComments: We are taking it very slow with crating; so far so good. Sleeps in crate through night, accepts crating when we are home, can stay alone in crate for 1-2 hrs with other dog support (Nordic in same room), can also stay fully alone in crate but barks/whines a bit at first û we are working on the latter
KennelCommandComments: Very solid on crate manners entering and exiting
ChewingComments: Pup has a very solid out, but will pick up inappropriate objects - we are working on it, don't think it is going to be a problem
HousemannersComments: overall excellent, but pup jumps on people/furniture - we are working on it, expect to subside as he gets older/taller
LeftUnattendedComments: when left in crate, will whine/bark at first, but then settles
EliminationHouseComments: Toilet training on target. Doesn't yet ask to pee/poop outside but knows to GB whenever taken outside, no accidents in house lately
PlaybiteComments: Pup can be easily activated, when activated he mouths but frequency is diminishing quickly in the last week or so
StealFoodComments: never steals food from humans; we can eat at high and low tables and there are no problems; we are working on good dog-dog food manners. Work in progress but pup on target
BarksExcessivelyComments: I'm not sure what GEB expectations are here - he is more vocal than I'm used to with GEB dogs - he has learned that demand barking doesn't work (although still tries it from time to time) but he barks at new noises, or when he is frustrated; he will even bark at his reflection in the mirror (not out of fear, but more taunting)
RaidsGarbageComments: working on it - he is too young to give him free access to garbage
JumpsComments: Easily activated, environmentally dependent (i.e. greetings in very familiar places = no big deal for pup, greetings in new places=big deal)
KidsComments: activated a bit, but I think he will outgrow this
StrangerComments: Formal greetings are solid but we keep working on it as it will change as he ages. Greetings at work are great, to the point where he will simply ignore new people;  in other locations he is not as ambivalent to new people-we are working  on it
WalkingComments: Have been focusing most of our efforts on WWP (and name recognition, check-in)
NoiseComments: so far, this pup seems fearless
StairsComments: he has LOTs of stair experience at home and office; this pup seems to have excellent control of his body, i.e. can already (on his own) reverse direction midway on stairs, no longer bunny hops, sometimes plays with other dog on stairs, etc
SitComments: he has a very solid sit
StayComments: working on it; he understands the concept but we are working on duration
ComeOffLeashComments: he has an excellent recall
PillsComments: NA but I would imagine he will be fine
NailsComments: we cut his nails weekly
GeneralComments: This pup is smart and very sweet. Needs lots of physical and mental exercise. Rides well in car, uncrated, either in the front floor or back of wagon. Can play by himself. He shows good self-modulation for a pup his age as long as he is exercised. Food bowl manners are excellent even with another dog present. He has had some experience with parks, stores, parking lots (at his pace). So far, he is great. (Nordic is often with us, and I can see the pup taking good cues from Nordic)

HousemannersComments: Will sometimes take tissues from bathroom wastebasket.  Is also tempted by socks in the laundry room.
PlaybiteComments: He is still quite mouthy with me when we are playing, but is learning to settle quietly with mouth CLOSED.
RaidsGarbageComments: Stays out of kitchen garbage / is tempted by tissues from the bathroom waste can.  No longer raids the toilet paper.
JumpsComments: Need to work on greetings.  Calms fairly quickly.
WalkingComments: Still working on WWP
GetBusyComments: Only if he needs to "get busy"
ChaseComment: Recently chased a squirrel on the fence while out int the yard.  Would have chase after a fox on two separate occasions if had not been on leash.
NoiseComments: Sometimes startles.  Not afraid of the vacuum.
GeneralComments: Would like to ask about sudden startles to common noises or bugs, etc.  Is this age related?  Need to work on people greetings and higher levels of socializing.  He rides perfectly in the car.  Minimal barking or whining in the house or outside in the yard.  Very quiet in his crate.  Chooses appropriately from his toy box.  Does not disturb anything on the coffee table (candles, books, etc.)  Has a relatively high activity level.  Still plays a bit rough with other dogs, and mounts often.  Sometimes shows demanding behavior (staring, barking) when I am watching tv. Good appetite and moderate watering.  Hank is a complete pleasure.

HealthComments: Has had hot spots, last in January
ExerciseType: Walking, chasing tennis balls, playing with other dog
ChewingComments: Will counter surf and steal things which she chews up
LeftUnattendedComments: But if I leave the house she is in her crate
PlaybiteComments: When she plays hard she will bite me and my shoestrings
BarksExcessivelyComments: Will bark when playing with my other dog
CountersDoorsComments: She will counter surf if I am not in the room
JumpsComments: She will jump on me when she is excited
WalkingComments: Will pull on lead at beginning of walking until she settles down
ChaseComment: She will chase the cat to play and she will chase squirrel in the yard
StairsComments: But not good yet at staying with me
ComeOffLeashComments: Usually but can be stubborn when distracted
NailsComments: I can not do, she pulls away
GeneralComments: Kasha is a work in progress, but she is coming along. She seems to move at her own pace. She shows no fear of anything and loves all people and other dogs. She still has a lot of puppy in her and loves to play. When I can get her to focus she is very good.
DayInLife: I live in a rural area.Own my own home and live there alone with two pets. Most days of the week my schedule can be flexible since I sell real estate and a pup would be welcome in my office. I also work in a supermarket part time. My employer will allow me to bring a puppy to keep in a private area of the store where I spend a lot of my time.  I have a cat and a 14 year old male cocker spaniel who has always been very good with other dogs even though he has not spent any time with a young puppy.  I feel I have the time to provide a puppy with the love, training and experience it will need during it's young life to suceed in fullfilling it's final destiny. I fill this is a very worthy project and I feel very blessed with the opportunity to serve.  My biggest fear is probably the same as every other puppy raiser, giving up the pup when it is time for IFT, but I know the pup has a job to do and a greater calling to answer to.

HealthComments: Has had hot spots, last in January
ExerciseType: Walking, chasing tennis balls, playing with other dog
ChewingComments: Will counter surf and steal things which she chews up
LeftUnattendedComments: But if I leave the house she is in her crate
PlaybiteComments: When she plays hard she will bite me and my shoestrings
BarksExcessivelyComments: Will bark when playing with my other dog
CountersDoorsComments: She will counter surf if I am not in the room
JumpsComments: She will jump on me when she is excited
WalkingComments: Will pull on lead at beginning of walking until she settles down
ChaseComment: She will chase the cat to play and she will chase squirrel in the yard
StairsComments: But not good yet at staying with me
ComeOffLeashComments: Usually but can be stubborn when distracted
NailsComments: I can not do, she pulls away
GeneralComments: Kasha is a work in progress, but she is coming along. She seems to move at her own pace. She shows no fear of anything and loves all people and other dogs. She still has a lot of puppy in her and loves to play. When I can get her to focus she is very good.

StealFoodComments: See above - will sniff plates on end tables or laps.
BarksExcessivelyComments: She will bark when excited or bored. working on longer settles.
CountersDoorsComments: Does not counter surf. Much better about closed doors with work.
JumpsComments: Improving people greetings but unpredictable.
FriendlyWAnimalsComments: Gradually learning to leave our cat alone. Great with house dogs.
WalkingComments: Variable. Sometimes fantastic. When very revved up she will pull hard and sniff a lot.
EliminateRouteComments: Most of the time
ChaseComment: Will chase cat if she moves. Mina is good if I see the squirrel/bird/deer etc first and Use Skills to Direct. But if we're both surprised she will bark loudly and chase.
StayComments: Getting better with distractions (cat, me moving around etc) but working on duration
ComeOffLeashComments: Not during play dates!
PillsComments: She had pills for diarrhea on arrival; since then have only given heartworm.
GeneralComments: We are just starting to work on jacketed outings. We have gone "shopping" in several local locations (post office, library, drug store) during early times when distractions are low. She is doing well.  Mina has difficulty in class, I think primarily due the close proximity of people/dogs. Her connection to me is very fractured and she tends to lunge toward other dogs and people. I bring high value treats and take her out for play breaks, but the intensity is a lot for her.  Her behavior upon seeing other dogs when we're out is dependent on the distance and the behavior of the other dog. She wants badly to greet and sniff, but if they get too close she barks loudly and continuously. If we can approach very gradually, with lots of time to settle between steps forward and lots of rewards for checkins, she can sometimes be successful. But if the other dog barks, she escalates immediately to red zone.  She is a very good girl at home most of the time, especially if she gets daily mental and physical exercise. She is smart, seems to like to please, and responds well to praise.

DayInLife: Anne Weber    My husband, Garry, and I live in a ranch house on 1 acre of land in a rural section of Glen Arm, surrounded by farmland and horse stables. Most of our neighbors have dogs and cats as pets. Joppa Road is only 2 miles away, so we can quickly reach suburban and urban areas to provide the puppy with a variety of experiences. We have 3 grown sons who visit occasionally. I work from home as a consultant (computer work) with a completely flexible schedule, so working with the puppy throughout the day (and night!) will not pose a problem for me. I occasionally travel for my work, 1-2 times a year for a few days each time. Garry works at Union Memorial Hospital from 7 am to 4 pm on weekdays. We vacation for a week at a time perhaps once or twice a year. We have 2 adult dogs, 8-year-old Bear and 6-year-old Cocoa, who are Lab mutts. The dogs are trained to an electric fence around our property. We have installed a small fenced-in area (about 20 ft. square) that leads off one of the back doors of our house, so the adult dogs can play outside with the puppy safely (under supervision, of course!) before he is old enough to be trained on the electric fence. We have 4 adult cats who are used to the dogs. We usually walk the dogs twice a day for 1-1.5 miles each time. I will be able to walk the puppy separately until he is old enough to be walked with the other dogs.

HealthComments: No issues thus far.
StoolComments: Generally - occasional looser stool
ExerciseType: 2-3 mile walk per day, playing with other dogs
CrateQuietComments: Very good in crate.  Slight whining if she is crated too much during the day with minimal exercise
KennelCommandComments: Flies towards her kennel in hopes of receiving food reward after going into kennel.
ChewingComments: Generally good - may pull strings/pieces off of toys
HousemannersComments: Generally good - still supervised when not in crate, always keep her in same room as me.  Has jumped up on shorter tables (side table, coffee table) in areas other than at home to check out what is on them
LeftUnattendedComments: Due to her age, I do not leave her unattended at home.  Has been left uncrated in my office for short durations (i.e. when I go to the bathroom) - has been generally good but did pull a storage box across my office
EliminationHouseComments: No accidents inside house - occasionally has accident outside on leash but that's handler error
PlaybiteComments: Only very rarely - easily redirected
StealFoodComments: Not given the opportunity to steal human or other dogs food - probably would if given opportunity
OnFurnitureComments: Will occasionally put front paws up on chair/couch
BarksExcessivelyComments: None
RaidsGarbageComments: Sticks her nose inside garbages - generally good name response away from them
CountersDoorsComments: So far, no issues
JumpsComments: Karo has difficulty in this area - social and wants to meet everyone, typically by jumping on them especially if they are excited to greet her.  Especially difficult with children - she lunges towards them before they get within 5 feet of her.
FriendlyWAnimalsComments: Friendly with my pet dogs and cat.  Can play roughly by biting ears, neck, legs, etc - has to be reminded frequently to play with a toy
KidsComments: Not much exposure to kids but when she sees them in public, she wants to jump on them
StrangerComments: Friendly but tends to jump - it's a work in progress
WalkingComments: Overall good - in new locations she may need time to just hang out and watch things before she can walk politely on leash
EliminateRouteComments: If she does, it's handler error.  Very rarely occurs.
ChaseComment: Have not had an opportunity to observe this but I think she would - things that move get her attention and can get her mildly excited.
TrafficComments: Generally okay but loud noises cause her to startle - generally good recovery afterwards.
NoiseComments: Appears to be noise sensitive, especially in new situations.
StairsComments: Bunny hops on the way down
StayComments: Have not taught her this yet
ComeOnLeashComments: Work in progress
ComeOffLeashComments: Work in progress - depends on the distraction
PillsComments: Easily eats her heartworm pill
EarsComments: Done once - only mild squirming
NailsComments: I cut her nails once per week
GeneralComments: Overall Karo is doing well.  She can be on her own agenda at times. She patterns things very quickly which can make working with her difficult at times. She needs some time in new environments to process but has handled all settings I've taken her too pretty well, remaining in the Think & Learn Zone. Biggest things I've noticed with her is sensitivity to noise (especially sudden, loud noises that occur in new situations) and some reactions to novel objects.  With both issues, she tends to recovery fairly quickly and is better upon repeat exposure.  Play breaks really seem to help her when out socializing.

HealthComments: conjunctivitis on and off
ChewingComments: stole items from my bag, destroyed a dvd and 2 books
HousemannersComments: desk and counter surfing
LeftUnattendedComments: see #38 and #40, will get into recycling or garbage, if those are not available will surf for papers on my desk at work and devour them
PlaybiteComments: nips my arm for attention when wants to play
BarksExcessivelyComments: barking for attention has improved quite a lot, but still does this a few times a week, usually in the evening
RaidsGarbageComments: not trust worthy, however has learned to stay away from the cat's litter box
CountersDoorsComments: counter surfs, has stolen keys, coasters and papers, not tempted by food though
JumpsComments: improving, likely to jump during people greetings when very excited
StairsComments: improving, hugs the wall, concerned by railing along the wall - i.e. above his head - will hug wall opposite from railing
NailsComments: allows feet to be handled, toes played with, clippers touching foot, but panics when hold foot and clip nail; have had success getting nails clipped by vet tech with a good holder plus me to distract him, he recovers immediately
GeneralComments: Leon is jealous of people interacting with me and will vie for my attention. He inserts himself between the other person and me, paws me, nudges, etc. On occasion he still barks at me for attention which is, at times, a legitimate signal that he needs to get busy. Other times it is purely seeking attention when my focus is elsewhere - like busy working at my desk.   He loves lap time, body handling and can be easily settled at home. He does not like body handling when he is out on a public exposure, at class or in other stressful environments. In these situations he will decompress if given opportunities for chewing or sniffing. His tolerance for public outings is improving slowly. A few minutes in a brand new place is still all he can handle before he's overwhelmed. When stressed his movements become faster and he is not able to maintain his focus or stay in a position without breaking. Gets stress dandruff, very heavy at times.  He's laying on my feet right now. Leon is a love bug who likes a lot of physical contact.

FoodType: Iams low residue and Iams smart puppy
StoolComments: very, very, very slowly mixing Iams smart puppy with low residue food. If we proceed too fast (1/8 cup puppy food) he has diarrhea.  We are almost at the 1/8 cup after starting with 10 kibbles per meal
ExerciseType: chases toy on tennis court every day. 3x daily walks. Food puzzle toy every morning
ExericeAmount: tennis court: approx 20-30 min walks: 10-20 minutes puzzle toy: 5-10 minutes
CrateQuietComments: at night-no problem.  if he is calm-no problem. but if he is not relaxed enough he will bark for about 5 minutes (probably less but it feels like 5)
KennelCommandComments: doesn't recognize the word but understands what we want when gesturing
ChewingComments: no longer chews furniture.  he will take shoes but doesn't chew them like a toy.  Loves outside sticks
HousemannersComments: Last week I would have said wonderful.  This week he has discovered jumping on counters when he knows his dog food is up there.  He does respond to us when we tell him, "off."
LeftUnattendedComments: Would prefer not to be left unattended.  He follows Mitch or me throughout the house.  If food is soaking on counter he will stay in the kitchen until we come back.  He will sleep on his dog bed while I'm in another room.  I guess basically it depends on his mood.
PlaybiteComments: When he is over tired he will play bite but has been doing this less. He grabs at tug toy sometimes at the end with our hand
StealFoodComments: He hasn't been given the opportunity....but I think he would try...just to test his bounderies
OnFurnitureComments: He has a dog bed (couch) and stays off the couches.  He does try to get on our laps but gently putting his front legs on us. We tell him off and put his feet on the ground.
BarksExcessivelyComments: He barks when he is ignored during adult conversation (settle).  We are working on this.  He barks when he is over tired and needs a rest.
RaidsGarbageComments: Does not have access but after looking at this question I may place a trash can on floor of bathroom with a couple of tissues so he learns what not to do.
CountersDoorsComments: see qs 39-40 regarding kitchen counters. Has never jumped on a door.
JumpsComments: Good with kids but may jump on hyper child. Will jump on people when they lower themselves to meet him.
FriendlyWAnimalsComments: When meeting goats and chickens he was interested but not overly excited.  Very excited to meet dogs but will calm down when walking with other dogs.
KidsComments: Will jump on hyper children but is very friendly with kids overall.
GetBusyComments: On command?  He knows his "get busy" areas.  On our trip to UConn, I made sure he could get busy every 2 hours and I say the words, but I don't think he is doing it on command.
ChaseComment: He did want to chase a friend's outdoor rabbit.  He left the indoor rabbit alone.  Still waiting for the chipmunks to run around outside.
TrafficComments: He is confident in traffic.  He does show interest in trucks and some cars but does not chase them or is afraid.  Walks well in crosswalks and parking lots.  Does well on sidewalks with occasional stops to watch vehicles but does then check in.
NoiseComments: We haven't been around loud noises like guns but he seems to do well in noisy environments.
StairsComments: Does not seem to have an issue
DownComments: Does better when he knows I have food in my hand.  He is getting better at the command without food.  I must lower my hand below his head to get the point.
StayComments: Getting much better at this.  Originally does not want me out of his site, but now can handle it for a minute or so.
GeneralComments: Keegan is an exceptionally bright dog.  He has been improving in many areas.  The hardest thing for him right now is to "settle."  He barks for attention/training treats.  We are working on this and he is showing some improvement. He now "loads" into car without lures!  We remove his dog bed during the day so he is learning to be comfortable in crate.
DayInLife: Laura-My schedule is very flexible. When I work, it is mostly from home with a laptop.  I do, once a week, occasionally more, occasionally less work at CT US&R headquarters in Hartford.  We have US&R dogs on our team.  Also some of the State Troopers have offices in the building and they have GEB trained dogs. The puppy will be warmly welcomed at the office.  I have a large, secure indoor train/play space available for the puppy and me.  Also a crate will be on site next to my desk for the puppy.  During the week we live in a condo with safe, quiet streets.  We live in a "cluster" with neighbors very close.  We have a golden retriever and maltese adult dogs in the cluster, and many dogs in the condo complex. We also have a fenced in tennis court where the puppy and I can train/play (after the snow melts).  On the weekends we live in a house with stairs.  The dead end road is quiet and we have woods with trails next to the property.  This switching of residences will end in mid-June when we will permanently leave the condo.    Mitch-Will do the early, early morning walks and the last walk in the evening. He will have a 1.5 hour weekday, daily commute. He will work at home one day during the week (we're thinking Tuesday).  His office hours are 10 am-6 pm. His weekend schedule is flexible.  The puppy is welcome to be with Mitch at the office.  The company is very understanding and supportive and will allow Mitch the time he needs to tend to the puppy's needs.    Kyle-High School senior.  Has the least flexible schedule.  Kyle attends high school from 7:10 am -2:05 pm.  He works after school at IBM until 5 pm-ish.  If, need be, Kyle can be home with the puppy after school until 3 pm. Kyle is also taking a 4 hour college course on Tuesday nights which unfortunately is a direct conflict with the GEB class.  On Tuesdays, Kyle does not work and is home from 2:30 pm to 5:00 pm.  In August Kyle will be leaving to attend Syracuse University.

GeneralComments: SOME CONCERNS/THINGS TO WORK ON: - TAKING PERSONAL SPACE (BODY RUBBING, PAWING AT FEET, PUSHING THROUGH LEGS, NOSE IN CROTCH - WHEN PEOPLE ARE SITTING SHE TRIES TO CLIMB UP THE FRONT OF THEM OR TRIES TO PUT TOY/BONE IN PERSON'S MOUTH -PUSHING DOGS AROUND HOUSE AND AWAY FROM US WHEN GETTING ATTENTION - PUSHING RUBEN A BIT TOO (A DANGEROUS THING TO DO....) BY EXCESSIVE SNIFFING, BODY RUBBING, ETC. -PUP PLAY- LOOKING FOR SUGGESTIONS ON HOW TO HANDLE TENSION I'M SEEING IN HER. SHE IS ALSO STILL "CORRECTING" YOUNG PUPS FOR MISBEHAVIOR BY PINNING PUPPY, GROWLING, TEETH ON PUP- IT'S VERY QUICK, MATTER OF FACT, AND SHE RECOVERS VERY QUICKLY- GOES BACK TO PUP TO TRY AND GET THEM TO PLAY - I'M SEEING A LITTLE MORE ACTIVATION IN HER LATELY TOO THAT WE'RE WORKING THROUGH DESPITE THESE FEW CONCERNS/ THINGS TO WORK ON, SHE IS A VERY PLEASANT PUP- VERY SMART, WILLING TO PLEASE, AND GOOD COMPANION

HousemannersComments: RECENTLY HAS BEEN PUSHING BOUNDARIES- OCCASIONALLY GETTING ON FURNITURE, TESTING OPEN GARBAGE CANS, ETC.
PlaybiteComments: STILL MOUTHS PEOPLE WHEN EXCITED AND UPON GREETING- STILL WORKING ON GREETING WITH TOY
OnFurnitureComments: TESTING LATELY- HAVE FOUND ON BED A COUPLE OF TIMES AND COUCH UPON PLAYING WITH KAREN
BarksExcessivelyComments: OCCASIONALLY WILL ALERT BARK, OCCASIONALLY WILL "SCREAM" WHEN SUPER EXCITED (IE. FEEDING TIME AND I ASK HER TO DO A NEW BEHAVIOR BEFORE RELEASING HER)
RaidsGarbageComments: TESTING OPEN GARBAGE IN OFFICE LATELY
JumpsComments: GOOD ABOUT NOT JUMPING ON GREETING BUT HAS BEEN PUSHING PERSONAL BOUNDARIES WITH PEOPLE CROUCHING/SITTING
FriendlyWAnimalsComments: SEEING SOME TENSION DURING PLAY WITH OTHER DOGS- MOSTLY IF OTHER DOGS ARE PUSHY AND RUDE, SEEING TENSION AND SOME OBSESSIVENESS WITH TOYS (GRABBING, SHAKING OF TOYS, HARD EYE CONTACT, TENSE BODY, VOCALIZATION)
KidsComments: APPROPRIATE AND MOSTLY CALM AROUND THEM- NEED MORE EXPOSURE
GetBusyComments: BEST GET BUSIER EVER- EVEN RETURNS TO HEEL POSITION AND SIT/STAND STAYS WHILE YOU PICK IT UP!!
ChaseComment: GOOD FOR THE MOST PART- OCCASIONALLY WILL CHASE CAT, HAVEN'T SEEN OVER ENTHUSIASM WITH CRITTERS OUTSIDE
TrafficComments: STILL A LITTLE UNCERTAIN WITH TRAFFIC GOING IN SAME DIRECTION/ LOUD TRAFFIC COMING UP BEHIND HER
NoiseComments: GOOD FOR THE MOST PART- HAVE BEEN OBSERVING SOME NEW UNCERTAINTY WITH SOME SOUNDS AND SIGHTS- NOT SURE WHY???
StayComments: WORKING WITH SOME OUT OF SIGHT STAYS
ComeOnLeashComments: GOOD FOR MOST PART- NEEDS WORK WITH DISTRACTIONS
ComeOffLeashComments: GOOD FOR MOST PART- NEEDS WORK WITH DISTRACTIONS
EarsComments: GOOD FOR MOST PART, BUT SOMETIMES TURNS HEAD AWAY OR WALKS AWAY IF SHE SEE'S BOTTLE- DOES MUCH BETTER IF YOU DO "CLOSE" FIRST
NailsComments: VERY GOOD- DON'T SEE ANY UNCERTAINTY AND SHE NOW JUMPS UP ON THE GROOMING TABLE ALL BY HER SELF
GeneralComments: SOME CONCERNS/THINGS TO WORK ON: - TAKING PERSONAL SPACE (BODY RUBBING, PAWING AT FEET, PUSHING THROUGH LEGS, NOSE IN CROTCH - WHEN PEOPLE ARE SITTING SHE TRIES TO CLIMB UP THE FRONT OF THEM OR TRIES TO PUT TOY/BONE IN PERSON'S MOUTH -PUSHING DOGS AROUND HOUSE AND AWAY FROM US WHEN GETTING ATTENTION - PUSHING RUBEN A BIT TOO (A DANGEROUS THING TO DO....) BY EXCESSIVE SNIFFING, BODY RUBBING, ETC. -PUP PLAY- LOOKING FOR SUGGESTIONS ON HOW TO HANDLE TENSION I'M SEEING IN HER. SHE IS ALSO STILL "CORRECTING" YOUNG PUPS FOR MISBEHAVIOR BY PINNING PUPPY, GROWLING, TEETH ON PUP- IT'S VERY QUICK, MATTER OF FACT, AND SHE RECOVERS VERY QUICKLY- GOES BACK TO PUP TO TRY AND GET THEM TO PLAY - I'M SEEING A LITTLE MORE ACTIVATION IN HER LATELY TOO THAT WE'RE WORKING THROUGH DESPITE THESE FEW CONCERNS/ THINGS TO WORK ON, SHE IS A VERY PLEASANT PUP- VERY SMART, WILLING TO PLEASE, AND GOOD COMPANION

GeneralComments: Kojak has definite guarding issues- He exhibited this first day when I picked him up from Jodi with the other GEB puppies.  Even with the water bowl.  We are working on this everyday with him and my pet dog.  Kojak also has trouble playing nicely with dogs other than GSD Rodeo- He is very rough with his mouth and does not want to play TOY.   Kojak also really changes personality when wearing anything- bandana- jacket-tshirt etc- appears to be the BEST dog ever but is very unlike himself.  NO sniffing no blowing leaf chasing- only calmly sitting by my side.  We are working on that daily in familiar places to warm him up to the idea.   Odd note - Kojak is extremely ticklish- for lack of a better term- His leg goes when you scratch his jaw line and his back has 2 spots and his stomach and his front feet- when chewing an itch on his paws- his back leg goes nuts.

HealthComments: We've had him for 2 months and he has had diarrhea and an ear infection in that time. The diarrhea went away when we switch from Iams to Purina. The ear infection was mild and has cleared up fine.
StoolComments: Better now; bad a month ago.
HousemannersComments: He will countersurf/couchsurf if he feels he's being ignored. Would also get into the trash consistently for the first few weeks; we got different cans with lids which has stopped that problem.
LeftUnattendedComments: In a crate is fine. When not crated, he will sometimes wait patiently and sometimes whine. We've never left him too long not in a crate b/c he'll steal things when we're with him, so we don't want to push it.
StealFoodComments: Countersurfing -- sometimes he'll go for his own food and sometimes for ours.
OnFurnitureComments: Mostly good unless he's excited or he's using the couch to get to the TV remote.
BarksExcessivelyComments: This has improved; he barked much more when he first arrived.
RaidsGarbageComments: Only b/c he can't open the lid
CountersDoorsComments: see above
JumpsComments: Greetings are hard and he'll sometimes jump; this is improving but he is not consistent yet.
FriendlyWAnimalsComments: Too friendly. Wants to lick them all to death.
KidsComments: We haven't seen him with enough kids to judge.
StrangerComments: Very friendly; gets excited but this is improving.
WalkingComments: We don't have to use his harness anymore; he's doing much better and checks in regularly.
GetBusyComments: He will go when he feels like it. Command doesn't seem to register.
EliminateRouteComments: Even after we've given him plenty of time and opportunity in our yard he will almost always eliminate on the walk.
ChaseComment: Depends on distance. Squirrels/birds outside are fine. Dogs far away are fine. Cats are not fine -- he wants to chase and play with them (it is not aggressive).
TrafficComments: Busy parking lots are too much; general walking near moving cars is fine.
NoiseComments: He does react, but this seems to be interest instead of fear.
StayComments: He will stay in the right place but not necessarily in a sit or down.
ComeOffLeashComments: Depends on distractions, but is usually really good.
NailsComments: He does not like this at all.
GeneralComments: Meyer is really sweet but does have a lot of red flags. His bad habits include the poor potty manners and the countersurfing/stealing. I will say re: the countersurfing that we've made some progress in convincing him that we do not like it, plus we're better able to anticipate when it will happen to try and prevent it. He is clearly stealing things that we value, like the remote or our phones, or things he wants to eat or play with, like his toys that might be out of reach. He is extremely smart and tuned into us. He shadows us everywhere and is very responsive to our commands for the most part.

LeftUnattendedComments: Does not like to be left alone in the car. Will shred anything that she can get ahold of.  During one class where we left the dogs in the car and worked with one at a time, Candy managed to turn my lights on and off(twisting motion), lean on the horn and set off the panic alarm. She could see me and wanted to be where I was. Is mostly okay when wandering around the house. Occasionally gets into something that she shouldn't have (daughter's wastebasket, cookies, dirty plates)
EliminationHouseComments: Mostly okay, but have several scattered accidents lately. If she has another one will ask vet to have her checked for another UTI. It seems that after she plays really hard that she guzzles a lot of water. She may go to the door, but doesn't stay there or she goes to a different door where I don't have a bell and I don't realize that she is there. She is usually pretty desparate to go if she guzzled water.
StealFoodComments: Had a couple of instances a couple of months ago when she stole warm chocolate cookies from a cooling rack on a table and  licked some plates that were left on a table.  No issues since then.

When one rings the bell the other one shows up to go outside as well even if they don't need to get busy, but just want to check the air.

GeneralComments: We've noticed a lot of progress in Kameko's behavior over the past couple of months.  However, she needs to learn what the acceptable limits are when greeting new people and animals.  Her walking is pretty good but she needs to be less distracted by the scents she smells while outside.  We keep the kitchen gates closed most of the time.  We'd like to get to the point where we can give her a bit more freedom in the house without being worried that she'll chew on a piece of furniture.
DayInLife: I get up around 6 a.m. and leave for work at around 745.  My wife usually leaves for work a little after 8.  My kids, who are old enough to take an active part in the puppies training, get home from school at around 240pm.  This is Monday - Wednesday.  My wife works from home on Thursdays and I am home on Fridays.  We are generally home on the weekends other than attending youth soccer games or visiting friends.

DayInLife: I work a 5 hour shift at an elementary school that is 2 miles from my home.  We have two children, one in 3rd grade and one in 7th grade.  We live in a house with a fenced in yard and swimming pool in a cul de sac and in a quiet neighborhood.  Both boys take Taekwondo three nights a week.  I have asked their instructor if I could bring the dog to their classes and he said yes.  We usually have plenty of free time on the weekends enjoying the pool or playing at the park, beach or in our yard. We also enjoy museums and taking the boys to various children related events in the area. We have three older dogs.  Two of them are 7 years old and one is 6 years old.  They are used to having pups and dogs around since we have fostered over 50 dogs for the SPCA and a local rescue group. I love to run and enjoy going on walks with the boys.

GeneralComments: Georgette is a great dog. She is incredibly smart and loves to train. Her biggest issue by far is wanting to meet everyone on the street and jumping on people. I would LOVE to improve my strategies for dealing with this issue.

ExerciseType: walks, off leash in contained area, play with raiser's own dog
EliminationCrateComments: Keeps crate clean w/o poop or pee accident
CrateQuietComments: Happily enters crate; visits throughout the day; sleeps unitl about 5:00 or 5:30 AM; might whine if door locked and people around
KennelCommandComments: Loves her kennel
ChewingComments: At times tries to chew furniture or shoes but is easily redirected
HousemannersComments: She is generally well behavied but has started to put her paws on the couch. She is redirected when this occurs
LeftUnattendedComments: She isn't really left unattended out of her crate but we can go upstairs or down for short periods without anything happening
EliminationHouseComments: She is completely housetrained for poop; still has occasional pee accidents (those are generally our fault, though)
PlaybiteComments: I wouldn't call it biting but she definitely mouths. We are working on saying "out" with her when she trys to put our hands in her mouth. That seems to be working
StealFoodComments: Has never tried to steal food
OnFurnitureComments: Has started putting front paws on furniture but knows to get off and is easily redirected
BarksExcessivelyComments: I'm not exactly sure what this means but she has started to bark when she's hungry or when she wants something
RaidsGarbageComments: Never gotten into the gargabe
CountersDoorsComments: She has never jumped on the counter
JumpsComments: She jumps on everyone she meets unless actively restrained
FriendlyWAnimalsComments: LOVES all animals and people -- too much
KidsComments: LOVES kids
StrangerComments: We say that Georgette things "a stranger is just a friend you haven't met."
WalkingComments: She is generally excellent on a lead but needs to be distracted when people walk by
GetBusyComments: Definitely pees at "gets busy." Poops immediately if she has to go -- we still haven't worked out exactly when she needs to poop and when she doesn't
EliminateRouteComments: If she doesn't go at the outset of our walk, 9 times out of 10 she won't go at all
ChaseComment: Distracted by loud birds, bunnies and squirrels but tends not to chase them
TrafficComments: Is not scared of cars or loud trucks
NoiseComments: Generally excellent with ambient noises but did bark at the vacuum cleaner yesterday
StairsComments: Will walk on all exterior closed stairs. Refuses to walk up the stairs in our house (both carpeted and hardwood)
DownComments: She knows this command and will comply but doesn't like to do it on cold cement
StayComments: She's great at just a few paces but won't stay for too long if I leave her line of vision
EarsComments: Does't mind it but sometimes tries to mouth hands
NailsComments: Not thrilled but will do it when distracted with treats
GeneralComments: Georgette is a great dog. She is incredibly smart and loves to train. Her biggest issue by far is wanting to meet everyone on the street and jumping on people. I would LOVE to improve my strategies for dealing with this issue.

CrateQuietComments: Occasionally will cry when I leave him in the crate and he hears me leave the house. I have stood outside and waited him out before and he always stops after a minute. This is the only problem I have and he only does this occasionally.
LeftUnattendedComments: I never leave him unattended in the kitchen or bathroom, but he and Vincent often have access to my room and the living room when we are all hanging out at the house
OnFurnitureComments: Occasionally puts his feet on the couch when he gets extra silly or worked up during play time. He gets a time out to calm down when this happens.
BarksExcessivelyComments: Occasionally play barks. He gets a time out for this as well.
RaidsGarbageComments: Occasionally air scents toward the trash can. I ask him to "back" and "sit" when he does that.
JumpsComments: Does pretty well with this. If he is overexcited he sometimes will jump. I just ask him to sit when he does this, and don't touch him until he responds
StrangerComments: He is sometimes aloof with adults he doesn't know, but this is actually pretty helpful.
WalkingComments: Sometimes will pull when he is in a new environment
EliminateRouteComments: Sometimes he will eliminate if I let him check something out for too long.
ChaseComment: He is interested in birds and small animals, but never really has the chance to chase them.
TrafficComments: He has been doing so well with this! Totally unfazed by the big trucks in the city!
NoiseComments: He's been doing great with noises.
StairsComments: He is still sometimes hesitating at the bottom step and bolting up the top. We have been working on stairs a lot and also just working on helping him get comfortable with his body in general. He is making slow improvements. Gerald has suggested making sure he feels no collar pressure on the stairs so that is something I have implemented into our practice.
PillsComments: N/A He's never had any oral medications
EarsComments: He is accepting but wants to dip his head. We work on ear cleaning weakly and I touch his ears (inside and out) daily.

ExerciseType: playing with the frisbee, walking on the street, and our outings once a day
CrateQuietComments: gets excited when we get home and starts to whine and bark
BarksExcessivelyComments: barks at dogs and when he is very excited
NoiseComments: often responds with barking
DayInLife: In the summer when I first get my puppy, I like to get up semi early and get exercise. But at the same time I love to relax and sit back and take the time to think about my day. After I get up, like I said, I like to workout. Then I may read a book outside and eat lunch. I spend most of my days in the summer outside and with other people too. I do  not live on a main road, I live in a neighborhood that has a long street that is perfect for running, and I live right next to a beautiful park, that unfortunately, but to my benefit, no one uses. When school comes around I wake up at six fifteen and get ready for school, but I am totally willing to get up earlier to take my puppy out to get busy and go for a walk. When I am at school my mom will be letting the puppy out and feeding it it's lunch. When I get home I will play with the puppy more and take It out and for a walk. When basketball season starts, although I am not sure that I am going to be doing basketball, I am usually home at seven at night, but I wake up and would do the same routine with the puppy in the morning, my mom is home most of the day will take care of it when I am at basketball too. I have an older dog who has bad joints so if there is a puppy who does not jump excessively that would be wonderful for my 11 year old golden retriever. I know my family and I were thinking of a German shepherd but I am really into the thought of getting a lab.

HealthComments: Episodes of panosteitis, scuffing hind legs, grade 1 luxating patellas
CrateQuietComments: Can occasionally bark when there is high distraction or excitement
KennelCommandComments: She doesn't consistently go into the crate -- respectful disobedience. She knows how
ChewingComments: Has chewed a pen and pencil that had fallen on the floor. Used to get a sock from the laundry but has stopped that. She is learning those house manners and I see her improving all the time
HousemannersComments: Doing very well, no counter surfing, stays off couches and chairs etc.
LeftUnattendedComments: For prolonged time I put her in a crate but that is because she has been with me for a short time and we are getting to know each other and the rules
EliminationHouseComments: A few missed training opportunities the first few weeks but it is better. She doesn't come to give me the signal but will go sit by the door which doesn't help me if I am preoccupied with something else. She is very remorseful when she has had an accident so I know that she will get this figured up.
StealFoodComments: She has had plenty of opportunity too!
CountersDoorsComments: She stays off counters. But if I close her out of a room, she whines and jumps up on the door. We are working on that and it is getting better.
JumpsComments: She will jump on new people and even me when she is excited.
KidsComments: I haven't seen her around children yet but I think she would be fine.
TrafficComments: We walked along Main Street in old saybrook and seemed pretty good to me
StayComments: She is building patience
ComeOnLeashComments: Good for shorter distances and not too much distraction but improving weekly
ComeOffLeashComments: Getting more and more reliable. Loses it with dog distraction like Leslie
PillsComments: Haven't had to do it.
EarsComments: Haven't done it but she tolerates body handling well
NailsComments: She isn't wild about it but is improving
GeneralComments: She is a sweet dog and is attaching stronger and stronger to me each week. She really took a while to develop a relationship to me. Barb has bonded heavily with Leslie and has learned quickly from her. I can see her being a good candidate as a guide except for her orthopedic issues which will be evaluated April 18.

CrateQuietComments: Whines in the morning.
LeftUnattendedComments: Last time we had a work schedule change, he chewed on a chair. Since then he hasn't been left alone.
PlaybiteComments: Nips at times when over stimulated.
JumpsComments: Some familiar people are difficult.
WalkingComments: At times goes for leaves.

StoolComments: After changing to Purina she is fine
ExericeAmount: 30 min walks/2 day outside play at lunch and after dinner
EliminationCrateComments: had some issues initially but that is gone
KennelCommandComments: sometimes
ChewingComments: she is a puppy ....
HousemannersComments: scavanger ...
LeftUnattendedComments: she get's into things
EliminationHouseComments: sometimes she does go inside - never marks she needs to go
PlaybiteComments: yes esp the kids
StealFoodComments: she tries
OnFurnitureComments: most of the time
BarksExcessivelyComments: she barks at our other dogs when she want to play
FriendlyWAnimalsComments: learning to get along with cat
KidsComments: she is still biting/playing
EliminateRouteComments: once or twice it has happend
ChaseComment: chases cat but is starting to calm down
StayComments: just learning
ComeOnLeashComments: most of the time depends on distractions
DayInLife: We live in a house with a fenced in yard.  I have two kids ages 10 and 7. They have grown up with dogs. We currently have two fixed males. Tigger, discharged guide dog, and Flynn a rescue mix Belgian Shepard type. Both are very friendly and like each other very much and the kids love them. I also have a cat that both dogs basically ignores. She does her own thing.    My husband works from home and is the primary caretaker of our two dogs. Since I work in an office away from home I tend to take them on hikes and walks on the weekends.  We let the dogs out initially in the am after their first meal in the fenced in yard. My husband then takes them out for a walk around the neighborhood (1 mile walk) before work. During the day since my husband is home they can go out in the fenced in yard as they please. In the evening it is dinner, homework, playtime or activities for all. For the dog we take them on an evening walk.    With a puppy we realize we have to change things up. I will take care of the puppy in the morning with feeding, getting busy and walk. During the day the puppy will be with my husband outside the crate if he can monitor otherwise in crate with regular potty breaks. During the evening I will have the puppy follow me for socialization and a final walk at night.

LeftUnattendedComments: Not if the other dogs are loose - loves to play, could leave for 5 minutes
StealFoodComments: Has not been in a position to steal food
KidsComments: Don't know has not been around children
ChaseComment: Have not seen him

ExerciseType: plays with my other dogs, ball, walks at the rec
ExericeAmount: Plays a total of 2 hrs throughout day with other dogs, 20 min with ball, 1hr rec
ChewingComments: chewed the corner of the wooden gate and the corner of the throw rug in kithen
HousemannersComments: Still tries to jump up when preparing her food but improving
OnFurnitureComments: Tries to put front paws on when I'm sitting there
BarksExcessivelyComments: Does bark at other dogs but much better
CountersDoorsComments: Only tries when preparing her food
JumpsComments: Improving
ChaseComment: Sometimes chases the cat
ComeOffLeashComments: Much improvement
DayInLife: My schedule is very flexible. I don't work, I walk 3 to 4 miles a day with Iola who is going to going to be retired shortly. I also have her daughter Scarlett who was released from training. For some reason I seem to raise high energy dogs. Scarlett was the class busy body and had to know what everyone was doing. When I came back to GEB 4 1/2 years ago as a foster, they must have said here's the sucker, let's give her Iola. (She wasn't just high energy, she was a lunatic which I say lovingly!!) What I'm interested in doing right now is starting puppies that don't have raisers right away, especially the gsd's

HealthComments: persistent limp on right front
LeftUnattendedComments: for brief periods, up to an hour or two.
PlaybiteComments: when excited and greeting, esp. children
OnFurnitureComments: will sneak on a chair that our pet dog is allowed on
CountersDoorsComments: jumps on back patio door to be let in if I don't response to first bark or nose bump
JumpsComments: jumps on new people and young children, working on appropriate greetings
KidsComments: attracted to children but overly excited, jumps, mouthy
StrangerComments: friendly but overly excited at times
WalkingComments: tends to pull at first on walks but quickly settles
ChaseComment: will run a squirrel to the back fence but breaks off chase readily, good with rabbits, squirrels and geese on campus walks at work.
ComeOffLeashComments: usually, sometimes wants to stay outside in yard longer.
GeneralComments: His limp is a major concern.  Lacks some self-modulation when greeting new people.  Has a hard time being calm around kids, their energy levels, rapid movements and noise tend to excite him.   I have him watch my grandson play behind a baby gate.  Working on calm, controlled greetings and exposure to small children.

ExerciseType: Walks, tug of war, fetch, Keeper in the middle
WalkingComments: Still working on pulling
EliminateRouteComments: Eliminates periodically without being released
GeneralComments: Keeper is extremely intelligent, confident, and friendly.  When we have issues it is usually because he is either interested in something (or more often, someone) or just needs to burn off energy.
DayInLife: OK, I'll try to get as much pertinent detail in here as I can without having it get boring on you.  Hope it works!      I'll start by saying that a lifestyle change is a definite possibility in the foreseeable future.  I am currently out of work and seeking employment.  I am a finance professional, which in this case means a couple things.  1. It may still be a while before I can get back to work.   2. Any work that I find would likely be in NYC, or southern CT, resulting in a commuting lifestyle.    3. The area of finance that I am in typically does not require really excessive hours except in unusual circumstances, so while a new job would mark a change in lifestyle for both me and a pup, it shouldn't be a change that prevented me from providing the proper care, enrichment, and training that the pups need.     In any case, all of that is speculative.  Right now, my lifestyle consists primarily of my ongoing job search and a variety of hobbies.  On a typical day, I will spend up to several hours searching for a job, half an hour working out at home, then add in some time spent on anything from trying to improve my Egyptian Arabic, dancing tango, or, weather and company depending, fly fishing, or squash.  This is aside from visits with friends and family.  As things stand, my entire schedule is rather flexible and my weekends differ little from my weekdays.      I live alone on the first floor of a two family house and have sole use of the basement as well.  The property includes a pretty generous back yard for outside play as well.  I am 31 and physically fit, so the physical aspect of working with a puppy (small or large) does not present a concern.   I do have a six year old cat, who has had some exposure to dogs and sort of likes to play with them unless they get too close or too aggressive.  He's never had a dog stay in the house for more than a month or so at a time.  I have a very close knit family, so multiple family members are very close by (and several are neighbors), in addition to my girlfriend who is following along with the GEB curriculum and policies and wants to be involved in helping out.   There are multiple dogs nearby in the family, all small, but also all very poor socialization, house manners, and "people skills".  The main things I want to make sure that GEB is able to work with me to get right are: socializing with other dogs (should the puppy be exposed to the poor untrained above mentioned dogs or avoid them to prevent being peer pressured into poor behavior?) and puppy proofing the house, in particular the basement (where the cat's litter is.)  Otherwise, the potential lifestyle change of a new job is the only item that could present a challenge.  I'm not certain what other information would be helpful for you, but would be very happy to discuss anything else you might like.    Oh, and question 4, regarding class schedules...  I didn't see the precise information on this, but I had been told six months of weekly and the remainder every other week.  Either way is fine as more training is better, in my mind.      P.S.    If GEB has a means of accomplishing the lottery ticket training mentioned in question 6, it could provide a great source of funding for the program as well as a nice bonus for puppy raisers during the training process!

FoodType: evangers fish and sweet pot until July 1
HealthComments: possible allergies/ intermittent soft stool
StoolComments: It is not reliably firm. maybe 1/2 time
CrateQuietComments: Sometimes in the am, she will whine or bark once before I get her out.
HousemannersComments: She had bad house manners until she went through her heat cycle in May and my previous dog was released and came home. I'm not sure which was the catalyst but she's been much improved since then.
LeftUnattendedComments: I wouldn't trust her for extended periods but she seems good for 30 minutes or so when I am outside doing something.
StealFoodComments: I think she would steal food if the opportunity arose.
OnFurnitureComments: She will still put her front feet on the couch if she is very excited and wants to see someone.
BarksExcessivelyComments: She will sometimes bark when she sees a dog when we are out. Just once or twice.
RaidsGarbageComments: Don't trust her
CountersDoorsComments: I have not seen her jump up on the counter since the end of May. She no longer grabs papers or pieces of clothing that are close to her level as she runs by.
FriendlyWAnimalsComments: Too interested in cats and small animals (rabbits).
GetBusyComments: will relieve on grass or rocks or dirt. Not good on pavement
ChaseComment: I think she would if there were animals to chase. I clear the yard of bunnies before she goes out.

HealthComments: She has been itching quite a bit the past few weeks and I've noticed increased shedding and hair loss on the back of her legs. I'm wondering if I should try a different food.
ExerciseType: Walks on a long line and fetch, plus outings walking in a park, sidewalks,strip mall, etc.
ExericeAmount: 20-30 minutes at home plus an hour outing
CrateQuietComments: Generally good, will whine if I'm in sight but quiets quickly
BarksExcessivelyComments: So far so good, occasionally she may bark under her breath at a noise or something she sees.
CountersDoorsComments: Used to jump on door or window sill if she wants to see something outside but hasn't done this in a month or two.
JumpsComments: Will jump on family members when they first come home if given the opportunity and will sometimes jump during a people greeting if the person is very excited.
FriendlyWAnimalsComments: Cats are a continual work in progress. Can stay settled when a cat walks by if she's in the right state of mind. If she busy and moving around the house she will follow and pester the cats.
KidsComments: Can get excited at times, mainly with the toddler my mom babysits.
WalkingComments: Very dependent upon the level of distraction. Can walk well in low key places like a quiet store or plaza. Needs a lot of time to check things out and can quickly lunge in busier settings.
ChaseComment: She will chase the cats if they run past her and are teasing. She can stay put and just watch if she's in the right state of mind and connected to me.
TrafficComments: Slowly but surely she's getting more confident.
NoiseComments: Will be frighten if she's in the process of checking something out or already unsure, such as hearing a loud motor cycle in a traffic situation where she's not at her normal confidence level.
StairsComments: Has gotten much better with stairs, mainly working on refining them, will sometimes skip the last step.
SitComments: It can take some time for her to respond, especially in high distraction
StayComments: She has a good foundation but we need to work on it more, I don't always take the time to practice it.
EarsComments: Usually very good and has gotten much better, every once and a while is not a fan of having them cleaned but will tolerate.

HealthComments: Healthiest GSD GEB has ever produced
StoolComments: poops like a champ.  never had any constipation or diahrrea
EliminationCrateComments: Oksana will periodically clean her crate out.  So she will pull her bedding out of her crate.  Don't know if it is because she wants it out, or because she wants to cuddle with the matts in other parts of the house.
CrateQuietComments: Overall she does fairly well.  BUT if you put her away when she is high energy or something is going on in the house she wants to be part of she will let you know.  She also sometimes will mouth off at you when its time to come out.
KennelCommandComments: loves to go into her crate
ChewingComments: For the most part she is good.  Sometimes she picks up the wrong thing, but she redirects fairly well.
LeftUnattendedComments: Unknown.  Have left for short 5 minute increments to get mail etc and its been fine.
EliminationHouseComments: unless you make her wait longer than she physically can
PlaybiteComments: When excited she play bites.  She will also snap/bark at you if you are correcting her and she doesn't like it.  Restraints when she is high energy (and restraint could mean holding collar or trying to make her down) could be met by teeth as well.
StealFoodComments: Hasn't yet, but I don't really trust her.
OnFurnitureComments: She wants to be up and cuddling.  She tries to crawl into our laps.  Will bound onto furniture when she is doing puppy zoomies.  Frequently tries to get on the bed.
BarksExcessivelyComments: Barking is better, but still too much.  Barks at people/dogs outside our house.  Barks at starnge noises.  Barks when driving over bridges....
RaidsGarbageComments: most the time fine
CountersDoorsComments: will counter surf if she gets the chance.
JumpsComments: lots and lots of jumping if she is activated.
FriendlyWAnimalsComments: She is friendly, but she will bark and have hackles up when she sees a strange dog.
KidsComments: Overly friendly.  If she is excited she jumps on them and scares them.  Between that and the play biting we haven't let her interact with children that much on her terms.  Its mostly been (forced) downs and the child comes to her and we manage her.
StrangerComments: She is fantastic with people.  So long as she isn't super excited (which tends to be an at-home issue) she is absolutely golden.
WalkingComments: The first bit of the walk she is PULLING.  then she calms down and walks very nicely.
GetBusyComments: best ever.
EliminateRouteComments: some peeing
ChaseComment: given the chance she would
TrafficComments: 2+.  This is improving.  She used to be a 1, so this is better!!
NoiseComments: Loud noises (jets etc) no problem.  vibrations/hums seem to unnerve her. I think that is part of her car issue
StairsComments: other than one weird incident that we think had more to do with a humming noise than the stairs, she is very good on stairs.
SitComments: except when very activated
StayComments: fairly good. duration is what is expected for a 6 mo old with her issues, but would like it better.
ComeOnLeashComments: as long as she isn't focused on something else, then she can't hear you.
ComeOffLeashComments: Depends on if something else is more important
PillsComments: N/A haven't pilled her.  But my guess is above.
EarsComments: she tolerates it, but doesn't like it.
NailsComments: doesn't like having her paws held.
GeneralComments: When "working" Oksana does very well.  People can pretty much walk right over top of her and she will just watch them.  She is very, very alert and struggles to stay settled so we have taken her to church sunday school and coffee shops (both places where we can get up and move around/leave easily).  She stays fairly attentive to me, but wants to be entertained.  I generally bring a chew/bone with me so that she can focus on that and chew out any anxieties that she has.   Car riding is MUCH improved.  She recently starting loading on her own without treats, tori or us to lure her in.  I still heavily treat her with a carrot or a nice chew in the car.  Yesterday she traveled all the way to Cape Charles (1 hour) without any vomiting/salivating.  She did bark on the bridges.  Don't know if there was a difference in the sound the car was making or if she didn't understand why we were high above the water.  I was driving so couldn't really watch and figure it out.  The back seat is her preferred place to ride.  When greeting people when we are out she is usually fairly good.  Sometimes she'll try to jump but tends to be very well mannered.  At home it is a different story.  When she is excited she barks/sings and will jump repeatedly.  We have tried blocking her so she can't get at the person, we have tried blocking her with our knees she she jumps to deflect her.  We have tried holding her in a sit until she calms.  The holding her in a sit seems to be somewhat effective.  But there has not been any real improvement here.  She is highly, HIGHLY athletic and jumping is part of her expression of exuberance.  When out playing and given the chance to really run, she tends to bounce initially before she "settles" into that very streamlined graceful run that GSDs have.  We see a lot of bounce in her play with Tori.  Oksana is a fearless dog in a lot of ways.  It really doesn't occur to her to have issues with underfootings, heights etc.  She is incredibly intelligent and exuberant about most of what she encounters.  There is a silliness to her personality which is quite endearing (But in a refined GSD kind of way, not silly they way you see it in a lab).  And she wants to express everything she is seeing/feeling.  So we get a lot of alert barks about the world around us/her.  She will bark at Tori incessantly if Tori is playing with (or more likely cuddling with) a toy she wants.  When first let out of her crate int he morning or when we have been out there is a lot of squealing.  Its double the fun with both her and Tori are excited and fussing.  Her personality is quite lovely, but really her biggest issues are the (at times) incessant barking, the jumping and the play biting.  I feel like everything else is coming along and improving at a reasonable rate for her.

ChewingComments: Chance has not had the opportunity to chew anything inappropriate but given the chance he probably would.
HousemannersComments: I would say his house manners are age appropriate.  We keep most things out of reach at this stage.  We are starting to allow minimal access to inappropriate things such as shoes and socks.  He is learning to leave them alone.
LeftUnattendedComments: He has never been left unattended for longer than a minute and this is a rare occurance.
EliminationHouseComments: He has not had any accidents in a couple of weeks but he goes out on a regular intervals.  He will occaisionally ask to go out.
PlaybiteComments: When he is very tired he will attempt to play bite.  I have been trying to redirect or give him a 2 minute timeout.  If he persists it usually means that he needs to take a nap.  In this case I will crate him and leave him in the crated for a nap.
StealFoodComments: He has never stolen food but he has never been given the opportunity.
OnFurnitureComments: He sometimes tries to get on furniture.  We have been working on this.  I have been treating him for apporaching the furniture and not attempting to jump up.  This seems to be working.
BarksExcessivelyComments: He barks inappropriately at my pet dog especially when she is laying down and chewing a bone but he does it often and she doesn't have to have something he wants.
RaidsGarbageComments: We are slowly introducing the garbage.  He has not really been exposed to kitchen trash.  He has been exposed to bathroom trash and stays out of it.
JumpsComments: He will occaisionally jump up but for the most part he doesn't jump up.
FriendlyWAnimalsComments: He is friendly with other animals but has a tendency to play too rough with smaller dogs.  We have been working on it in class.
KidsComments: He has not been exposed to children in an indoor setting.  He is is friendly with them when we are out and about.
PillsComments: Have not given him any pills but I doubt it will be a problem.
NailsComments: We are working on this.  He pulls back slightly.  I am very slow at nail clipping so it is difficult for me.  I usually cut 1-2 nails a night and pretend to cut the rest.
GeneralComments: Chance is a lot of fun to be around.  He loves to play but also calms down and settles very quickly.

CrateQuietComments: Sometimes whines if she is crated while people are home...we're working on this now

StayComments: This is improving. She'll stay if there are no distractions
GeneralComments: Noel is a very sweet puppy. She can tend to sometimes get over-excited, especially when we are about to go out for a walk. She has always been a big fan of my treadmill so over the past month or so I have been letting her walk on it. If she does 5 minutes or so, this settles her enough to be able to walk calmly outside. She is getting more curious, jumping up on the tables and counters. She doesn't take anything, just looks around then jumps back off. I've been working on this a fair amount and it is improving. She tends to be hesitant at first when she encounters something new but she is quite willing to explore anything with a little patience and encouragement. She is very well-behaved on outings for such a young puppy. We need to work on more outings where she stays still for a time because she has a tendency to grow impatient and bark sometimes. Other than the jumping and occasional chewing, her house manners have always been quite good. She likes to be in whatever room I am in but she'll usually carry a nylabone along with her and play quietly while I am cooking, cleaning, etc. I am very much enjoying raising Noel.

CrateQuietComments: Have made good process from barking to whining.  Class this past Sunday was a good milestone where she was able to be crated inside classroom and only whined to be let out to poop and pee.
KennelCommandComments: Able to Kennel from at least 6 feet away.  Practice using different crates in different locations.

OnFurnitureComments: Working on wanting to jump on the bed to get closer to us.
BarksExcessivelyComments: Will alert bark only  a couple barks when she hears a strange new sound, like door bell on TV. But does not bark at loud sudden noises - just unfamiliar stranger new sounds.
JumpsComments: Has been doing quite well with greetings.  She stand from a seated position but does not jump on put paws on people..
FriendlyWAnimalsComments: Sitter reports good with cat after exposure. Friendly to all breeds of dogs.
KidsComments: Continues to do great with tons of exposure to children of all ages and size and baby carriages at her weekly outing to the library.
StrangerComments: At times, too friendly by her eye contact to draw strangers to her while walking.  Working on keeping her focused forward when walking and to not stare at people as they walk by.
WalkingComments: Does a great job, but working on my handling to keep her closer next to my leg.
EliminateRouteComments: Does great pooping and peeing before or after outings.  Great at peeing on command.
ChaseComment: Working on ignoring those annoying birds who pester you while eating at an outdoor cafe.  She notices them, but shows great restraint and eventually ignores them. No attempts at lunging.  If by herself off leash, she does great with other animals such as rabbit and dear, but will probably give chase if instigated by other loose dogs.
TrafficComments: Appears to do well in her work next to slow and higher speed traffic.  Has shown no reaction to large loud trucks, both moving and idling.
NoiseComments: Have not seen any recent reaction to loud sudden noises.
SitComments: Does great with verbal without needing hand signal.  Working on Sit Means Sit - to sit immediately and to stay in sit position without any additional cues or prompts .
DownComments: Does great with verbal without needing hand signal.  Working on Down Means Down and not to pop up like an automatic pop-up toaster.
ComeOnLeashComments: Continues to make good progress on proofing a reliable recall around higher distractions.
ComeOffLeashComments: Does well under low levels of distractions. Work in progress on proofing a reliable recall using higher levels of visual, auditory, and olfactory distractions.
NailsComments: Has done quite well with allowing nail clippings, still working on using the dremmel.
GeneralComments: Nothing out of the ordinary to report - Phoebe is brilliant!  It's an on-going fun challenge for me to find many different ways to keep her busy and challenged.  She does great in learning her obedience work (providing her teacher can keep her act together!) and is the perfect physical size for honing her agile nimbleness!  It's also a tremendous joy to take her anywhere knowing she will be well behaved.

LeftUnattendedComments: need to have all things off floor and out of reach, he'll grab things off the couch or table if he has the chance
EliminationHouseComments: usually very good, only occasional accidents (#1)
PlaybiteComments: Much improved :)
OnFurnitureComments: in the past, sometimes he would run and jump on the couch to lay down, this behavior is greatly improving.
BarksExcessivelyComments: does this when trying to play with our older dog, or when Escort has something he wants
CountersDoorsComments: mentioned earlier, given the opportunity, he'll take things off table, counter, etc.
WalkingComments: he will not listen as well when our older dog is with us, therefore we usually walk him alone
ChaseComment: cats & rabbit, sometimes the ducks
ComeOnLeashComments: working on this, improving but still requires treats
ComeOffLeashComments: continuing to work on "come"
NailsComments: I haven't done this
NbrOvernights3Mo: we've only had him since mid September
GeneralComments: Caleb is a high maintenance puppy with lots of energy. He is extremely friendly.  We want to start taking him to public places, especially Letchworth school. It is difficult when he is in a crate for a long time during the day while we are at work/school. Starting to have home switches would be helpful.

HealthComments: Cagney has had two eye infections and just got over a double ear infection.
ExericeAmount: walks 1-1.5 hrs day, other activities 20-40 mins day
CrateQuietComments: When other pups are around, he may get a bit vocal (barks) after around 1 hour or so.
ChewingComments: still goes after shoes and socks, but releases with "out" very well
HousemannersComments: Will sometimes get on sofa, but 95%of the time is very good.
StealFoodComments: may want to see what is on counter if smells really good - not a usual problem
OnFurnitureComments: see note under house manners.
BarksExcessivelyComments: only when he is kept in kennel for over hour with other pups around/kenneled
CountersDoorsComments: over the past two  months has jumped on the table, not counter but there were dog treats (really smelly ones open on the table).  Not a usual problem
JumpsComments: Only if "dog people", he seems to pick up on thier excitement.
FriendlyWAnimalsComments: Has gone after the stray cats on our street during the last two months, but getting better at leaving them alone.
KidsComments: LOVES KIDS!!!!!!!
GetBusyComments: Cagney still likes to pee in one spot and poop in another.  He will not poop/pee in the same 6 foot circle.
EliminateRouteComments: Have had a couple of episodes of starting to mark.
ChaseComment: Has gone after the stay cat once - not sure what he would do if off lead.
ComeOffLeashComments: Getting better, still wants to do what he wants.
DayInLife: A typical day starts out around 6 - 6:30 am, get up and make coffee, eat breakfast, workout.  Time on computer until 8 ish, Get kids up for school, home school from 9:30 - 3:30 ish, get dinner ready, have meetings on Monday, Thrusday nights.  Do errands as needed during day or evening.      When we have a pup, I ususally take him out first thing in the morning, 6 am or so (we usually have to work up to that).  I get my coffee, feed pup, have breakfast then take for walk between 7 - 8 am, work on training in morning if still little.  When the kids get up, they usually play with pup for a bit, and we keep to the "get busy" schedule.  Each of the kids helps with "get busy" and training during the day time.  After dinner, and pups dinner, I usally take another walk around the neighorhood, working on LLW.  Then we all settle in for the evening.  During the week, I usually have to go to the doctors, Target and weekly classes with my kids, so the pup goes with us.  If at our doctors, the pup comes in - they all know us and what we are doing with GEB.  At stores,  we work on settleing outside and the different environments.  We try to get in at least 5 outside experiences each week.  On the weekends, we go to parks, and explore with the pups different areas.

ExerciseType: Fetch, walk, playing with other dogs
OnFurnitureComments: Wants to be on couch only when we are sitting on it.
DayInLife: On a typical day my husband wakes up around 8am and takes care of our three labs.  I typically awake at 10am.  For both of our jobs, we work from home.  Both of us have appointments outside the home that we schedule, usually two or three times each day for which we are gone about two hours each time.  Rarely are we both gone at the same time.          He is a sales rep, I am a dog trainer.  I teach obedience classes, both private and group sessions.  Typically I will have two or three evenings each week teaching group classes for two or three hours each time.  I will work sometimes on Saturday, he does not.         We have two college-aged children who live at school during the school year and visit during breaks.  They have always had dogs.          My husband is having knee surgery next week.  He should be rehabbed within eight weeks.  Otherwise, we are both physically active.         We are very sociable people.  We enjoy going out to restaurants in the evenings, usually about three times per week.  We entertain friends in our home often, usually at least once per month, up to ten people at a time.  At Halloween and for the Kentucky Derby we have big parties, up to 30 or more people in our home.  For that reason, a less hyper puppy is probably best for these settings.         We have Browns season tickets and go to all of the games.         We have a swimming pool that our dogs enjoy with us.  We have a large fenced in back yard.         One of our labs is a female that has not been spayed because she has a heart valve problem and anesthesia could compromise her health.  She goes in heat every six months.  Therefore, it may be better that we have a female puppy.  Our one male is neutered.  All of our dogs are well-behaved and very calm.  All have been around other puppies and dogs for extended periods.
