GeneralComments: Gil's dog distraction is still a challenge tho we see improvement. He is highly visual and sensitive to visual changes in the environment-- if not given time to process, or surprised by something, he will go over the red zone. We've been working the dog distraction with some good success and generally, I see good progress in this ever so delightful, easy to have around pup. Thank you.

StoolComments: Starts out very firm, then turns extremely soft for the last portion.
ExerciseType: Long leash chasing ball, swimming, long walks, playing with other dogs/puppies
CrateQuietComments: We have a cat so she goes in there when terrorizing him. Barks a lot for about 15 minutes. When in for night, barks, whines, and whimpers for about 20 minutes. Settles in and sleeps through nght. When put in crate during day just so I can sweep floor or go upstairs for a few minutes, cries and carries on until I come back down.
KennelCommandComments: Doesn't respond hardly at all. Still needs treat/reward to go into kennel at any time.
ChewingComments: Chews occasionally on chair leg or sofa cushion, but responds immediately to the word OUT.
HousemannersComments: Still pees in house occasionally. See #39.
LeftUnattendedComments: I don't think so. I am with her all the time except for taking a shower, but she doesn't do well with my absence. Whines, cries, chews, etc.
EliminationHouseComments: Pees in the house maybe once every 2-3 days. She usually has given us the non-verbal cue, but we either missed it or my boys didn't want to break away from the TV long enough to take her out.
StealFoodComments: She would if she got the chance, but we are very diligent about leaving food around.
BarksExcessivelyComments: She really only barks at the cat. Rest of the time outdoors or in she does fine.
RaidsGarbageComments: We have very small cans in the livingroom and sometimes she will surf those, especially when my youngest son disposes of paper plates with food on them.
CountersDoorsComments: Only on the door when chasing the cat.
JumpsComments: She meets people usually by jumping up, but within 2-3 minutes is ignoring them and laying  down on the ground.
FriendlyWAnimalsComments: Very friendly. Not intimidated by larger dogs and plays rough, but nicely with the smaller ones.
WalkingComments: It doesn't show in puppy class, but she does walk very well with the lead.
GetBusyComments: Getting better, but has a way to go.
EliminateRouteComments: If she needs to go, she goes.
NoiseComments: The 2 noises we noticed she struggles with is fireworks and we have a small SHARK vaccum cleaner she doesn't like too well. It is OK from a distance, but when it starts getting close, she goes into the "bunny hop" mode.
StairsComments: She does pretty well with the limited exposure she gets. We don't let her upstairs as it is not puppy proofed. She won't go down the basement stairs as she instantly shys away when we go out to the garage.She has never fallen on them, but just won't go near them.
StayComments: Just learned thet this past week and is learning. Doing pretty well with it.
PillsComments: Don't know...haven't had to give her any. The heartworm cube went down well.
EarsComments: Don't know...had it done with the vet when given 12 weeks vaccines.
NailsComments: Don't know...done with the vet when given 12 weeks vaccines.
GeneralComments: She has a tough time in class. Not sure why, but she is exhausted. Rachel mentioned it to us and we have gone to class with Dasha having done nothing during the day, but after about 15 minutes of class, she has checked out. She does really well with the training at home, but during class just can't keep it together.    We haven't switched homes yet, so not sure how to answer the questions above, since 0 is not an option.
DayInLife: I live in a 3300 square foot home with my two sons, Bradley and Corey who are both attending this class. My wife passed away 8 years ago. I have always wanted a dog, but told myself I wouldn't have one until I was sure I could take care of it. Now that I have been retired for 3 years and my children are older, I think now is a good time. I recognize that a potential 15 year commitment may be a little agressive since I don't know what I will be getting into. I think raising a GEB puppy will give me the proven knowledge to raise a puppy successfully. Just reading the materials makes me sure that If this was my own puppy, I would be proud of his behaviors when I took him somewhere.     We live in a townhouse with a family next to us in the same building and neighbors in the next building about 25 feet away. The folks in the same building have no dogs, but 3 indoor cats. They have 2 children...a 6 year old girl and a 1 year old boy. The ones in the building next to us is adopting an 11 year old girl this summer and they have a very obnoxious chihuahua. They don't leash their dog and I anticipate it being a problem at some point this summer. The folks across the street have a 3 year old Puggle and the unit attached to them have a beagle and a terrier and 3 cats. The cats are always roaming the neighborhood and the beagle is never leashed.     I am home all day unless I am doing errands...grocery shopping, pick up a script, stop at the bank, Dunkin Donuts for breakfast, etc. There is no reason the pup wouldn't/couldn't go with me everytime I leave the house. I volunteer at the local middle school on Thursdays and they have already said it would be OK if the pup came with me after he is house trained. My son has already checked with the high school and they have said he could have show and tell days there so the puppy if exposed to about 1500 kids moving in the aisles after each class.    We have a camp for the summer. We would take the dog to camp with us. The camp is right on the water so he could swim. We have a 60 foot dock and a boat which he could certainly ride with us. The neighbors there are very good. One has a 13 year old yellow lab and the other is rarely there. Their nephew come now and then and has a Rotweiller.  We are at camp 4 to 5 days a week during the summer...mid-April to late October.    We are planning a cruise April 2013, usually gone for 7-9 days, so would need a sitter during that time.    I would like a female yellow lab, on the whiter side if possible. I would like to request that the name isn't Sue, Susan, or Suzanne as my wifes name was Susan and while I wouldn't have any trouble with those names, out of respect for my in-laws  I don't think those names would be appropriate.    I am a morning person whereas my sons are more afternoon to evening/night. I would hope for a puppy who isn't high energy, but one who doesn't mind moving and going out and learning new things.

PillsComments: Don't know...haven't had to give her any. The heartworm cube went down well.
EarsComments: Don't know...had it done with the vet when given 12 weeks vaccines.
NailsComments: Don't know...done with the vet when given 12 weeks vaccines.
GeneralComments: She has a tough time in class. Not sure why, but she is exhausted. Rachel mentioned it to us and we have gone to class with Dasha having done nothing during the day, but after about 15 minutes of class, she has checked out. She does really well with the training at home, but during class just can't keep it together.    We haven't switched homes yet, so not sure how to answer the questions above, since 0 is not an option.
DayInLife: I live in a 3300 square foot home with my two sons, Bradley and Corey who are both attending this class. My wife passed away 8 years ago. I have always wanted a dog, but told myself I wouldn't have one until I was sure I could take care of it. Now that I have been retired for 3 years and my children are older, I think now is a good time. I recognize that a potential 15 year commitment may be a little agressive since I don't know what I will be getting into. I think raising a GEB puppy will give me the proven knowledge to raise a puppy successfully. Just reading the materials makes me sure that If this was my own puppy, I would be proud of his behaviors when I took him somewhere.     We live in a townhouse with a family next to us in the same building and neighbors in the next building about 25 feet away. The folks in the same building have no dogs, but 3 indoor cats. They have 2 children...a 6 year old girl and a 1 year old boy. The ones in the building next to us is adopting an 11 year old girl this summer and they have a very obnoxious chihuahua. They don't leash their dog and I anticipate it being a problem at some point this summer. The folks across the street have a 3 year old Puggle and the unit attached to them have a beagle and a terrier and 3 cats. The cats are always roaming the neighborhood and the beagle is never leashed.     I am home all day unless I am doing errands...grocery shopping, pick up a script, stop at the bank, Dunkin Donuts for breakfast, etc. There is no reason the pup wouldn't/couldn't go with me everytime I leave the house. I volunteer at the local middle school on Thursdays and they have already said it would be OK if the pup came with me after he is house trained. My son has already checked with the high school and they have said he could have show and tell days there so the puppy if exposed to about 1500 kids moving in the aisles after each class.    We have a camp for the summer. We would take the dog to camp with us. The camp is right on the water so he could swim. We have a 60 foot dock and a boat which he could certainly ride with us. The neighbors there are very good. One has a 13 year old yellow lab and the other is rarely there. Their nephew come now and then and has a Rotweiller.  We are at camp 4 to 5 days a week during the summer...mid-April to late October.    We are planning a cruise April 2013, usually gone for 7-9 days, so would need a sitter during that time.    I would like a female yellow lab, on the whiter side if possible. I would like to request that the name isn't Sue, Susan, or Suzanne as my wifes name was Susan and while I wouldn't have any trouble with those names, out of respect for my in-laws  I don't think those names would be appropriate.    I am a morning person whereas my sons are more afternoon to evening/night. I would hope for a puppy who isn't high energy, but one who doesn't mind moving and going out and learning new things.

GeneralComments: Louie is a boisterous, loving puppy that will activate quickly when interacting with others (especially if eye contact, talking to him, handling, etc).  However, when we go places (including office settings with close contact with others walking right by him) he can ignore and stay settled.  He will lie still while I do body handling, clip nails, even let me put ice pack over his eye and muzzle when recently stung by insect.  He needs his daily exercise but spends hours sleeping, chewing bone, etc.  He does well sitting and watching activity - can get fairly close.  When not overly activated he is a wonderful walker, staying right at left side with no pulling.  While challenging at times, he has been an absolute joy to raise!

HealthComments: Had one ear infection which was treated and is now gone.
ExerciseType: Walking, as well as playing with humans and known dog friends.
KennelCommandComments: He needs to be able to see the kennel to respond to it. So we're working on that.
ChewingComments: It is truly awesome to see Scooter pick up only his toys to chew - but one thing that has come up every once in a while (much less so than when he was a puppy) is that he grabs his leash in his mouth.
HousemannersComments: Scooter has great house manners, no counter surfing, no food stealing, he's curious about the kitchen garbage, but knows not to go into it, however there are 2 major areas we're working on with Scooter: couch and toilet paper.
LeftUnattendedComments: Scooter can absolutely be left unattended if the following conditions are met: couch xpen-ed off and bathroom door closed. I would love to give him a 5 on this, but realize that should probably be reserved for when he doesn't need those 2 conditions.
EliminationHouseComments: We can't tell if it's accidental marking or excitement, but every once in a whlie he does have mini accidents.
OnFurnitureComments: He does get up on the couch, not always, but enough that we xpen-ed the couch off and he seemed to understand his place was his bed, but since removing the xpen after a couple months of it being up he's started getting up there again so we're putting the xpen back up and we're thinking we would invest in a fluffier bed since the stuffing in his has been compressed.
BarksExcessivelyComments: He does a lot of this at Elizabeth - after our last walk and talk we continued to make a lot of progress with Elizabeth leaving the room, but it's resumed and would love some reminders and suggestions on how to resolve this.
RaidsGarbageComments: He is great with a closed kitchen trash, but the open bathroom trash is sometimes a little too enticing.
FriendlyWAnimalsComments: Scooter does this laying down thing when he sees another dog, he doesn't pounce as it's usually from a distance and sometimes he won't get up even when the walk by and depart. We can try to show this to you at the Walk and Talk.
ChaseComment: Birds are a weakness.
StairsComments: Scooter has made incredible progress on stairs, but confident is still something we're working on. Can't wait until this is a 5.
ComeOffLeashComments: Depends on distractions - would love to work on this more in class if possible since it's a safe place to practice with other dogs and people.
EarsComments: He was great at this, but the ear infection may have hurt this a bit. definitey must soak a cotton ball with the cleaner and put it in his ear and squeeze for it to go smoothly. Which is fine - the person just needs to know not to just go ahead and squeeze a bottle into the dogs ear - no one likes that.

GeneralComments: Grant has never been a super confident puppy. He's always been a bit cautious, but would check things out in his own time. However, he's become scared of many sounds. For instance, he never minded the vacuum cleaner, but now he's spooked by it. I always make sure he has the opportunity to leave the room before I vacuum, and he always decides to leave. He may or may not check it out later when it's off and I leave it in the corner. A few days ago my son was playing with motorized hot wheel cars that run on a track. He heard the sound of the cars and ran out of the room into his crate. He's never been bothered by the cars before. We immediately turned it off and put it in a corner. My son has been playing with it when he's far away from Grant. Now Grant is not bothered by the toy at all and will walk next to it. He was troubled a few days ago when he heard the sound of aerosol stay can. W've been spaying it when he's far away from us, and he's clearly less disturbed. His reactions to noises are unpredictable. A heavy book recently fell close to his head, and he never even looked up (not bothered). He's not scared of traffic/construction noises. I think his fearfulness started when we were in a bathroom at a restaurant and a loud automatic hand dryer started. We left immediately. The sound of the dryer and air blowing profoundly affected him. He's an extremely calm dog, so it's easy to see when he's disturbed. He starts shaking, waging his tail, pulling his leash and whimpering. A few days after the blow dryer incident we went to a hospital to pick up medical records. He was fine at first and then became agitated. I still have no idea what spooked him (there was nothing obvious like a loud noise or unfamiliar object). Again, we left immediately. I haven't taken him into a building since that time. He stayed with an experienced raiser for 5 days, and she worked with him. She didn't find any specific triggers either. We've been hanging out in parking lots or shopping centers and walking in new places. He's great on those outings. At home we try to anticipate what will upset him and make sure he has the opportunity to leave the room.  He is generally good with under footings and will walk on most textures. He gets a little bothered if the under footing makes strange noises.   He can be indecisive. He understands basic commands and is compliant, but takes a few seconds to think through the process.   He's also a sensitive dog. He gets upset when we get upset (thin skinned). Therefore, we stay calm and never raise our voices. We give him tons of positive feedback.   His house manners are wonderful.   Anyhow, I'm trying to help him regain his confidence. He's a sweet dog with a great temperament.

WalkingComments: Pulls!
DayInLife: My husband, John, and I are very excited to be puppy raisers and truly feel that we will be able to give our puppy the time and energy required.  We also feel that our 4-year-old Golden Retriever, Aisling, will love being part of the process.      A typical work day for us starts with coffee and then a walk with our dog before work.  John works Monday-Friday, but I only work on Thursday and Fridays so am home during the day for three of the work days.  I am at work all day on Thursdays and Fridays, but since John works very close by, he is able to come home during his lunch hour to visit with Aisling (and the puppy) and get them out for a bit.     During the evenings and weekends, we also spend a lot of time with Aisling and take her lots of places with us.

DayInLife: (Kristin writing!) Karim & I will probably be splitting our puppy raising responsibilities in half due to our schedules and the fact that it is just the two of us, no other family members. We live in a one-floor/one-bedroom hours (no upstairs/downstairs) in a pretty rural part of Watertown (we can't even get internet connection at the house) that is bordered by a summer camp and a horse farm.  The house has about a 1/4 mile long driveway...so there is lots of room outside!  We are both very active and do a lot of biking & running, so we are used to having to go outside in all kinds of weather.  Karim works at UConn (there will be some awesome socialization options on campus at some point!) and I work at the YMCA (about 10 minutes from home, so not far). Monday-Thursday I will typically be the one to get up in the morning with the puppy, before work, and then Karim will be home with him most days until noonish, and in the afternoon I will be home, or be able to take a break and come home for a while to let the puppy out.  We are both off on Fridays, so it is only four days during the workweek we have to juggle schedules a bit. We have a close friend who actually works on the camp property next door to the house who has said she would be willing to learn the process by which we are training the puppy, etc. (understanding that the puppy will need consistency) in case we need her to go over and check on him and take him out to get busy in a pinch. I frequently work late on Tuesdays, but we should be able to lay out our schedule and figure out which Tuesdays I can come to, which Tuesdays Karim can come to, or when we can go to another region on Saturdays if neither of us can pull off the Tuesday that week. We will be going out of the country for a wedding at the end of December and will need a puppy sitter at that time, for two weeks.  Overall we are very excited about doing this, and being a puppy raiser for a program like this has been a dream of mine since I was a child, which Karim is totally on board with and looking forward to as well.

GeneralComments: Rosa overall is a very sweet and friendly pup. She loves meeting new people and other dogs, and is very smart. In the house she picks up commands fairly quickly but can still get distracted outside the house or at class. Still need to tame some of her puppy behaviors like occasional counter surfing.   Could use advice helping her settle while we eat family dinner, etc. We always feed her first and take a get busy break if she needs. Sometimes she will fall asleep and/or settle; other times she can't seem to settle - will bark or nip for attention or go from person to person trying to climb up on the chair and potentially steal food. Efforts to re-direct her with toy, kong, ice cube, etc. are short-lived and if we put her in the kennel at those times she will bark and bark.
DayInLife: My husband and I are active people in our early 40s. We have a single family home on a quiet suburban cul-de-sac, walking distance to a few nearby stores, etc. Several neighbors also have dogs. We have two school aged-children ages 6 and 9; our 9-year-old is autistic but likes animals; he is very active.     My husband and I both work from home. He does sales and customer service and is on the phone a lot; I'm a freelance writer so my job involves writing/working on the computer and some phone calls.    A typical day for us is waking around 7 to get the kids ready for school by 8. My son gets a school bus at the door, then one of us drives my daughter to school. We basically work from home until 3/3:30 when it's time to get the kids from school/the bus, supervise play time and homework, dinner, showers, getting them ready for bed by 9 p.m. We usually go to bed around 11:30 p.m.     Our weekends vary - sometimes a lot of social activity going on, other times not as much.

DayInLife: I am a teacher and am off during the summer and federal holidays.  I have a break at Christmas and in April. We have no set weekend schedule.  We live on a private road with only eight houses, three of which belong to immediate family members.  Amy's grandmother lives on the street, is retiring in June, and will be able to let the puppy out to get busy when we all return to school next fall.  We have two, female golden retrievers that are both 11 years old (they are sisters). These dogs are very laid back although they love to run around and play with each other when they are outside. When the weather is nice they stay outside all day as we have Invisible Fence installed. We also own sheep, horses, and chickens along with two parakeets. Amy will be going to camp this summer for one week and I have agreed to train the pup during that time. Amy's sister is going to be a high school senior next fall and we will be going on several college visits this summer that may include some overnights. Amy is in the Ag program and is interested in possibly bringing the puppy to school at times.  She would be allowed to leave the pup in a crate in the Ag department and go down periodically to take the dog out to get busy.

HealthComments: Oak has had some recurring issues with his eyes, otherwise okay
ExerciseType: Playing in fenced yard, playing with other dogs, tugging, fetch, walking
EliminationCrateComments: Will shred foam bedding and occasionally blankets. He also has been know to vomit stick fragments in his kennel during the night.
CrateQuietComments: Oak is terrific in the crate with one exception: if it is past his dinnertime and he hasn't eaten.
ChewingComments: See below, not sure if this counts as "chewing" or simply ingesting.
HousemannersComments: Oak will attempt to steal napkins off counters/table, will raid garbages for napkins and fabric, and will ingest any socks/gloves in reach. He has done this since he was 8 weeks old and has made almost no improvement despite the enormous amount of effort we have all put into working on it. His other house manner issues he had a young pup (getting up on furniture, ingesting carpet, and chewing) have all progressed completely normally as he has aged.
LeftUnattendedComments: Oak cannot be let unattended unless in a secure kennel with minimal bedding/toys, otherwise he will ingest almost anything. Whenever I need to step out of eyesight I call someone to watch him for me.
PlaybiteComments: Oak will attempt to jump and snap to grab toys when playing
StealFoodComments: Despite Oak's neurotic scavenging for paper and fabric, he progressed completely normally with food-stealing and will not attempt to steal food, even when close to his face.
BarksExcessivelyComments: Oak will attempt to provoke household dog by barking at her if she is on the couch. He also will back out of suspicion on occasion.
RaidsGarbageComments: Oak will take and ingest napkins and fabric scraps from the garbage if left unattended
CountersDoorsComments: Oak will attempt to steal napkins if left within eyesight, otherwise he is fine
JumpsComments: Oak will launch full-force at people's faces if I don't hold onto him. He also attempts to jump and bite me when he is extremely activated.
FriendlyWAnimalsComments: Oak tends to get overexcited very easily and will jump on other dogs/animals, we have found that sort repeat exposures work best
KidsComments: Oak does extremely well with children when asked to lay down before they approach. With support he will remain in a down the entire time they approach, engage and leave.
StrangerComments: Oak will almost always jump up on people without fail. People greetings work best when I hold his collar and apply pressure to keep him focused.
EliminateRouteComments: Oak does like to urinate on walks, which we are working on by cutting down the length of his walks and having longer get busy breaks beforehand
ChaseComment: Does try to bolt after the cat if the other household dog bolts first
SitComments: Oak is slow to respond to most commands, collar pressure helps immensely when trying to get him to change position.
ComeOffLeashComments: Oak is generally very reliable, however he can get distracted and not return right away
GeneralComments: Oak is a neurotic scavenger, which has been the main focus of both his previous Walk and Talks and many get togethers. He is a serious danger to himself when left unattended. Other than this, our main issue is his jump-launching at people when they approach.

DayInLife: There are 3 of us in the house mostly: my son-11 yrs, my dog Belle -4 yrs, 13lbs,  Japanese chin & papillon mix and myself. My daughter is in college, home on school break & summer.    We live in a "community" neighborhood where we do know our neighbors.   We (Belle&I) start the day w/ walking the neighborhood for at LEAST 1/2 hr when it's not too cold. We are really active.    I work mostly from home, when need to I go to office. I have flexible schedule. I am mostly on the phone for meeting in the morning. I tried to get Belle exercise and tired out so she just relax most morning while I attend my meetings.  We walk again at lunch time 30-40mins. When Rugby, neighbor dog, is out Belle plays w/ Rugby for 15 mins.    Belle comes w/ us mostly when I will only drop or pick up Soney.  Soney has activities mostly every night and I mostly shuttle him.    I don't have fenced in yard, when we let Belle out, she is on leash and for 10 mins at most (she calls/barks to come in, does not like to be out by herself).   I understand we always have to watch and leashed puppy when we do let them out.  My kitchen is one big open area (great room): kitchen & family room.  Plan is to have crate in this great room, in my office (upstair) and my bedroom (1st flr).    Any question do call 518-461-2044

StoolComments: She frequently has loose stool and sometimes will wake me up to go outside. She will also poop on walks after just having gotten busy.
CrateQuietComments: She is good in familiar places but barks when the kennel is somewhere unfamiliar and there is activity going on around her
ChewingComments: Rosa needs a lot of work in this area, she steels inappropriate objects frequently.
HousemannersComments: She steels and counter surfs, she also chases the cat
LeftUnattendedComments: She would steel/ get into things
StealFoodComments: Will try even if you are with her
OnFurnitureComments: If left unattended she will climb on furniture to steel pillows or food off the table. Does not do it when you are looking
BarksExcessivelyComments: She has gotten better at this but it still needs work.
RaidsGarbageComments: She has learned to stay out of the garbage
FriendlyWAnimalsComments: Good with dogs, tries to chase cats
KidsComments: She absolutely loves children. She is fantastic with them.
StrangerComments: Typically friendly but my be somewhat unsure around people that may look strange. (i.e. clothing that confuses her, carrying large objects ect)
WalkingComments: She does a good job in low distraction situations. But she will stop to sniff/plant herself in one spot if she is starting to get stressed or there is a lot going on.
GetBusyComments: She does eliminate on command but also has trouble with going again on walks after she has already gone. She also pulls on the leash a lot when she is squatting to poop regardless of get busy command.
EliminateRouteComments: explained previously- although I think this has to do with her propensity for loose stool
ChaseComment: doesn't try to chase squirrels and birds on walks, but will try to chase the cat when off leash in the house
TrafficComments: She is ok in short doses but gets stressed easily
NoiseComments: does exhibit nervous changes in body language with loud noises
StairsComments: good going up but really needs to concentrate on the way down
DownComments: She sometimes refuses to down while I am trying to get her to settle
ComeOffLeashComments: She did really well with this when we practiced in my parent's large fenced yard
PillsComments: unknown
NailsComments: She is pretty good, but squirms a bit
GeneralComments: I am very concerned with Rosa's confidence level and house manners. In active public situations she does well for short periods of time.

DayInLife: Since Jen is an 8th grade teacher in Nashua, the schedule in the summer and during school vacations will be different. Jay works from home as an engineer. A typical day is a low-key routine: getting up, breakfast, Jay works until noon then breaks for lunch, then continues to work until Jen gets home between 3-4pm most afternoons. On rare occasions, Jay leaves the house for up to a few hours during the day. Sometimes we run errands before or after dinner, but usually home by 8pm. Being a puppy raiser will add walks and multiple teaching/play breaks throughout the day. Weekends vary for flexibility as sometimes we travel to CT or RI to visit family, usually leaving on a Friday night or early Saturday morning and returning on Sunday. We do not have kids or other pets, but we live in a condominium complex where many people walk their dogs around the main loop (which is 1 mile) and there are young children next door. Our unit is a 4-story, mostly carpeted townhouse located near several wooded areas of various sizes that are host to various wildlife, including deer, turkeys, chipmunks, etc. We have extensive experience owning and fostering Weimaraners (short and long term) as well as assisting with various rescue activities for the breed.

StoolComments: Natchez is currently taking a daily probiotic to get his system back on track. The first stool of the day is always normal and the second a bit soft--he seems to have improved a lot since beginning the probiotic. We'll continue this another month per the GEB vet
ExerciseType: Daily walk of 3-5 miles. Playtime throughout the day, inside and out--ball fetching, running with other pet, etc.
BarksExcessivelyComments: In class he barks frequently, but never anywhere else.
GeneralComments: Natchez is a wonderful, smart, puppy with a great disposition--he's an absolute pleasure to be around, and not just for our family, but for the families he has stayed with, who have given us very positive feedback. He is calm and confident and is quick to learn new things. He has really improved regarding outside distractions, like squirrels, birds, and blowing leaves. The one negative is the barking in class and I'm working on that--being more of a leader to him...

DayInLife: Background:  Edward Ruitberg and Laura Ruitberg are empty nesters living in a home located in Davidsonville, MD.  Edward is the prospective primary puppy raiser and Laura is the secondary raiser.    Ed is going through a life change and raising a puppy is part of the plan.  Ed is transitioning into retirement following a 40-plus year career working for the NASA/Goddard Space Flight Center.  It’s been difficult to decide when to retire, but the commitment of being a puppy raiser is making it easier.  Once the puppy arrives, Ed will continue with some consulting work from home, but the puppy becomes priority number one!    Laura is retired and was a bookkeeper and office manager for various companies over her career.    Our son lives and works in Ashburn, VA, approximately 1.5-hour drive away.  He has two children that live in Oklahoma City and they come to visit us about twice a year.    We do not currently own a dog, but have three cats.  We both love dogs, but our daily work schedules and Ed’s frequent business travel didn’t lend itself to proper dog raising.     Typical Day:  We both expect to be home most every day.  We typically get up early and go to bed early.  It normally starts about 5:00 am, workdays and weekends, and ends by 10:00 pm.  Ed usually makes most of the meals.   Ed plans to do consulting work at home during the morning hours.      Lifestyle:  Ed and Laura have a quiet relaxed lifestyle, that is, until the grandchildren visit.  We are both non-smokers.  Ed’s hobbies include bicycle riding and he spends lots of time working in the yard and on other home projects.  Laura’s hobbies include reading, especially mystery novels, and quilting.  Although she’s a cat person, Laura hasn’t met a dog she didn’t like.  She always enjoys greeting and playing with the Weimaraner who lives next door.    Work schedule:  Ed’s work plan following retirement will consist of consulting work from home averaging about 12 hours per week, with occasional visits to business offices.  The schedule is totally flexible.    Weekend schedule:  Ed and Laura’s weekend schedule is open format.  There are weekend shopping trips usually on Saturday mornings.  We attend church on a weekly basis.    Home setting:  Our home is in a residential community near Annapolis, MD.  The homes are on large lots (~2 acres) so there is plenty of open space.  There are many children in the neighborhood, the elementary school is nearby, and the school bus stop is down the street.   Most of our neighbors have dogs and there are many dog-walkers.  Our neighbors have offered encouragement and support for us becoming a puppy raiser.    What led us to Guiding Eyes for the Blind:  After not having had a dog for many years, the desire for a dog came to me (Ed) in a surprising way.  Several years ago on a bicycle ride in southern Maryland I came across this dog that I still think about.  At the time, I was alone on a rural road within sight of the Chesapeake Bay.  After making a turn at this scenic place, there was this chocolate Labrador Retriever standing behind a fence silently watching me.  I came to within a few feet of the dog, made eye contact, and connected with him/her instantly.  I thought what a beautiful animal!  I continued riding, a changed person.    Recently, several people brought service dogs in training to the office.  One of these people happened to be a dog-sitter for Guiding Eyes for the Blind, Montgomery Region, and I felt that connection again with her black Labrador Retriever.  I told myself, “I need to get one of these dogs.”  So here I am.

ExerciseType: walks, ball/frisbee playing, playing with other dogs
HousemannersComments: Working on stopping the crumb sweeping.
LeftUnattendedComments: We have 2 other dogs and sometimes the other 2 are done playing before Rhiana is done.  She has not gotten a stuffed animal or anything she shouldn't around the house in 1-2 months.
PlaybiteComments: If you rough house with her, she does playful nips. If you don't rough house with her, she won't do this;.
StealFoodComments: She will sniff, but not take food. Working on crumb sweeping.
RaidsGarbageComments: She doesn't pull anything out of the garbage but she will sniff it.
JumpsComments: She will when people rough house with her.
FriendlyWAnimalsComments: Too friendly. Loves cats, dogs, etc. Always wants to meet other dogs and play with them.
WalkingComments: Very fast and pulls.
GetBusyComments: Sometimes takes her a while; sometimes needs to walk a bit first.
EliminateRouteComments: If I forget or she really has to go, she will stop in her tracks.
TrafficComments: I think she doesn't like fast traffic or lots of traffic. We are working on this and will do more as the weather gets better.
NoiseComments: I don't think it is the noise of the traffic since she doesn't seem to mind noise from commuter buses, fireworks, shooting range, basketball games, etc.
SitComments: Working on this with more of the 3 Ds.
DownComments: Working on this with more of the 3 Ds.
StayComments: Working on this with more of the 3 Ds.
ComeOnLeashComments: Other dogs and food on the floor are hard for her.
ComeOffLeashComments: Other dogs and food on the floor are hard for her.
GeneralComments: We are working on getting to the next level of 3 Ds, items under foot, dog distraction, crumb sweeping, settling, and confidence in everything.  We live in a rural area so in addition to being with me each day at a PK-8 school, I'm trying to get her out to a different place each day to increase her experiences and confidence.
DayInLife: I work in the main office for a private PK-8th grade school with about 325 students. In the main office area, I sit with a co-worker, Grace, who also has dogs and is willing to help me with the puppy when I have meetings or am involved with another student.  I have about 1-3 meetings each week lasting an hour.  Our school does not have a nurse, so Grace and I handle student illness, cuts, scrapes, etc. as well.  In the past, I have provided first aid, CPR and AED training.  Grace handles the cuts, scrapes, etc.  I tend to handle the big stuff such as administering an Epi-pen.  We also have a diabetic student which I help administer or test approx. once a day which takes about 5-10 minutes. The main part of my job is development work and is very flexible.  I have permission from our headmaster, Randy Hollister, to bring the puppy with me to work each day.  In our office there are 7-8 people who have additionally said they would be willing to help with the puppy.  I tend to work from 8:15-5pm.  I typically work the last two weeks of August until the third week of June and a couple of days in July.  The summer hours are 9am-3pm.  The puppy/crate would be by my desk, but out of the way.  I do not work in a classroom or have any set times that I am watching students.  However, I plan to take full advantage of having all these people around for the puppy to meet!    Our family lives in a rural area. We have about 30 acres which is mainly wooded.  We have 2 labs; Blackie has had 5 litters and we kept one from the first litter, Vader.  Both are females and not neutered.  Blackie is 12 years old and Vader is 9 years old.  Both have outside kennels and until this past cold winter, stayed outside all year around.  Blackie is slowing down and so we kept them in the kitchen area most of the winter.  We have an open floor plan but taught them to stay in the kitchen area.  With the warm weather, they are back outside all the time now.  However, the puppy would be with us wherever we are in the house.  We also have two cats, our mousers, Santa and Mrs. Claus.  They are also mostly outside except on cold winter nights.  Mrs. Claus and Vader are often seen licking each other!  Our cats are used to puppies and our dogs are as well.  We have not fenced in our yard, but have kennels and an extra kennel we used when we were raising Blackie's puppies.  When outside and not on a leash, we would use this extra kennel.  We are working to fence in our yard because of all of the deer in our area, but have only started that project.     My husband often works from home and will keep the puppy home when I can't bring the puppy to work. He has raised several dogs and is very interested to learn how it's done with Guiding Eyes.  Alex is a sophomore at Virginia Tech and will be home for the summer in May.  His plans aren't set yet, so we're not sure how much he'll be home for helping with the training.  Leland is a junior in high school and leads the NJROTC drill team.  They practice each day from 4-5pm. He also takes guitar lessons.  Leland is really looking forward to help raising the puppy.  Besides me, he will be doing a lot of the training.  He hasn't been able to take the classes because of his school exams, but I've been going over the material with him.    I work out 4-6 times a week, twice a week with a trainer.  He said I could bring the puppy there.  We do not generally go running, but if we do, I'd make other arrangements for the puppy.  The other workout times are at home in the morning or evening for 30-45 minutes.      I also volunteer for our church. We are considering expanding our facilities and I am on the finance portion of the building committee.  We meet after church on Sundays twice a month for about an hour and half.  I also help out with the youth group who meet Sunday evenings for a couple of hours.  We have often taken Blackie's puppies to them and to school for socialization, so they are used to this from our family!    On the weekends, I'm either running errands, playing in the garden, going to concerts (we are music fans!), or getting together with friends.    Most of my schedule and my family's schedule is flexible.  I don't see us having blocks of time when the puppy will be crated and alone.  If I had something going on at school, my husband would either work from home or take the puppy with him to his work.  He has a separate closed door office and a co-worker has one of our pups from Blackie.  My main concern for the puppy is being able to take the puppy to work with me each day in an open office area and being around PK-8th grade children.  I think this will work.  I know I will have to expand my hours a bit to do the training and bathroom breaks.  And I have taken several batches of 1-8 week old puppies to school for a few hours, but haven't taken a single puppy to work for several months and would welcome any suggestions!    We are all looking forward to this opportunity.  Thank you so very much for considering us!

Besides me, he will be doing a lot of the training.  He hasn't been able to take the classes because of his school exams, but I've been going over the material with him.    I work out 4-6 times a week, twice a week with a trainer.  He said I could bring the puppy there.  We do not generally go running, but if we do, I'd make other arrangements for the puppy.  The other workout times are at home in the morning or evening for 30-45 minutes.      I also volunteer for our church. We are considering expanding our facilities and I am on the finance portion of the building committee.  We meet after church on Sundays twice a month for about an hour and half.  I also help out with the youth group who meet Sunday evenings for a couple of hours.  We have often taken Blackie's puppies to them and to school for socialization, so they are used to this from our family!    On the weekends, I'm either running errands, playing in the garden, going to concerts (we are music fans!), or getting together with friends.    Most of my schedule and my family's schedule is flexible.  I don't see us having blocks of time when the puppy will be crated and alone.  If I had something going on at school, my husband would either work from home or take the puppy with him to his work.  He has a separate closed door office and a co-worker has one of our pups from Blackie.  My main concern for the puppy is being able to take the puppy to work with me each day in an open office area and being around PK-8th grade children.  I think this will work.  I know I will have to expand my hours a bit to do the training and bathroom breaks.  And I have taken several batches of 1-8 week old puppies to school for a few hours, but haven't taken a single puppy to work for several months and would welcome any suggestions!    We are all looking forward to this opportunity.  Thank you so very much for considering us!

I guess that I am more concerned when she is sitting staring at the cat, that the cat might do more harm to her. can get overly aroused playing with some dogs.  Need for supervision and help her to turn on her Off Button which is good when she is given  support to do so
KidsComments: she seeks them out and I use children as a reward when we are out in public.   Her body language is comfort

EliminateRouteComments: I have to make sure we go before we leave home on long line.   she has gone without permission.   urinating more often now.  handler needs to pay attention.

GeneralComments: a pleasantly energetic and responsive pup.   playful and  fun companion.  Easy going.  connects very readily and then rearing to go with appropriate moves.   She knows her skills and needs for handler to move with confidence in her.  devoted and affectionate .   On and Off Button excellent in most situations.   Sometimes playing with certain dogs, she gets excited and play turns rough and  she  needs help with Off button.    Once given the support , she settles with a  shake off.    With two transitions from sitter to class setting, she was unable to participate in class appropriatly.   she was totally distracted by other dogs.     As her handler , I was not able to be present . I was so surprised by behavior and couldn't get out of my own way .  Another handler took her and she settled  somewhat/    We are paying attention to transitions with her. However    she does really well when other people work her !   even people who are new to  GEB protocol.    I REALLY appreciate the collaboration with what we see and  the teaching and  support of Pat and Lee-Anne. I think that this little peanut is a winner.   a lovely house companion and traveling companion.   Incredible with grandson 4 yrs. old with downs syndrome.   He leads her around until she says.......Enough!   and she  lies down to end the walk.    What  a girl..... a mind of her own for sure.     My gratitude for yet another wondeful visitor along the way in my life!   I love her and  the  experience   is more alive today than ever.    with gratitude

GeneralComments: Imari is a very friendly, high energy pup. She is great with her commands. She had been attending school with me every day during the school and was great in those situations. She learned how to appropriately greet people which is hard for her exhuberant personality. However, she seems to show great anxiety when around dogs that she does not live with. She seems to be getting a bit better when walking the neighborhood. However, if in the presence of a dog or other dogs for any extended period of time, becomes overwrought and uncontrollable. Class is a perfect example in that she could not settle long enough to complete any task asked of her. Since she is a very strong dog, it becomes difficult for me to control or handle her. Imari also benefits greatly from repeated exposure to all new situations. She has been to lots and lots of places and various kinds of places and situations, and the more she repeats the same scenarios, the more confident she becomes. She is a great dog and I hope can find a situation that will work for her.

DayInLife: Our adult children are gone from the home, occasionally back on a weekend. So it is just Mary and I for the most part. Mary goes out to work 9-5 Monday - Friday. I work from home 3-4 days a week, some days going to visit customers and occasionally gone over night. Mary works 20 minutes from home so can return at lunch to care for puppy. On days at home I am free to use my time as needed, so lot's of opportunity to work with pup. My office is in the finished basement, door can be closed, puppy monitored and taught. Weekends are usually in and out, chores, errands, yard work, pool time, etc. Our home is 4 BR Colonial on 1+ acres, in a peaceful, family oriented development. Many opportunities for socialization. Yard is spacious with a large fenced in area. Our family dog is 14+, has been a big part of family life since a puppy. He is neutered. His hind quarter is arthritic, becoming very weak; he no longer sees or hears well. But his appetite is good, he is responsive and we are monitoring closely. We will not let him suffer, when the time comes we will consult with his vet and do what is necessary. We are active socially, try to get away once or twice a year for a week or so.

DayInLife: My family wakes up early in the morning at which point the puppy will be let out of the crate and taken outside on leash to get busy. He will then have his meal and socialization time. I would walk him and then head to school around 10 (first period is a free block) at which point one of my parents is typically home. I return from school at 3:30, having allowed the puppy to have some crate time while I was gone so that my return would equal a walk a play, and taking him out to the nearest town where sidewalks, people, and distracts are present. I am very active, I love going out for hikes and being outdoors, as well as interacting with friends. We have an older dog, so a wild puppy would not be great, but one who would be able to go to soccer and football games with me and be okay walking in the woods and meeting new people. My weekends are always unscheduled so they are the most flexible. A male puppy is definitely preferred, and a yellow lab would also great based on past experience with the differing mannerisms.  I will be going to college next fall, so my mom and I are going to be sharing responsibility so that he will respond to her when I leave in 12 months.

DayInLife: I've shared my schedule so I just quickly recap here.  I work a 9-5 job with flexibility to take leave and also work from home.  I plan to take leave the first weeks of the puppy's arrival and then work from home.  I also live close enough to get home during the lunch break.  My plan is to bring the puppy to work once I have confidence he/she can be successful.      We live in a converted town home (used to be one town home -- now it is four separate units (terrace level, first floor, second, and third)).  We are on the third floor (walk-up).  We have only a few neighbors that make up our building.  We live in Dupont which from what I can tell is a very pet friendly neighborhood.  Folks will not be surprised or annoyed of dogs.      Weekends are low key.  We have a car and like to go see places during the weekend.  I like to be outdoors.  I am someone who is very  active when there is a purpose.  I    From what I know of at this moment, there are no upcoming life changes.      I am very excited for my first pup!!

DayInLife: There are currently eight members of our family: my husband and me, three kids (one each in college, high school, and middle school), two cats, and a snail. Our schedule during the school year goes like this--I wake up at 5:30, feed cats and lounge til 6:30 or so (this is an hour I can spend with puppy!); I leave the house around 8 for work; Jerry and kids get up around 7 and leave for school between 7:15 and 7:30; Jerry returns home from school drop off and then leaves for work around 9:45( a window of two hours or so to help with puppy) he returns for lunch at 12 or 1 for 45 min; Gracie gets home from school around 3 and Joey around 4. Jerry gets home at 4:30 and I'm usually home somewhere between 6 and 8 (but a pup might be incentive to leave earlier!). Sunday mornings our schedule is church from 8:30 til 12:30 so we may need to adjust that for the first few months or so.   We have basically no experience with dogs. I have never owned a dog and this last day with Lil has been so enlightening and enjoyable! Jerry grew up with dogs but never had one on a leash before Lil. She is so docile and friendly. I've been really impressed with how well Gracie has handled Lil. I think she's going to do a great job with a puppy.  I wrote the info for our cat vet above. I'm happy to use whatever vet you recommend.   With this being Amy's first year at college, we will need to travel to Pittsburgh a few times. We would love to bring pup but it may be better to leave with a sitter the first few times. After the trip at the end of August we don't have plans to be away other than the college trips.

GeneralComments: Mathias is a CHALLENGE! He came to us at about 4 months old with some rather bad habits (jumping, not coming, not responding to his name, and treating my teenage boys like chew toys). He has improved in the two or three months that we have had him, but he is still not an easy pup.   He appears to me to be rather insecure with new experiences - though he does improve with time and repeated exposure. He is highly reactive and this is getting worse lately. If I know someone is arriving, I can keep him focused and quiet, but if someone comes in the house unannounced or knocks on the door, Mathias erupts. He is also starting to bark at noises outside or even occasionally in the house. We do the best we can to redirect and get him focused, but it is not easy. His dog reactivity is getting worse as well. He is not aggressive at all, but highly reactive and barky when he sees another dog.  When out in public - interestingly - Mathias is very good. He is quiet and generally well mannered. I just started taking him into stores briefly and took him to church for the first time this past weekend. He was restless, but did better than I thought he would.  Overall, I find Mathias to be a rather odd mix of insecure, but bull headed and tenacious at the same time.

DayInLife: I am recently retired from education, as a special educator and administrator, and am currently substituting from 7:30-3:00 on some days with special needs students . We rise at 5:30 am and walk our current Australian Labradoodle (mini) Hannah Grace at this time for 45 minutes to an hour around downtown Westport. I leave the house at 7:15, my husband leaves the house at 8:00 am. I can arrive home for lunch at 11:00 a.m. (This is flexible, as I have someone who can let the dog out with some play time midday) Following my workday, I typically arrive home at 3:10 and on some days run errands with Hannah Grace who is  quite good in the car and settles when waiting between errands. I might visit the library or the gym or grocery store or visit a friend. We eat dinner between 5:30 and 6:30 typically. I attend Book Club once a week on Wednesdays and Guide Dog Training on Thursdays. On the weekends, we continue our morning walks in addition to a Sunday morning beach walk at Compo Beach in Westport where dogs are allowed off-leash in the off-season. I tutor a student twice a month who is fearful of dogs. Hannah Grace attends the session with me. In the summer, I co-teach a Literacy for Dog Lovers camp session at my home for 8-10 children (grades 1-6) for mornings over the course of two weeks. There are visiting dogs and guest speakers (Guiding Eyes!). The purpose of the camp is to help children develop their knowledge of dogs and understand the relationship they can have with a dog. Some children are fearful of dogs, are recent puppy owners, or are planning to get a puppy. Some of the children are special needs children. Hannah Grace is a Therapy Dog registered with the Good Dog Foundation and is scheduled to attend Read to Rover as well as anticipated visits to Silver Hill Hospital in New Canaan.   We are very flexible on our weekends, usually hanging around the house and engaging in yardwork, gardening, and beachwalking . Our son who has Downs Syndrome lives with two roommates independently in Norwalk and we usually visit at some point over the weekend and bring the dog as they are dog lovers. We have raised 6 Golden Retrievers in addition to Hannah Grace, the last of whom passed on a year ago.   We live in  a house, within walking distance to town, that has a small fenced in area in the backyard behind the garden and patio. We do not take our dogs to the front yard and they are not allowed outdoors alone. We have many friends with nice dogs and periodically will have one stay with us overnight. (Golden Retriever, Australian Shepherd, larger Australian Labradoodle.)  We will be going on a vacation for one week in March and a second week in August. We typically take our dog in August. We have  our youngest son in college currently, and our middle son lives locally, all dog lovers.   I am working currently to explore my next career passion, with the intention of it including dogs and children. (One of my main goals is to be able to bring my dog to my workplace!) Because I am retired, I intend for my work to be part time.

GeneralComments: Jude is a sweet boy and likely intelligent given his ease and willingness in learning new commands and his demand barking while kenneled.  He is the eleventh dog we have raised for GEB and the first to defecate in his kennel not due to illness (5 times as compared to say Omaha who had diarrhea due to Giardia). Jude will urinate in his kennel within 30 minutes of having been allowed to get busy and has indoor accidents when he gets excited. He seems very immature and highly distracted around getting busy. As a result, we do not consider him housebroken at 5 months. He did very well on his puppy sits and accompanied his two puppy sit handlers to work where they reported that he settled nicely and did not have accidents while with them at work but they also took him out frequently and never left him alone. They also reported that he barked a lot when put in his kennel in their homes (keeping one poor couple up at night) and that he had accidents at home which improved over time (both sitters had no other dogs in the home). We have learned that he cannot concentrate on getting busy unless on leash and away from the other older dogs. Despite being kenneled within two feet and in sight of the other dogs in their kennels, he barks every time he is kenneled. While he settles down after a while (receiving rewards and treats when quiet) he still has accidents. This has been a time suck for us (regular cleaning and deoderizing of the kennel tray) and has made us rather distrust him in the house (we have taken up some rugs to avoid soiling). Despite being taken out very frequently (sometimes about every hour if he has been playing or waking from sleep), he still has accidents. He will not be allowed to work indoors for another month at least.  Jude returned last week at puppy class from his last sit highly distracted and pulling badly on leash although the sitters said he had been easy to handle. It took half the class to get his attention, and even then he was highly distracted by smells. Due to his being bitten by a copperhead this weekend, the raiser had to keep his leash time to a minimum and has not had much opportunity to refresh his leash manners.  While we were once resolved to return him to GEB, we have decided that his sweet temperament; ability to settle calmly when alone and undistracted; and willingness to work trump the frustration of his extremely unreliable habits of elimination. We will also overlook our disappointment that like Omaha he seems cow-hocked and unlikely to be considered for stud even if we were to ensure he made his IFT. You know, having raised two broods, we'd really like to have a stud or two and some more grandpuppies to raise ... Sigh.  We think over time he will prove to be a sound dog and if medically fit then temperamentally able to handle the demands of working.

GeneralComments: Fay is a very pleasant dog to have around. She is low energy until you ask her to "perform" and then she stays right with you. She has bonded very closely to me (her primary handler) and takes some of her confidence from mine. Because of this attachment, she can become upset when I leave her. She will bark until/unless she is distracted from my leaving. She is very sweet and people oriented. She loves to play with other dogs and is usually very respectful of them. She also enjoys keeping herself occupied with her toys. She has great house manners and I have left her alone (out of the crate) on numerous occasions with much success. On outings she is very well-behaved and I can trust her anywhere.

DayInLife: 4:40AM get up, throw on some clothes to allow me to take the pup out for "get busy" (gb) - if weather allows, do 15 min. of outdoor training or go for a short walk. 5:15 do my own exercise and some indoor training with the pup. 6 AM prepare our meals and feed pup. 6:20 morning devotions then finish getting ready for work -- pup stays with me as I brush my teeth and finish getting dressed. Leave pup with my husband who will walk him to gb, exercise him with a game of fetch on a long tether. If my husband has to go out the pup will go into his kennel with a toy, if not the pup will have some kennel time during the day to just rest. 3PM when I come from school, I take the pup for a walk, visit neighbor's dog for a playtime, relax with the pup. 6PM dinner for us and the pup and another walk/training time. Relax together for the evening. Last gb at 9PM and into bed.

DayInLife: On weekdays, I get up at 7:30, shower, dress, take my dog out to get busy, feed him and myself and go to work at 8:45.  I come home for lunch from 12 to 1 to eat and walk the dog.  After work I either come straight home at 5 or go to the gym and then come home around 6:30.  I live in a 3 story townhouse with a small back yard in a suburban neighborhood.  I have a 5 year old Golden Retriever that I raised from a puppy.  His house manners are good, although he does beg for bananas and that's my fault.  I usually take 2 one week vacations a year when I go out of town and kennel my dog.  I enjoy the outdoors and take my dog with me on day hikes during the summer and snowshoeing in winter.

GeneralComments: Jenny has grown in confidence and energy level. She is testing both me and the other dogs. She is no pushover. She is very smart and is a thinker and problem solver. However, what she considers a problem is not always what I consider a problem. It is fun to watch her wheels turn. She thinks she can talk and tries her best to communicate with me. She is very connected and tuned in.    The major thing we are working on is having her settle while I disconnect from her. She would prefer to keep moving, and if we arenÆt moving that I at least engage her and feed her treats. She considers æsettlingÆ a problem that she would like to fix. She is making good progress though. She is now letting me sit and disconnect without doing all kinds of behaviors to get my attention. She still doesnÆt lay down and settle for long without getting ansy, but itÆs a process.     Jenny walks well in all environments and shows good confidence. She is fabulous with noises and has very low small animal distractions. She is great around other dogs and children. She is observant and pays attention to her environment. IÆm very excited about Jenny because she has some real potential to be a fabulous guide.

KennelCommandComments: She only responds to "kennel up" when someone is pointing from her nose to the kennel

HousemannersComments: Has improved greatly in the last two months
LeftUnattendedComments: We haven't ever tried this. I was under the impression she was never to be left alone outside of her crate
PlaybiteComments: Hasn't play bit anyone or any clothes in months
StealFoodComments: She will sniff from a foot or so away, but won't eat it even if you put people food in front of her face and leave it there. Takes lots of effort to introduce new treats that are also people food (like cheese)
OnFurnitureComments: Used to be a constant issue, but is improving. When she's feeling really good, she likes to show off.
BarksExcessivelyComments: Has been very good until recently, Barked during class at Jason (GS pup). I don't remember her ever barking at another dog, though she may have when she was very little.
RaidsGarbageComments: Unless she sees tissues, she'll stay away from the garbage. We have a swing top on the only garbage she can see anyway, so it's not a constant probleml.
JumpsComments: There are certain people she'll jump up on, but they're always people she knows. She jumps on our neighbor, but our neighbor also encourages it to a certain extent. She doesn't jump on strangers, even when they get in her face and get excited.
FriendlyWAnimalsComments: She loves animals more than anything else. She and one of our cats sleep side by side.
KidsComments: Loves children, knows to be more gentle around them even when they're riled up.
StrangerComments: Close 2nd to animals
WalkingComments: LLW is off and on a battle with Joyce. Some days she'll LLW very well, others she can't seem to hold a connection. Example - At Applefest last weekend she was a great LLWalker, on Monday at class she was pulling in every direction. There were strange dogs and people at both.
GetBusyComments: Always goes when and where Bryan tells her to. In the last week and a half she hasn't been listening to me (Rebecca) about getting busy.
EliminateRouteComments: In the last week and a half she has been eliminating #2 on walks. This may be related to her back legs. We think it might be hurting her to go #2.
ChaseComment: Mostly doesn't chase after the cats. Once every couple of weeks she chases them,
TrafficComments: Always looks to her handler when a truck or car comes by.
NoiseComments: Can shake a coffee tin full of coins while she's doing drills and she doesn't even bat an eye.
StairsComments: Joyce has some problems with stairs, which we think is related to her leg problems. It's hard to work on stairs often because of how often she's on crate rest.
SitComments: Most of the time listens and obeys. She does sit slowly because of her legs.
DownComments: She'll go to down quickly unless it's very unpleasant (hot cement, really cold cement, etc)
StayComments: Still improving. She stays very well at home even when I hide behind things. Currently working on this outside of the home.
ComeOnLeashComments: Sometimes she comes, sometimes she doesn't. It depends on what's going on.
ComeOffLeashComments: She'll run to me (Rebecca) as fast as she can.
PillsComments: We use them as treats. She loves her medicine.
EarsComments: I've never cleaned her ears before. At the pre-puppy meeting Russ said that raisers gave more ear infections to their dogs when they tried, and we don't want to add any mroe problems to Joyce's list.
NailsComments: She lays down still for it. If you take more than 5 minutes, she gets antsy.
GeneralComments: She didn't behave very well at the first pack 2 class she attended (October 4). Lately she has been doing well at pack 1. She attends whichever class happens to be on a day she's not limping. We did a home switch with Bishop last weekend. Carolyn said that she was very good. When Joyce first went in for a medical evaluation she stayed with the Fuller family (who foster broods Babe and Mia). Mrs. Fuller gave Joyce glowing reviews about her 2 week stay there. She has also been to Karen Seifert's home for 2 nights, but that was when she was only a few months old. I'd like her to go on more overnights or home switches, but her constant need to be on crate rest really interferes with that.

ExerciseType: walks, hikes, play w/ other dogs
ExericeAmount: varies from minimal (few get busy walks/day) to 1-2 hours/day depending on work schedule and weather
ChewingComments: 3+/4 work in progress but improving with age, still occas chews papers
HousemannersComments: age appropriate
LeftUnattendedComments: 3+/4 age appropriate - see # 50 & 54
StealFoodComments: ? about how to score: has never been given opportunity to steal food when with me - starting to work on setups to challenge her
OnFurnitureComments: 3+/4 on 2 different occasions climbed onto easy chair and couch in other raisers' homes. I haven't observed this behavior at my home yet.
BarksExcessivelyComments: occasionally barks at sounds outside house & car (eg. wind, voices), on rare occasion will bark a few times at another dog or unusual person
RaidsGarbageComments: 3+/4: much improved but not perfect - occas. takes things out of bathroom trash basket at home and office trash basket at work when I am not present, so I have managed it by not allowing access unless I am present to observe it. None of my dogs have ever been allowed access to kitchen trash basket in my home - I think it is asking for trouble.
FriendlyWAnimalsComments: Is good on the other side of fence from horses, is friendly and gently mouths my cat and is less preoccupied with her, but still occas. will chase, and often whines at her - I assume frustration because she won't play. Interacts and plays appropriately with many dogs (usually older and more experienced dogs) but is highly aroused by movement, and has been inappropriate with some dogs (will assume dominant posture over them, growl and grab neck, and doesn't respond to food in face/call out. Have been working hard on callouts/comes around other things that excite and interest her, but need help with managing dog play interactions.
KidsComments: Children interest and excite her (movement) but she has been doing well with supervised interactions on & off leash in quiet calm places
StrangerComments: I haven't seen any unfriendliness - will occas. alert bark but has always been successful with approach and meet & greet when opportunity to do so.
GetBusyComments: winter's icy conditions has made this a little challenging
ChaseComment: 3+/4 Her interest in movement has all of us working very hard on recalls in arousing situations and she is doing well with her training
EarsComments: Has had minimal wax in ears
GeneralComments: 1) Moxie has had excellent health since the day she left the CDC. Other than 2 brief cystitis/urethritis episodes when younger which responded immediately to antibiotics, she has had no health issues. Her stools have been perfect, 1st on Purina Lg Breed Puppy Chow, and now on Purina ProPlan Lamb & Rice. She has never missed a meal!  2) Lots of body handling & massage, wearing tank tops and then the longer puppy coats for eating, playing, bone-chewing, hanging out, etc.  seem to have helped with much of her body sensitivity, though she will still occasionally briefly turn to nose her apparel or stop to scratch at it briefly (1 to a few seconds).  3) She has a pleasant energy level and can readily settle in any environment I have exposed her to, loves to work, appears to love and have endless energy for learning & for rising to new challenges in skills, activities, and environmental exposures. She is motivated by handler praise & interaction, food, toys, go sniff command, and many life rewards.  4) She has extremely quick reactions which makes teaching her easy, but also can work to her detriment if she thinks she should be in charge. While action and movement excite and arouse her, for the most part she can split attention and resume/maintain focus on the handler and the activity or work ay hand. She will respond readily to direction in almost all situations so far with the exception of some dog interactions I have described above - I understand she may be making her best guess/choice at behavior, but I would like help with teaching her better choices if that is at all possible. Having expressed that concern, I can also say that she is quick to lower her arousal and work with me offering requested behaviors at a relatively short distance as well as to appear to relax very nicely with massage. I am not sure whether this inappropriate play arises from being single female with six male sibs, whether estrogen effect after 1st heat will be beneficial, or whether she is uncertain with some dogs and wants to settle or dominate the action - and maybe none of that makes a difference.   5) Moxie is overall a lovely, fun pup to raise and have around. She is teaching me a lot and is giving me and her other 2 raisers, Maura Cornish and Ellen Joseph, much pleasure in the process.

GeneralComments: Saxon is a very pleasant dog!  Very attentive to handler and eager to please. FoodType: Science Diet Lamb and Rice Adult
ExerciseType: walks 3+ miles a day, plays in backyard and in home, and with GEB pups in tennis courts
JumpsComments: getting better - he will jump on people he knows very well

GeneralComments: In March he went to Virginia and was amazing with the long car ride, my Aunt's 190 pound St. Bernard, fire alarms, the hotel, traveling to museums and going to restaurants! This past week we were house/farm sitting and he was able to get closer to the horses then the last time we watched the property and he didnt bark or growel at them this time! He also lived through his first tornado experience, he was paniced and worried with the wind blowing against the house (we were in a very old home), but calmed down when we got to safety. He even alerted me to a wild snake in the room we were in and was cool and collected while i screamed and freaked out because of it being in the house (I have a really bad fear of them).

GeneralComments: Floyd is a powerful pup; He enjoys working with handler but needs to limit sessions to small slices to avoid increase in his stress level. He is easily aroused, and tends to be very olfactory in new environments. Once he is familar thru repeated exposure, he will reduce amount of sniffing and drooling... He has a sensitive side, and is reachable, but needs time to take in things slowly with repeated exposure prior to moving on. Initially uncomfortable with new experiences at times. He has shown improvement during his time here, and his ability to handle the environment in a relaxed manner is improving over time :)

FoodType: Nature's Select Chicken, Lamb, and Rice
NailsComments: Cut one nail short, so he doesn't like it anymore.  Working on it with him.
DayInLife: Typically, I get up at 7 am, get dressed, and go to my home office to work from about 7:30 am to 5 pm and have lunch around 11 am - noon.  Then I have dinner at 5 pm and watch tv or participate in activities until about 10 or 11 pm when I go to bed.  Weekends are fairly open with not many set events, except for church Sunday mornings from 8 am - 10 am.  In order to meet the needs of a puppy, I plan to make full use of the flexible work at home schedule I have.  I will probably get up earlier and work with the puppy in the morning.  Additionally, I will try to take some breaks during my work schedule to work with the puppy.  Since I work from home in one of the rooms, I will sometimes have the puppy in the room with me.

GeneralComments: Crystal is doing very well, and pretty much goes everywhere with me. She loves work and class, and does very well at the greetings as long as the greeter stays calm. If the greeter gets excited her bottom almost always comes up. Auto settling is going well, she is much quicker and stays settled better when I'm standing vs when I'm sitting. The closer I am to the ground the worse she gets. She does do better when she has the blue jacket on...probably because I'm accepting less bad behavior. I have some personal life decisions coming up and so would like to talk about possible evaluation times for her.
