HealthComments: 2 ear infections
ExerciseType: 3 walks/day (~40mins. each), free play 30 minutes, ~2 training session (~15/min. each)
EliminationCrateComments: wet his crate, 3 months ago, @ a puppy sitter
CrateQuietComments: He will is quiet at my house, at sitters or new places he will bark
KennelCommandComments: Sometimes he will run in before I say kennel, this is almost always my fault because I didn't tell him to sit first
LeftUnattendedComments: He doesn't get into trouble on his own (chewing,etc.), but he follows me ALL over the house and would rather not be alone.  He will wake up from a nap and follow me.  Atleast I won't ever lose him in the house! Often I try working with him by shutting the door behind me and praising him when I return (he doesn't bark at this time....he just waits at the door).
PlaybiteComments: When playing with him he usually does very well with this, but he will forget on occasion, he never hurts anyone but I still stop play if I see this behavior.
BarksExcessivelyComments: At puppy-sitter and in new places he will bark in his crate. At my house, he barely barks.  I don't remember the last time he has barked at my house.
CountersDoorsComments: He will sniff the kitchen table, now that he is tall enough to, but he has never jumped onto it or gotten any food off of the table.
JumpsComments: He is quite excitable, if he does get really excitable he sometimes will jump on people
FriendlyWAnimalsComments: He never growls or bites, but rather is so excited when he sees an animal that he sometimes will scare them.  He has now been socialized with cats and does well with them (does not chase them, but sometimes licks them more than most cats prefer).  If they run away he does sometime try to follow.
KidsComments: He has gotten most of this experience at sitters, but when on walks and a child wants to pet him, he usually is very well behaved.  The only problem he seems to have is avoiding licking sticky fingers and faces.
StrangerComments: He may be too friendly with strangers.  Depending on their dispostion when they pet him often dictates his excitement lever, I often have to keep these pets quite short to get Dandy to maintain his sit.
WalkingComments: Dandy has gotten so much better!!  He will still pull a times, at which I use his partial choker.  He will still randomly get distracted (leaves, other animals, excited people, food on the ground), but does really well in crowds and much better at keeping his head up :)  I still want him to get much better than he is, but I am happy in the progression thus far.
GetBusyComments: Even off leash!
EliminateRouteComments: This is usually my fault, because I may have forgotten to led him use the bathroom before leaving for a walk.
ChaseComment: I still has to put him in a sit when he sees an animal.  He will maintain the sit, but if he isn't asked to sit he trys leaning and pulling in that direction.
TrafficComments: Doesn't finch.
NoiseComments: Hillsborough St. has taken care of that.
SitComments: He knows this well but will not maintain it for as long as I would like him too.
DownComments: |4||3|Recalls are difficult when there are distractions (especially when it is food)|3|When in the yard, he will ignore me sometime when I call him, yet he usually does come quickly.|5||5||5||5|5|4|4|2 overnights (a. 1 weeks, b. 4 nights)|He barks at the puppy-sitters, I need suggestions on what to do for this.  At times he sleeps well close to the other dogs and at other times he will bark at them.  Using a sheet over the kennel usually helps.   I would also like to work on swapping Dandy between people and get some more suggestions on this (Laura and I work on this after every class for ~30 minutes).  We are making some advancements but I wanted to see if you had any other tips.   I look forward to the eval and the help!  Thanks!
DayInLife: At the time that I will be getting the puppy, the only responsibility that I will have other than to train and take care of the dog is to work for about 20 hours a week.  I have already cleared it with my boss that I can take the puppy with me to work.    Once school starts in the fall, I will be responsible to go to classes.  My course load is to be rather light during the semester, with adequate breaks to spend time with the dog throughout the day.  I look forward to taking the dog with me to class sometime later in the semester.

FoodType: Iams Minichunks Proactive Health, green bag
HealthComments: On 3rd regimen of Cephalexin for facial Acne.
StoolComments: sometimes a bit soft at end.
ExerciseType: Long walks; on long leash in back yard running after frisbee or ball; jog around block with Papa when I'm at work; occasional romping with other GEB dogs when we get together.
EliminationCrateComments: Only had a couple accidents of urine.
CrateQuietComments: Has started to bark in crate if he's in crate when people are in the house( sometimes even when someone gets up in the night to go to the bathroom)
ChewingComments: Will chew the inside of Keith's slippers if he gets ahold of them.

LeftUnattendedComments: We don't leave Manny unattended, so not sure how he'd do.

BarksExcessivelyComments: See #35
RaidsGarbageComments: Is improving on this. Eileen helped us with how to work on this with Manny.
CountersDoorsComments: Same as above.

SitComments: Knows the command, but sometimes now there's  a delay in obeying the command.
StayComments: Will break his stay if I go out of his sight.
ComeOnLeashComments: Does well with this. If very high distraction(like another dog), Manny have a bit of difficulty coming to me:)!
ComeOffLeashComments: We only would do inside. (We don't have Manny off leash outside)
PillsComments: Lots of experience due to the Cephalexin :)!
NailsComments: Does well with lots of praise and rewards(food). I usually break it up into several sessions.

StrangerComments: She's never shown any fear of anyone--she loves people in general.
WalkingComments: We go for long walks and she's been great.  Is doing better with distractions.  We've been doing lots of outings in town, at the local outlet malls and a local state park.
EliminateRouteComments: Sometimes she does need to go, but she waits until i find an appropriate spot and give her permission.  Then I clean it up.
ChaseComment: She shows an interest in birds, squirrels, chipmunks, bunnies--she watches them, but doesn't strain to try to chase them
StairsComments: open stairs too--grated ones.
NailsComments: She doesn't mind my handling her paws, but she isn't overly fond of clipping.

NoiseComments: will startle frombehind occasionally

EliminationHouseComments: When at puppy sitter last two times, Savannah pooped in sitter's house
JumpsComments: Will jump on instructors and other raisers at puppy class.
WalkingComments: Walks well on lead with me during exposures, doesn't always walk well on lead at puppy class.
EliminateRouteComments: Pooped in Home Depot, issue resolved additional opportunities to get busy before entering location.
NoiseComments: Generally unafraid, startle reflex diminishing but does get startled occasionally at sudden loud noise.  Doesn't bolt.  Alerts and looks around.
DayInLife: Parenting including participating in my childrens' daily lives and activities. Complete household chores.  Work from home office.  Visit clients.   I will meet the puppy's needs by serving as the raiser, follow GEB guidelines, obtain and schedule medical advice, groom, feed, play with, socialize, and attend class and activities with the pup.

ExerciseType: Either walk or run with me. Other days taken to a fenced in area to play fetch etc.
ExericeAmount: Averages to about 3 hours of outdoor play/walks a day.
CrateQuietComments: Will bark in the mornings when he wakes up to go outside and occassionally in the middle of the night.  Once I take him outside, he usually always goes to the bathroom and goes right back to sleep in his crate when we return inside.
ChewingComments: Will grab a shoe or other inappropriate object to chew occassionally.
HousemannersComments: Doesn't go into the garbage or jump on counters etc.  I continue to work on his "stealing" of things that are not his toys.
StealFoodComments: Would occassionally steal food off of a table at his level.  I have been working with this and he won't do it when people are watching but I'm still questioning if he would when no one is around.
BarksExcessivelyComments: This needs work.  He barks for attention a lot.
JumpsComments: He's been improving a lot but still gets VERY excited when people arrive, especially when they come into the house.
GetBusyComments: Has recently started to bark near the door as if he has to go get busy.  When I take him outside he either doesnt go or spends a lot of time outside before he eliminates.
EliminateRouteComments: Can't get him to go before we walk so he ends up going at some point since we take pretty long walks.
ChaseComment: Doesn't, but would if he had the chance.

ExerciseType: retrieve ball, run & play w/ our other dogs, walks w/ me,
CrateQuietComments: sometimes will bark loudly for up to a minute when I leave,
ChewingComments: 99% of the time she's a 5, BUT she chewed up new shirts & the hanger,  thru store bag when I tried leaving her for 10 min NOT crated
HousemannersComments: MOSTLY rates  4, but sometimes springs into spazzoid dog & pounces on other dogs, & steals their toys.  Also has occasionally jumped on people entering house.
LeftUnattendedComments: if indoors & w/ other dogs can get too rambunctious & start running & play fighting.  If outdoors, dog play must be supervised bcuz she is so easily aroused & will escalate to aggressive play quickly.  No longer allowed to play w/ more than one dog at a time.
BarksExcessivelyComments: almost never barks except when on the rare occasion when she sees our neighbor's dog outside through the fence
JumpsComments: poor self control when people enter our house.  We are working on this.
FriendlyWAnimalsComments: BIG improvement here...can sit nicely next to our Parrot now
WalkingComments: outdoors is the challenge...constant work to keep loose leash, nose off the scent of something, and PRAY we don't encounter another dog or cat
ChaseComment: fast as lightning, sees the slightest movement before I do, then BAM, she's at the end of the leash
ComeOffLeashComments: not dependably when there's a dog distraction
GeneralComments: Looking back over this, I feel like my own evaluation of Barb has been harsh.  But, these observations are accurate.  Barb is a smart dog w/ great potential.  Things that may startle or concern many dogs don't phase her, like the moving Halloween mannequins in the stores.  Self control is her biggest problem.  She's been with me ~10 wks, & is finally showing signs of being more connected w/ me. If given the choice, would still pick dogs over people.  To avoid reinforcing unwanted behavior, haven't walked her thru the neighborhood behind my home in over a month.  Continued failure. Have to work/walk in more controlled setting, where I know there will not be many visual dog distractions. Want to help her grow w/o pushing her over her threshold.  She's been one tricky girl, but a sweet, smart, & worth the work!

DayInLife: Brian - Primary Raiser  Awake 6:30am  Wife to work by 7:15am  Kyra to school by 8:30 AM  I do not work in a traditional job setting in terms of office/hours.   Primary job is stay-at-home parent (house husband , if you will).  What work that I do is from home and sporadic(catering sales/marketing)...computer/phone.  I volunteer at nearby horsestable with therapeutic riding program twice weekly.  Laundry/grocery/yard&housework/food prep.  3:45 Kyra returns    Homework most nights, sometimes trips to library. Twice monthly GScouts, weekly riding lessons.   6pm family dinner.  8pm Jen/Kyra bed  I stay up later...TV/books/work.  We live very close to Rock Creek Park and I try to walk/hike twice a week for 1-2 hrs....sometimes with the neighbors' dogs...(underexercised labs.)  Yoga class weekly.  I drive a Honda element.  The decision to to this program has taken me about two years to come to.  I find the structure (GEB requirements/classes/training and the dogs needs) to be appealing.  My days now are 7-9 hours without structure....

EliminationCrateComments: never had an accident in her crate

FriendlyWAnimalsComments: She loves everything
KidsComments: She's so tolerant of all kids
StrangerComments: She just gives strangers too many kisses

NoiseComments: Haven't seen a loud noise bother her in a while

DayInLife: As a firefighter each day is different.  We typically work 6-7 days each month.  24 hours on and 48 hours off, plus other special days off each month.    On a scheduled fire duty day I would wake up at 6:30am, get ready for work and leave at 8:00am.  My wife would meet the puppy's needs that day.    The next morning I arrive home at 9:00am and would be off for 48 hours.  This would allow me to care for the dog myself.       I would have the bulk of the daytime to train, exercise and play with the dog.

JumpsComments: People greetings are a weakness
WalkingComments: Pulls and sniffs every spot
DayInLife: Puppy will be up early, busied & fed before the kids leave for school at 6:40am.  We work from home, so the puppy will spend part of the day in my office and part of the day in John's office.  Some of that time will be in the crate and other time will be spent practicing skills at my feet while I work.  Working from home allows flexibilty to take puppy out to get busy starting every 30 minutes duing house training and then working towards fewer times a day with maturity.  Puppy will have mid-day play time and lunch.  Puppy will have more play time when the kids come home from school at 3pm. All play time will also be used to reinforce known skills.  Puppy will continue to have appropriate busy times.  Dinner will be between 6-7pm and bedtime is between 10-11pm.  Puppy will go with us to any outdoor activities like tennis or lacrosse games.  Puppy will also be taken out in the evenings to settings that are appropriate tot he puppy's ability level.  An example would be a small shopping plaza bench, or a park.

DayInLife: Currently, I am living at my home in New Jersey with my parents, sister, 2 dogs, and a cat. From New Jersey I am commuting everyday to a 10 week program Internship in New York City down by the World Trade Center. My job is 9-5 with an hour lunch break. When I arrive home around 630 I normally cook myself some dinner and relax at home for the rest of the night or go out to meet friends. When I receive my puppy, however, I will be already moved into my new house at my college, Marist in Poughkeepsie NY. I have my own room and everyone who is in my house (5 girls) is excited and anxious to meet the new puppy and help in any way they can with the process of becoming a Guide Dog. I scheduled my classes purposely in anticipation for my puppy needing a lot of my attention. I scheduled 930 AM classes so that I will have time to tend to my puppy in the morning, and then 2:00 and 3:30 classes so I have time for lunch and play time. When I am not at class I am on the executive board of the largest social group on Campus called Campus Ministry. We every last Sunday and first Monday of the month for meetings in addition to any extra fundraissing events we do on campus for local food shelters or homeless shelters. I have received the approval of my campus to allow my dog to come with me to classes and anywhere else I may need to get to (pending the pup is ready for those experiences and what the Guiding Eyes deems as acceptable places for him to be). I also am the President of Fox P.A.W.S (People for Animal Welfare Society) and this will have monthly meetings on Wednesday nights as well. On a more day to day business, after my classes (the times I have posted above are the same Monday-Thursday I have a 3 day weekend) I normally will make myself dinner at home around 530-6 and then hang out around the house or take a walk on campus down by the river. I normally go to bed around 1130-12 depending on the amount of homework I have. I have been waiting in anticipation for this puppy for so long. Everyone on my campus, including the administration, is aware that this is going to happen and are fully supportive of anything that I need or Guiding Eyes may want of them. Thank you for giving me this oppurtunity!

DayInLife: Right now I don't work so although I have lots of time to spend with the puppy my schedule is somewhat inconsistent from day to day.  The things that are always the same are:    6:00 wake, shower  6:30 - 7:30 wake kids, breakfast, get kids to school  8:00 - Exercise (gym, walk etc)  12:30 Lunch  2:30 pick kids up from school  3:00 snacks & homework  6:00 dinner  7:00 - 10:00  reading, computer, tv, games  10:00/11:00 bed  The remainder of my days are filled with a variety of things depending on the weather and the day:  volunteer work at schools a few times a week (2 hrs)  Grocery shopping  General shopping  Gardening  cleaning  errands  dr appointments  sporting events - soccer, frisbee,swimming, squash  entertaining  we live on a lake so much of our free time is spent at the beach.  There is typically someone home for a good portion of everyday.  My husband often works from home.  Our household is typically quiet and routine.  We have a 12 year old lab that I expect will get along just fine with a new puppy.  I don't think there will be any problems meeting the puppy's needs.

StrangerComments: too friendly!!  Working on this
GeneralComments: In our oppinion Klute is highly intelligence and easily trainable.... however, he has a tendenciy to overfraternize with other dogs and some people.  He has had an extremely hard time learning to sit when encountering people and has missed out on opportunities due to this.  We have had to turn and walk away when it is clear that both he and the other party would enjoy getting together.   Given the chance to observe the situation first and when people do not approach him or make direct eye contact he does much, much better.   Also, Klute is a sniffer. When on hard surfaces or indoors he is learning...but on grass he wants to concentrate on smells if allowed.  Working on this every day.   You can see him trying to work out the issues.  He is a very sweet, friendly dog but still is a bit puppy like.  .
DayInLife: Earler risers.  2 hours before work.  George (other helf of the team) is retired and home most of the day.  Home by 5:30  Dinner is at 7:00  reading/TV 8:00 -11:00

DayInLife: I work full-time from 9-5pm, M-F.   Currently, I work in the office on Monday, Tuesday, Thursday and Friday and work from home on Wednesdays.  However, I have the flexibility to work from home whenever needed.  Our weekend schedule includes activities for our kids (sports and choir lessons-- all nearby and not very lengthy).  I live in a suburban neighborhood with my husband and 3 kids (12, 9 & 7).  We have a sitter who is home with our kids at 3pm on Tuesdays/Thursdays.  She is enthusiastic about GEB and has always had dogs growing up.  She is available to help us with the puppy on days that I cannot work from home.  She will be home with our kids full time, M-F, from early June through the end of August.  We have 1 vacation planned in August.  2 of the other families in our pre-placement class are family friends, so we look forward to going through this experience together.  We have no experience with puppies.  We previously had a cat as a pet for over a decade.

DayInLife: My life is pretty laid back,  I attend college classes on Monday and Wednesday until end of April.  I intend on integrating the puppy into the college atmosphere as soon as possible.  My classes are from 10:45 AM - 4PM, which consists of three classes and I do have time to run home and let him get busy, play and feed him between.  The rest of the week I usually get up around 7:30 and I'm not working right now so I have plenty of time to raise and educate the puppy.  I usually go to bed around 11PM but have had puppies in the past and willing to get up in the middle of the night with him.  My children are grown and live out-of-state, so I live by myself, however, do have an emergency back up to let the puppy  "Get Busy" if needed, with a quick phone call. I really don't have any health, physical restrictions or ailments to speak of, pretty healthy!

JumpsComments: At time will jump up when he first meets someone
StayComments: Depends on amount of stimulis around.
GeneralComments: Is a very gentle pup. No aggression at all. Loves to play and interact with other dogs.  In my opinion is a bit slow in maturing mentally. In the past few weeks have seen him increase his attention span, and maintining his focus on handler.  With the exception of three bouts of pano, he has been a very healthy pup.  Loves to be with people. He is extremely good in his crate in the house. Gets along very well with family dogs, "respecting their food bowls, and not poaching"  Our small family dog can climb all over him, even when sleeping and it does not phase him.  He has been a vocal pup since we first got him, but that is improving, but not totally resolved. Does bark at unfamiliar dogs.  He does not sniff the ground excessively. Very solid on all types of flooring, surfaces, stairs, and in elevators. Does very well when boarding and exiting public transit busses, and rides very well in cars. Does well around shopping carts, and disabled persons in wheelchairs. Does well in shopping malls, with his focus increasing as he ages.

GeneralComments: Christy is beginning to display good maturity at home and on outings.  She recognizes that she's going out somewhere special when we pull out the GEB Jacket.  She responds very well to all commands in all settings, and is increasing with her confidence at the Mall, the Train Station, the grocery store, and on our walks.  We've introduced her to the children play ground and she is showing confidence in negotiating various obstacles.  She plays wonderfully with other dogs, never growls / bites / mounts other dogs.  Always with a toy playing keep away or chase games.  We've also used a local fenced in tennis court to teach commands off the leash, which she is responding to very well.  Christy has the best temperment of any large size dog, I've owned.

GeneralComments: Gemma went to sitters for a week in Jan. She participated in a 2-wee exchange in Jn-Feb. Then she went to sitters for 2 weeks in Feb.
DayInLife: My work is relatively flexible. I usually leave the house around 8:15 and can come back for lunch at noon (I should be able to take more breaks when the pup is younger). I can work from home two full days of the week or do half days at home. Usually we are back home around 4 and then leave for a couple of hours to take my kids to afternoon/evening activites most days. The family is very active. We do some sort of sport or exercise several days a week. We have an indoor/outdoor cat which is very friendly to people but has never seen/interacted with a dog. We take about two or three vacations a year that range from one to two weeks. During the winter we spend weekends skiing/hiking. During the summers we spent most weekends in our boat. While we leave in a relatively rural area (we have conservation land in two sides of our house), we leave just a couple of miles from the center of town and about 30 min from Boston.

GeneralComments: When I first got Sean, he did not come when called, would bolt out door if someone opened it.  He was very excitable and hard to control,  Since he has had the pinch collar he has calmed down alittle.  He walks with a loose lease and is very good with the people greeting when he has the collar on.  I have walked him around my yard without the collar and he still pulls alittle but nothing like he did before.  He comes now when he is called  stays in different positions until called.  He is able to settle much better than when he first came to me.  He is very good with my 13 yr old lab.

ExerciseType: 1 mile in the morning and evening
BarksExcessivelyComments: he demand barks at times
DayInLife: I live with my husband and twins (age 17) in a small town in ct.  We live in a house and have a nice yard.  We love dogs.  We all get involved in raising our previous GEB dog, tilden.  We have learned a lot.  We love pup sitting.  i get up at 6am and I used to walk Tilden.  He would eat and then we would play.  I would go to work.  I come home at lunch to do errands.  Sometimes I work from home.  The kids get come home from HS at 1:30.    We eat dinner around 6:30.  In the evening, i used to walk Tilden or we would go to malls.  If the kids miss the school bus, or need  a ride, Tilden would come.  If I went to work off hours Tilden would come.  we took Tilden camping with us.  The weekends are walks, outdoors time.  During the holidays we would have people over and Tilden would mingle.  It was funny even people who did not like dogs felt ok with Tilden around.  Hope this helps.

DayInLife: Both my husband and I are retired, so our typical day is not really "typical", but more flexible.  We do attend church services on Sunday mornings (approx. 3 hrs.) and Wednesday nights (approx. 2 hrs.), and both of these commitments are flexible.  We interact a lot with grandchildren; birthdays, gymnastics, sports events, etc. -- all of which are flexible.  There are no health problems that would make puppy raising difficult.       We plan on making this puppy a member of our family, and will do all that is required to meet the ultimate objective, that being to raise a future guide dog.

DayInLife: I currently have a very flexible schedule. I teach after school art classes in the evenings and I am usually only gone about 3 hours for that. During that time my husband often comes home from work and could work with the dog. Our weekends are usually relaxed. We would definitely have time to take the dog out for socialization trips. We some times go down to Richmond, Virginia, where both of our parents live, on some weekends but we would be able to bring the dog with us for that. It is possible that I will be getting another part-time job for the mornings. If I do get the job I would be able to take the dog out before I leave for work and come home for lunch. My husband does travel occasionally for work but we have planned for me to be the primary trainer. He will always go to the classes ect. with me that he will be home for. We also just found out that he is going to be sent to Australia in November and I would like to go with him. If I am able to go with him we would be gone for 2-3 weeks. We are very excited about being puppy raisers and are prepared to take it very seriously :)

GeneralComments: On one sit became afraid of crate and would not go in. Resolved once he was home. On same sit, he was afraid on the stairs at first(long,15, steep wooden), but by the end of the sit, he was going up and down all 3 flights with ease. House manners have been an issue. Have been receiving extra help and things are improving.
DayInLife: Work as a physical therapist at a hospital 1-2 days week. If working more than one day a week, the other day is Sat. when my husband is able to be home with the puppy. I have a 25 year old daughter (she hopes to move out in the next 6-12 months) who works at night, sleeps during the day when she comes home, but gets up to take the dogs out at noon or so to get busy and to have some play time when I work during the week. I have a 21 year old daughter who comes home from college during the summer and has helped with a previous puppy. I didn't work much when I first got my other puppies as I have a flex position and am able to choose my days of availability. We live in a split-foyer home on .4 acre on a neighborhood through street, not overly busy. There are no sidewalks on our street, but there are some ~ 1/4 mile away. I attend a Bible study on Tues. mornings and then work for about an hour in the church office. I go to a 2 hour choir practice on Wed. evenings. Sunday morning we go to Sunday school and church. Once the other GEB puppies that we have had have been housebroken, we have started to take them to these events so that they have learned to settle quietly for long periods of time. Most of my days are relatively unstructured. My husband works 4 10 hour days/ week. We have 4 other families that we get together with every month with children ranging from 8 years up to adulthood. I like to take walks. We enjoy camping and kayaking. I have family 5 hours away that we travel to for the major holidays.

GeneralComments: Wendy did well with Dominion's Gingham at an outreach program involving 1st grade class. She could use more time around children.  We've enjoyed raising Wendy because she is bright, energetic gal. Wendy recently came into heat and during the last month we experienced increase awareness to sounds especially at night and overall excitement. Required us to use patience and wait for her to respond at times.  That said, at times when she becomes excited, she self-modulates which is very cool.      She can be olfactory including mild air scenting especially walking in small towns where dogs have eliminated on every object.  Increase use of you, faster pace, high value rewards somewhat help.  Her level of comfort on stairs has improved. Wendy prefers to move out and continue to work on "settle" in different situations that can be of challenge to her (Mall).  Began taking Wendy inside a grocery store last month, going fine.

DayInLife: Spouse leaves for work about 7 am.  Before that, our other dog is fed and walked, and the 2 cats fed.  I am now home most of the day.  Twice during workweek visit father in assisted living, days can vary..but gone about 3 hours on those days, usually tues and thurs.. There are the usual errands and work on computer during day.  Live close to Clarendon which is very dog friendly, so lots of places for socialization. We live in a house with a fenced backyard...neighborhood very dog friendly, but unfortunately that means some walk their dogs without a lead...some of our streets have sidewalks, and some do not.  Our cats are of the "in your face" variety..one in particular follows me about quite a bit, has swatted at dog a couple of times which was all that was necessary for this dog.  The other one does play and run (usually in the evening) despite their older ages. The cats did adapt to the greyhound with no problem. The dog sleeps in her bed when not being walked or fed or played with...very docile, so much so that it will require me to teach the pup to leave her alone..her only reaction will be to go somewhere the pup isn't, if being bothered by the pup.We like to travel, but our pet menagerie at moment doesn't allow for much..on driving trips take the dog as much as possible.  No long trips planned at the moment.  Weekends much the same with day trips to visit sister in DC, usually take the dog.  Live near a bike path where either walk the dog or bike on nice days.

DayInLife: I am a chef who can leave the puppy in a crate in the back office when i am working the line. I have the ability to let the dog "get busy" during my 8hr shift. The rest of my week is extremely flexable. I usually get up at 5am and go to the gym from 6-7 (the dog can come with me) I then work from 9-2 M,T,W,R. F,S,Sun are 12 hr shifts for me at work but my family (who will be attending class as well) can take care of the pup or the pup can be crated in the office at work.   I live in a house with my mom and sister (15yr old). We have a 5 yr old silky terrier (Andy)  who gets along with other dogs. My mom takes Andy everywhere with her, he is never crated always goes along for car rides. We have a minivan and the ability to put a crate in the back. I have a small 4 door car and will have the pup on the floor. In the fall I will be commuting to college to obtain my second degree. My work schedule will change and I will be working less hours.

GeneralComments: On Susie's papers when I received her at 8 weeks it said give her time to think.  She still needs time to think when we first arrive somewhere.  She has a very high smell distraction and her nose is constantly sniffing.  I work with her to check in and reward her generously  Susie is a strong willed pup and challenges me to work with her to get the most out of her.  We both enjoy outings and exploring new places.  Susie is a wonderful pup to raise and I have learned a great deal from her.
DayInLife: My typical puppy raising day starts out with taking the pup outside to get busy, back in the house for some food, massage, play, mental exercises (for both of us), then getting ready to go to work.  Once at work we are in an office that has a crate, gate on the open doorway and area for the pup to choose to relax.  We typically go into town every day to get the mail, do banking, visit the local hair salon, library, walk the sidewalks and curbs of the village and college campus.

GeneralComments: Fonzie continues to learn and respond well. He is very excited to be with people and other dogs( we are working on his excitability by having him sit or down as people and animals approach
DayInLife: Have been retired for quite some time. I live alone but have a very active volunteer and social life, an aging in place organization in Somers as well as Mah Jongg one evening a week (7-10pm) nearby or in my home, play tennis twice weekly Tues and Sun, concerts one monthly 3-5pm   My volunteer work takes me away from my home for several hours ( 1-3) several mornings or afternoons a week, but is flexible.   I watch my 14 yr old grand daughter  Hannah on school vacations. She has a genetic syndrome called Prader Willi. She has her own dog but I would not leave the puppy alone with her. I can not leave her alone in my house at any time ( investigates, touches everything, would eat any exposed food) She would be very excited around the puppy. I also visit her home in Pawling about once a month  I spend my summers in Maine on Lake Parlin ( central Maine). I plan to travel to Guiding Eyes in Maine July/Aug  I have made arrangements to travel to Italy Oct 4-12, 2013 with my two adult daughters  My condo is on one level,   surrounded by trees and lawn, large areas to walk but no sidewalks. In socializing my pup I would take her to Mt Kisco, Katonah, Pawling, Brewster etc.  Somers is opening a dog park in the Spring 2013 which I would visit,following the GEB regulations.

GeneralComments: Fiesta has been consistently improving with all her commands and obedience training. She settles well  during the day and sleeps well in her crate at night.  Her counter-surfing has improved and she does exceptionally well on her outings to the mall and other places we visit.  She will pull occasionally when on the leash if she sees another dog so she can get distracted, but this too has improved over the months. Fiesta did have some stomach issues a few weeks ago which involved throwing up every few days, but the vet ran extensive tests and did not find any digestive issues.  The Vet felt it t was possibly stomach inflammation due to ingesting an acorn or stick???  After treating with medication and feeding Fiesta low residue food, she has improved and the throwing up stopped.  We just started giving her Iams lamb and rice 2 days ago and she just threw up yesterday.  After speaking to the Vet today, they recommended continuing with Low residue food for the next 2 days and Very SLowly introducing the Iams back in her diet over the next week.  Her energy level is fabulous and she seems confident and happy.
DayInLife: I attend Walter Panas HS in Cortlandt Manor I am currently a JR(11th grade). My typical day includes waking up at 5:40 to start to get ready for school. once I wake up I take a shower and eat breakfast around 6am I take my dog for a walk and then get dressed for school. My bus picks me up at the end of my driveway at 6:45 I usually arrive back home at 2:15. once a month on a Thursday I arrive home at 1:15 because our school is let out at 1:00 for teacher conferences. Once I arrive home I take my dog for a walk and play outside with him after I do my HW and eat a snack. Once I Finish my Hw depending on the time I watch TV or take my dog out to play with him. Most nights I go to be at 10pm. On the weekends I usually wake up around 8-9:30 In the early morning I do SAT prep for around1- 2 hours. After i finish my SAT prep I usually have the rest of the weekend. My weekends and afternoons are very flexible. I live in a house with a large backyard, with woods in the back. The dog i currently have is a 2 year old Morkie. he is well behaved when home alone he follows me around the house and doesn't like to leave my side. when i am doing my HW he always lays right next to me or in his bed near my desk. Outside he is very well behaved he stays in our yard and loves to play fetch once the ball is thrown he always receives it and brings it back to me. He is also very well behaved with other dogs he doesn't growl or bark at them. He is very use to other animals because we currently have a bunny and my neighbor has chickens there are sometimes deer in my yard and always squirrels.

DayInLife: I just moved up to this area 2 months ago, and am still decompressing from a very demanding job in NYC - 24/7 demands. The lack of demands on me is wonderful. I don't know that I'm retired, but right now I'm not working. So, I'm very flexible and available to the puppy. I am very active and healthy, and walk my current dog 3 X/day, probably 2 miles. He doesn't know about back yards, and is used to being walked. I like the exercise too. He is 8, and super beta. Very very sweet. I have a 10 year old, large male cat, who is very alpha. I tried Brook Farm vet this week for a bath for Tony (my dog), and between that experience and their incessant surveying/reminders/etc., I need to try another vet. Roosevelt Vets were recommended by my neighbors, but I haven't checked them out yet. I don't know the policy for puppies. I had a brood dog for 3 months, and then all vet care was provided by Guiding Eyes. I don't know what the case is for puppies. I have a new house that I built with radiant floor heat throughout which the animals love. I have a fenced back yard.

DayInLife: I am the main puppy raiser.  I am a substitute teacher in the public school system, work very infrequently, less than once a week.  My husband works from home on fridays and that is the only day I make myself available for sub work.  We have never had a family pet before.  3 children living at home  Jessica will be 20 in October.  She had a true dog phobia as a child and has worked hard to break herself of that "embarrasing" condition.  Still not   100% but Jodi is working with her and she's been to every class so far and is excited to be participating.  Oliver will be 13 this summer.  Oliver describes himself as an indoor person and was turned off by the smell of the treats and slime on his hands at the last training session, his first intro to treating!  he had to wash his hands half way thru the session.  He is very excited about being a trainer however and he and his brother have been begging for years for a dog.  He is very smart and is well aware of the commitment and the requirements - lots of going outside - and is still willing to be a part.  John will be 11 this summer.  A little nervous around bigger dogs ever since he recieved a long red scratch that broke the skin down the entire length of his back when a friends large dog jumped up on him to greet him about a year ago.  He is very excited about participating and is a real outdoor boy.    We are very active in our church, which is half an hour from our home.  Sunday morning we leave the house before 9 and can return by 12:30ish but twice a month we go out for lunch afterwards, every other month we have a fellowship meal at the church building  followed by a meeting for committees that Jose and I are part of (Jose is a deacon and has more meetings than I do.)  We will probably be able to bring the puppy to the building with us most times when we need to.  Jesica doesn't go with us very often becasue she works on Sundays (Kohl's) so she may be able to take care of the puppy depending on her schedule (sometimes she goes in at 9 on sundays, sometimes 12.)  We go home, Jose and I take a nap and the boys finish up any homeowrk then it's back to church again in the evening leaving about 5 and returning about 8.  I teach John's class on sunday nights and can have the puppy in class with me.    Monday thru Thursday I am home most of the day, usually doing all my errands on monday.  Oliver and John usually have after school sports and clubs after school Monday thru thursdays.  Fridays this year were arranged visits with a friend for John, so every other weekend he had a friend over for an hour after school.  Saturdays the boys often spend in their pajamas!  Or we go somewhere, festival or something.    We live in a townhouse.

She did two friendly greetings whereas yesterday she was way too excited to do any friendly greetings.  She is due for her IFT at the end of October and I am sure she will do wonderful. She can be a bit stubborn occasionally but she is a teenager and therefore testing her limits
DayInLife: I am recently retired so I have a bit more unscheduled time.  On weekdays Tom and I get up at 5:30 am, shower, have breakfast,  and get Cleo's breakfast.  We are out of the house by 6:40 am to drop Tom off for his ride to work.  Usually Cleo and I then go for a 3-4 mile walk.  We pick Tom back up around 5 pm as he works Monday through Friday.  The rest of the time for me is busy with sewing, gardening, and other unscheduled activities.  I do have grandchildren in town so I do attend some of their activities. On Wednesday afternoons Cleo and I go to Northwest Hospital to visit patients, and in the fall I will be teaching a class on Fridays.  I usually go to lunch once a week with friends, and naturally the usual grocery shopping and other such excursions.  Our weekends are usually busy.  In the summer we have a summer home in Barton and spend weekends with family up there.  The rest of the time we are in Milton.  We have quite a few family get togethers.

ExerciseType: Walks on sidewalks, beach, fetch, play with other dogs

CrateQuietComments: A little whiny if he can see people
ChewingComments: He has been good lately.  He requires very durable toys such as nylabone, jollyballs, deer antlers, bones, etc.  Soft toys, rope toys, and rubber toys will be torn apart and ingested.  Will pick paper or tissues up and chew them.  Otherwise has been good.

PlaybiteComments: Will if over excited
StealFoodComments: Will eat crumbs off of kitchen floor.
BarksExcessivelyComments: Barks at other dogs.

KidsComments: A little clumsy and bumps into them.  Licks them in face
WalkingComments: Does very well with lead wrapped in front of shoulders.
EliminateRouteComments: Occasionally if it is hot.
ChaseComment: Will chase cat if cat does not stand up to him.  Getting better.
SitComments: Slides into down.  Need to work on duration
StayComments: Need to work on duration.
ComeOffLeashComments: Needs work.  If low distraction will come, but if another dog is there he will not.
PillsComments: Have not needed to, but he is very good about mouth handling.
EarsComments: Holds head away.  Has improved greatly.
NailsComments: Does better standing.
GeneralComments: Missed a couple of classes due to getting lost or not getting the email about a change in location.  I will work on this.  Tetris has begun to mature and act less puppy like.  He is able to focus better and is not as likely to alert bark.  I have found a few tough toys that are appropriate to chew on.  He has chewed on wall where already started by another dog at someone elses house, but otherwise has been more trustworthy.  I do not leave him unattended except to go get something from another room.  Needs work on dog distractions, duration of staying in positions, and continued work on appropriate chewing.

DayInLife: My husband and I live in Williston. We live in pretty large condo complex with lots of sidewalks and walking trails. Both sets of our parents live close by and we visit them often.  I am a special educator working with high needs students in Montpelier. Ben (my husband) is a student teacher and afterschool counselor working in Hinesburg. We are currently very busy and do not have time for a puppy. We will  have a lot more time in the summer when Ben is done with student teaching (late June). There is a possibility that either of us could take the dog to work in the fall so we need the puppy to do well in a  crate.    We have a four year old dachshund who is very important to us. I volunteer with him as a and trained him as a therapy dog . We visit people in the hospital once a week. He is very submissive and can be scared of larger dogs. He is particularly scared of high energy dogs. He is never aggressive but generally seems scared that he will be stepped on. We would prefer a calmer dog because this. I do feel that if he gets to know the dog  when he/she is a puppy (therefore smaller) he will get along better with the dog.   We are usually pretty busy with work during the school year but during the summer we have a more relaxed pace. We enjoy being outdoors and active (i.e. going for hikes).

DayInLife: I am a teacher currently on summer break until August 13. During the summer I am available all day and night. During the school year, from Mid-August through June, I work from 7:15 to 2:45 M-F. I am not in the classroom, but rather am a specialist. If I need to I can arrive late or leave early in an emergency. On the weekends, I am usually in and around my home. I have a two bedroom townhome in a row of 6 homes. I have a small fenced in back garden and a small grassy front yard. There are plenty of parks and walking trails. I have three cats who are older but calm around dogs. There are a lot of dogs, elderly people and children in the neighborhood. I have a very good pet care person who is available to help me until the pup can stay for 6 -7 hours. I am undergoing a job location change, but I hope to be able to bring the pup to work after she earns her jacket.

GeneralComments: All sitters have said he's done well, some counter surfing, but not too bad, and he seems to have imporoved with that.  I think that he will grab items if he seems to become bored, and play keep away, I think it's for attention.  He knows which toys are his, and he will get them randomly.  He also always needs to have something in his mouth especially when it's time to go outside.  When it's time to get out of his crate, he always brings a toy/bone with him when before he exits the crate.
DayInLife: I live on 5 acres in a very dog friendly neighborhood. We have 2 dogs at home, a 7 yr. old spayed female and a almost 15 yr. old neutered male beagle.  I have a 17 yr. old daughter who is very interested in helping raise a puppy. We have not had a puppy in 15 yrs., as the 7 yr. old female was adopted at age 4yrs.  I work 5 days a week, leaving the house approx. 4:30am, and returning at approx. 1:30pm. My daughter is home on summer break, so, this is an ideal time for us to try to raise a puppy, since she is home during the day.  My husband is retired and he is also home on and off during the day, as he is busy in the summer crabbing.  I am home all day on Sunday, and another day during the week, which sometimes will change due to the needs of my office.  I work on Saturday's but  I am home by 12:30 and then home for the rest of the day. We will be on vacation in August for approx 10 days.  My daughter and I are looking forward to hopefully being able to raise a puppy.  We have been "out of practice" for 15 years, and hope that we do a good job.

GeneralComments: At home, Jenny is a great dog.  We have been taking her to church every Sunday and she sits through the entire service with no problems.  She does well in most stores also. DayInLife: We are a homeschool family, with a 1st grader, pre-schooler and 15 month old.  I just found out I'm pregnant, but don't have a due date yet.  Most of our mornings are at home for school.  We wake-up between 6:00-7:30.  My husband leaves for work around 7:30.  We have breakfast, then start school.  We are usually done before noon.  The 15 month old takes a nap late morning to early afternoon.  We have lunch.  On Monday the oldest has piano lessons at 2:00 in someone's home.  Sometimes we grocery shop after that, sometimes we come home.  Tuesdays the 6 year old  and 4 year old have dance class from 4:45-6:15 (one after the other).  Wednesday we have dinner at our church at 6:00, followed be Pioneer club and choir. We are usually home around 8:30-9:00.  Thursday we either spend time with my mother-in-law or are part of a homeschool coop in the afternoon.  Friday we go to a play group with 1-3 other family's.  Sometimes we also do errands.  My husband gets home between 5:30-6:30.  We have dinner as a family.  The kids go to bed around 7:00-8:00.  On the weekend, Saturday's vary.  Sometimes we stay home other times we are very busy.  Sunday, we go to church from 9:30-12:00.  We are usually home for the rest of the day after church.

DayInLife: Our family consists of Bill, who works full time outside of the home, Terry, who also works full time outside the home, Michael, who is a full time college student living away from home, and Ann, a high school senior.  On a typical day Terry will get up first, take the puppy outside to get busy, feed the puppy, and then do some training.  Terry will take the puppy to work with her, frequently taking him from his crate for training and exercise.  Ann will work with the puppy after school and in the evening.  Bill and Terry will work with the puppy again in the evening, taking the puppy for a long walk before bedtime.  We have another dog, Frampton, a 3/4 Golden Retriever 1/4 Poodle mix who is a seven year old male who expects to be walked and played with daily.  Frampton is not particulalry good with other dogs, usually barking at the initial meeting.  However, he does settle down quickly and accepts the other dog.   We live in a two story house in the Village of East Aurora.  We have a large kitchen/family room where we spend most of our time.  This area is closed off from the rest of the house which will make it easier to monitor the puppy's behavior.  Our location in the village will allow us to have many socialization opportunities.  We are all in good shape physically so will not have a problem exercising the dog.  We plan on taking him to local parks and for hikes.  Terry's parents are in a senior living facility and she stops by to check on them frequently and will be taking the puppy with her.  We are concerned that there is not much diversity in our village, so we are planning on taking the puppy into the city for more socialization activities.    Ann will be leaving for college in August and Bill will be away for a five week period in late May and June.

GeneralComments: When Lila starts to settle and get into the think and learn zone, then a late or new dog enters the classroom setting she will get aroused. Eventually, she will calm down with the new/late dog in the classroom setting, but it will take longer than it did the first time to get her back into the think and learn zone. She is getting better with her dog distraction outside the class setting and around all the dogs in our neighborhood. Most of the time she will look over at the dog, but then she will check back in with us and pull little or not at all towards the dog.  She does well with her socialization outings.

HealthComments: His ears seem pinker than they should be- but I don't get any debris from them
ExerciseType: stair play inside, play with pet dog & 1-2 mile walk daily
PlaybiteComments: He does get over excited with people and must have a small toy in his mouth when greeting someone new.
BarksExcessivelyComments: Will bark when he sees a cat out the window, also if we are outside and a dog is walking by he will 'talk' (not bark). He wants to get to them and play.
JumpsComments: Meeting new people can be hard..he often goes to get a toy on his own- but I'm always there to remind him.
FriendlyWAnimalsComments: He has dog distraction & small animal distraction (esp. crows!)
WalkingComments: (Despite the Bear Mtn. outing with 8 dogs...Simba does walk well on a lead)
EliminateRouteComments: He toilets before every outing...if he gets really excited, he will need to toilet before we get back in the car. I have seen him pee on the road twice- obviously marking where a fox or something had been.
ChaseComment: Would chase animals if not on a lead. He responds to crows? other dogs, cats.
StairsComments: Inside yes- outside he is having trouble with stairs. Mostly going UP new stairs. Coming down is far easier for him.
ComeOffLeashComments: His 'come' command is very good! Even if other dogs are there- he listens and comes.
GeneralComments: My biggest concern is Simba is very attached to me. He comes looking for me now more often than he used to. My husband reports that Simba looks for me even when he's home with him & I'm away.  He has a tendency to 'talk' (not bark- though he will do this occasionally,too) I am trying to eliminate this behavior.  His stair regression- is somewhat worrisome. He did stairs perfectly well until 7 months old. Now, I must plan carefully where I take him, so I don't get stranded.  He is a gleeful, sweet, playful dog- but is less confident than Jethro or Hamilton (2H08) were. Simba learns in a very gradual way (he gets there- but needs time to process).   He does love being touched and will stand very still for brushing & massages!

GeneralComments: He is doing great. He walks loose-leash much better than he used to. He listens well, and he stays attentive for much longer than he used to. He does get distracted easily, especially in new places. We have been taking him out about 4 times a week, but we have been trying to increase that to 5 times a week. With more socialization, we are sure he will improve on his attentiveness as well as his manners around new people. He knows all his commands and does them with ease. His duration on all of his commands have improved but with new handlers, we are told he still needs work. We also have some concerns about him "humping" other dogs, specifically Tamara's three. He also occasionally attempts to "hump" people if we are on the ground playing with him and he gets excited.
DayInLife: I am currently starting my last semester of college. My days vary based on my class schedule (currently i have no friday classes).  I have a part-time job on the weekends and work an average of 10-15 hrs a week (friday-saturday).  My classes range from an hr to 3 hrs long and I work in the kennel at a vet where personal pets are allowed.  I work shift of a max of 5 hrs but could be as small as an hr (long enough to feed and walk boarding dogs).  During the time not in class or at work I don't have set plans.      I live in an apartment near college campus with my husband and two cats.  My husband is also taking classes and working part-time.  Our schedule vary in a way where there is always someone home or someone able to take the puppy with them.  After graduation, I will be looking for a job change but I am keeping to dog-related jobs.  I hope in another year or so I can open my own business depending on the area where my husband can find a job (the job will probably not be any farther than an hour drive from our current location.  A baby is a possibility over the next two years depending on how things work out after graduation.    Typically once a month we drive to visit family in a city that is an hour drive.

DayInLife: i work from home for my husbands business. jim owns a screen printing business called All-U. my son mike also has his own small company "mike made this" which is a line of t-shirts that are printed at all u.mike made this is run by the family since mike is away at university of vermont. we sell his t shirts at craft fairs on most weekends. we travel to the craft fairs and throughout the year they range from within new york, Vermont, Massachusetts, and Connecticut. we would be able to bring the pup with us and the craft fairs would be great for socialization. there are many people and different environments. we would always be able to have someone take turns watching and socializing the pup while the others are working. if we visit mike and danny (who is at Champlain college for film)  in burlington the pup would be sure to come with us. most of the craft fairs would be flexible as well because we could always have some people stay at home while others go and work. our normal week/day: the girls go off to school and are gone by 7:30. jims goes off to work shortly after. i make my coffee and then start some work for a while. then i'll take a shower. depending on the day i'll run some errands or go to the ymca. otherwise i am working at my computer. i'll be able to supervise the puppy in the same room as me and take the pup out to get busy and for walks. monday grace has ballet in down town albany. we would be able to bring the pup with us while she is at ballet and work on walking on sidewalks. emily will either get home from school at 3 or she will have an after school activity and will get home at 4:20. then jim gets home around 7 depending on how busy it is at work. then we eat dinner around that time and thats it for the night. we have a somewhat busy life, but the activities we do can involve the pup as well.

StrangerComments: gets so excited that he wants to play wildly and jump on them.
WalkingComments: working on it...ML's idea to walk only a couple of steps and sit, walk a few steps,  and sit,,,,etc.
GetBusyComments: not sure how to answer this. He "asks" to go out and/or I take him out  regularly so he always "gets busy" but I don't think it's  on command.
ChaseComment: wants to chase the outside cat every time it moves
TrafficComments: haven't taken him in traffic yet...he's not ready
NoiseComments: was afraid last Sat. of the snow plow truck that came to shovel us out...the closer it got, the more he backed  away
StairsComments: didn't like stairs the first few times but I think it was because he didn't know how to get them.  he seems fine with stairs now.
SitComments: generally sits on command but out of the blue occasionally just ignores you and refuses to do what he's done well in the past such as  sit, or lay down or close.
DownComments: same as above.  generally goes down but every once in a while just refuses to do it and tries his best to ignore me
StayComments: same as the comments for sit and down
ComeOffLeashComments: When he's playing out in our big enclosed area, he won't "come" when he's chewing on a stick or sniffing out some great corner or is otherwise distracted by something.  If he is not playing with a stick etc., he'll come.
PillsComments: Haven't had to give him any pills.
EarsComments: Tries to play bite when you mess with his ears.
NailsComments: Haven't tried this yet but he is okay if you just  run your hand along his foot, touch the toes and pads etc.
GeneralComments: We've successfully and happily raised many dogs in the past but Kelsey is probably the most frustrating one we've had.  We're not sure if it's us...or the breed....or him....or what?????  One key thing I've noticed is that inside our house is the only place where he seems to really connect and pay attention to us. Anywhere else he's just all over the place! We've learned A LOT in our classes so we anticipate that the walk and talk will be equally helpful and enlightening.  Thanks for all your time..help..and ideas. Kissingers
DayInLife: We live in the Village of Florida on 5 acres.  Our kids were in 4-H, Andrew still is, and raised various animals.  Andrew raises rabbits.  We raise chickens and turkeys.  Maqrv is retired and home most of the time.  Andrew is home schooled.  Joan is a retired teacher and is called to sub time to time.  We have two dogs Abby,Golden Retrevier and Beemer,Yorkshire Terrier. Puppy schedule:Joan is up at 5:45 and showers and dressed by 6:15.  Puppy GB with Abby and Beamer at 6:15 followed by socialization.  7-8 puppy crate while Joan feeds animals and gets ready for work if she has been called as a substitute teacher.  Marv and Andrew up by 8 and one will take the puppy out for GB with Abby and Beamer,some play time and feed puppy by 8:30.  Puppy nap time untill Andrew starts home schooling at 9.  9-1  Andrew completes school, Marv works outside, runs errands, etc.  Puppy is in an enclosed area.  Marv or Andrew will watch the puppy during this time, take him our for GB, socialization, walks, play, lunch and rest.  1-4: Andrew has lunch and continues school and plays.  Marv  works outside and inside. Puppy out 3:30 for GB with Abby and Beemer.   Joan home by 4 but my go out for tutoring.  4:30 feed rabbits and get eggs, feed ouside cats.  5-6:30 dinner prep, puppy dinner and GB,family dinner, clean up kitchen.  Andrew Plays with puppy.  6:30-8 Andrew reviews school work with Joan.  Marv works in his office. Puppy GB with Abby and Beemer and Puppy  bed time.  8-11 family free time.  11 Puppy GB with Abby and Beemer and bed time for all.  2-3 Marv takes puppy for GB and back to bed and it starts all over again.

HealthComments: No health problems
StoolComments: No problems after the transition
ExerciseType: Walks in neighborhood, fetch in the house, playing with kids
EliminationCrateComments: Never has had an accident in the crate
CrateQuietComments: Quiet at night and when working at home but whines if there is a lot of activity in the house if he is in crate
KennelCommandComments: Only with treats going into the kennel
ChewingComments: He knows his toys and the kids toys and if we are watching leaves them alone.  If we aren't watching he will try to get their toys if left in his reach.
HousemannersComments: Is doing good staying off furniture, doesn't jump up on people, leaves food alone on the table
LeftUnattendedComments: I'm not sure...we haven't left him unattended.  He does get free access to first floor when we are home and is doing well
EliminationHouseComments: The last few weeks only 2 accidents and he is doing better at barking/whining at us when he wants to go outside.  I think he is almost there.
PlaybiteComments: I rarely see him do this...sometimes when playing with the kids he gets excited and forgets they are kids and thinks they are dogs.
StealFoodComments: I haven't seen his steal any he usually goes and lays down on the kitchen rug when we eat
OnFurnitureComments: Most of the time yes - sometimes when he is running and playing he jumps up on the couch - but it is usually after one of the kids jumps on the couch
BarksExcessivelyComments: He doesn't bark much at all...
RaidsGarbageComments: We have a garbage with a lid but he stays away from it - i'm not sure what he would do with the lid open
CountersDoorsComments: He hasn't jumped on the counters or doors yet
JumpsComments: Most of the time - he doesn't jump on people
FriendlyWAnimalsComments: He has been around a few guiding eyes dogs during overnights and I get good reports - we don't have any other animals in our home
KidsComments: He is excellent with our kids
StrangerComments: He still gets excited when he sees them - he is friendly but we are still working on greeting people
WalkingComments: Only with treats...we continue to work on this
GetBusyComments: Very good here - usually immediately
EliminateRouteComments: As long as he "gets busy" before we walk
ChaseComment: We haven't been in this situation a lot - but he doesn't seem to be bothered by the deer and squirrels in our yard
TrafficComments: Not sure...our streets are not that busy.  We need to take him into town
NoiseComments: For the most part
StairsComments: Yes - he goes up and down them
SitComments: Pretty good - always if we have a treat
DownComments: Still working on this and he doesn't seem to like to do it on the cement outside - perhaps because it is cold now
StayComments: Just introducing this - he stays small distances
ComeOnLeashComments: Most times
ComeOffLeashComments: He comes when we call him in the house - I'm not sure how he would do with other distractions or outside
PillsComments: He takes the Heartworm pill easily but we haven't had to give him anything else at this point so I'm not sure
EarsComments: No problem with ears
NailsComments: Haven't had to do it much but he hasn't given us any problems
GeneralComments: Overall for 5 months - I think he is doing well with the basic day to day activities.
DayInLife: Up at 7 - work from home or travel about 30 nights per calender year.  have 4 and 5 year olds and love dogs.  We have a good sized house and are ready to work together to raise the puppy into a great guide dog!!

BarksExcessivelyComments: shes a moaner not a barker.. she heavy sighs when displeased
CountersDoorsComments: will counter surf but has never made an attempt to get anything up there.
JumpsComments: if energy level high of person she meets, she would jump but under normal greetings she does not
FriendlyWAnimalsComments: she wants to play.. no aggression but will easily come off task
WalkingComments: awesome.. we are working on when other dogs walk by
GetBusyComments: she will pee no problem.  the other takes some work
EliminateRouteComments: she will,  we are working on giving her breaks when i notice her walk but sometimes she wont go and then 5min later she is on someones lawn.
ChaseComment: if given the chance she would go for a dog;  she does not chase squirels, birds, rabbits.
TrafficComments: she is getting better.
NoiseComments: she is not really afraid.. but a sneeze will make her get up and investigate..
StairsComments: she is good.. but will sometimes hug your body which kind of knocks you a bit
PillsComments: havent tried to give her a pill for illness but she eats the heartgaurd with no problems
EarsComments: we are still working on that.. she turns her head to see what/where you are going but once i get in her ear w/ cotton ball she is ok
NailsComments: she is not a fan.  but i have no confidence with this either.
GeneralComments: she did a 2 week puppy swap but that was it.   still working on her issues with water.. she is getting OK with the hose and will actually drink from the spray handle.   i had her sit and watch someone power wash a side walk with no issue, but i didn't walk up to it or by it because i knew that would push her over the edge.   she is doing very well on her people greeting skills, the hard part is getting people to not pet her when she stands..
DayInLife: I work 8.5 hours a day at home start 7am finish 3:30pm  (i have a little flexablity with start and finish,  flexable breaks and lunch time).  we are pretty low key, laid back lifestyle.   we live in a nice neibhorhood with sidewalks, people jog, walk dogs, ride bikes.  We do enjoy Sunday drives and some hiking.

RaidsGarbageComments: peeks into garbage when opportunity arises
CountersDoorsComments: much better here

GeneralComments: went to Lil's....she said she was a good guest!!  Silk is a work in progress.  she is smart, sweet and a good girl.  she sometimes gets bored and zones out when working on a lot of commands at once but she is a" teenager".  she is confident and has some really good days and once in a while not so good.  Ava and i will keep working so she progress to where she should be.  she is pleasure to have.
DayInLife: I work from home , my husband works ouside of the home.  3 kids go to school.  I usually go to gym and or do errands in the mornings and walk Ivalee.  Her walk could be local for 20 mins or big walk - hour and half if I dont exercise in am.  Afternoon consists of shuttling kids to different after school activiities.  I always take Ivalee in car with me.  she is hardly ever left at home (maybe 2 hours a day ..sometimes not at all.  we have a fat female cat who can hold her own with all visiting dogs.  I we go to VT most weekend in winter.  we ski so dog(s) will be left alone for longer periods of time (too cold to leave in car). in springtime, kids have many ourside activities (lacrosse games, regattas) that I always bring Ivalee too.  Ihave 2 weekends coming up that I will be out of town for - my sister's bridal shower and her wedding.  for the shower (dec 3...soon)  my sons will be home and I could potentially leave puppy with them.  As for the wedding 3/31, I have a dog swap with Ivalee's friend so she will go there for weekend.  I will need help that weekend for puppy.  Also - after consideration, we would like  a male puppy, maybe a black lab or shepard, something totally out of our normal range...mind as well make this a whole new experience.!  looking forward to it!  and yes, I saw the ZU ZU petal comment - I read everything.  kids will have to read this week...a lot of info!!!

HousemannersComments: Does get excited when people come in even family members. Getting better at settling down.
LeftUnattendedComments: In a kennel if not she will find something to get in trouble with. I do allow her the freedom to use the LR KIT Hallway and upstairs when I'm home working. She usually stays with me.
PlaybiteComments: She does this with Jen Judy and Chris.
OnFurnitureComments: Jumps up mainly at night when the Family is settling in for the evening.
BarksExcessivelyComments: Barks for attention...Food or play, We do the appropriate training to get her to stop.
RaidsGarbageComments: Always interested in the bathroom Tissues.
CountersDoorsComments: Better at this although once in a while she does jump up and steal a towel. Then runs to have you chase her. We don't play that game...
JumpsComments: First contact she is very aroused and there is no attention to commands. She does sit but that is for a short period and then she circles the person and does not stop until you can get her attention again.
FriendlyWAnimalsComments: Very friendly likes to play.
KidsComments: Has that contact, sniffing and licking thing going with children.
StrangerComments: From a distance she is very aware of them some she barks at, then settles usually runners.
WalkingComments: A lot better still does some pinging.
GetBusyComments: These last two weeks she just sniffs around and does not get busy when we get to where we want her to go. Takes a long time.
EliminateRouteComments: We give her the opportunity to bet busy before a walk and most times she does. She has stopped in the middle of the walk to get busy.Also at the end we give her an opportunity to get busy.
TrafficComments: Very aware and wants to look at each and every car truck bike until they are out of sight.
NoiseComments: Unafraid but very aware, she stops on the walk to get a better understanding of what is making the noise. Although that limb cracking last week sent her running. Also since that time she is very hesitant on walking past the area where she got scared.
StayComments: Working on that more, she has a very short duration to a Stay command. you need to repeat it a few times before she gets the point of what you want her to do. Other people in the room are more interesting.
PillsComments: With Food, or treat. Not alone.
EarsComments: She moves if your taking too long.
NailsComments: Same thing you need to be quick.

ExerciseType: daily walks/run, play time in apt
DayInLife: I am typically done with classes at noon m-f. I work at a genetics lab on Cornell's campus usually about 3 days/week after class for roughly 2 hours. On the weekends my schedule is completely open. I am a member on the E-Board of 3 campus organizations. I am most free in the afternoons/evenings. I live in an apt/house where my landlord lives upstairs. He is not big on pets due to previous furniture stains caused by a prior tenant's dog but made an exception for me seeing I would be working for Guiding Eyes. Therefore I ask that I could work with a male puppy. Additionally, I would LOVE to raise a Golden retriever if possible, but a Lab would also work :)

GeneralComments: Zettie loves to go places and is very well-behaved in stores and restaurants. Behaving around other dogs is still a challenge for her.
DayInLife: I live alone now that my children are grown, although two live nearby and will drop in. My out-of-town son occasionally comes for a visit. I have two grandchildren, ages 2 and 4. Currently, I take the 2-year-old to a half-hour class, then bring her to my house for play and lunch. The 4-year-old will spend the night on occasion.   I live in a house with a fenced-in yard; no pets now other than fish in a small outside pond.   I am not employed outside the house. I will have occasional freelance writing work that I do from home and I am working on my own writing projects.  I try to run just about every day, three or four miles, outside weather permitting and I go to the gym several times a week.   My mom lives in assisted living and I am the one who takes her to her appointments. These are close enough that, if necessary, I can swing by the house to let the pup out before taking my mom home - she is very excited about the prospect of a puppy. As am I!

ChewingComments: sometimes finds plants irresistable
JumpsComments: a work in progress
FriendlyWAnimalsComments: Excited around other dogs, tail wagging.  Played enthusiastically with Sonya and Sharla, two GEB dogs in the region.  Always ready to play in class.  I get him off the trail when I see other dogs on our walks and feed him through the experience.  I haven't let him interact with "unknown" dogs.
KidsComments: He gets excited with little ones.  I try to keep him in a down stay, but he REALLY wants to lick their faces.
GetBusyComments: With the recent extreme weather events, he gets distracted and doesn't  eliminate.  So, more frequent trips outside.  With the snow, it takes longer for him to fine the "right spot."
EliminateRouteComments: He is stimulated on walks in the woods and eliminates several times.  On walks around town, we get busy beforehand and I keep an eye on his behavior and get him to a get busy spot as needed.
ChaseComment: Hasn't been given the opportunity
TrafficComments: The noise doesn't faze him.  I keep him close to keep us both safe.
StairsComments: He has slowed down going down stairs.  He's actually walked with me a few times.
StayComments: He sometimes breaks his stay.  On the other hand,  he  maintained a down stay for an hour when bell choir was practicing at my house.
ComeOffLeashComments: I sometimes have to up the ante with a toy or a treat.
PillsComments: Never have had the need to.  Heartguard goes down with no problem
EarsComments: Cleaned exterior only
NailsComments: I use a grinder on his nails daily.  He is very good about it.  Mostly just lies there.  I haven't used used the clippers often.
GeneralComments: Keenan is a delight.  He has responded well as I  have expanded his environment.  People we meet are surprised taht he is still so young and behaves so well.  He's still distracted by other dogs and small children.  All adults are his admirers in his opinion.  He is outgoing, friendly, affectionate, cooperative and an excellent companion.

ChewingComments: still grabs shoes if left on floor, but not from the closet.  Also fond of the bath mat - its spongy and paper.
HousemannersComments: Davey still get items to chew that are inappropriate and gets into the garbage if possible
LeftUnattendedComments: Need to restrict his movements to the floor I am on (two rooms per floor)

BarksExcessivelyComments: BArks when he has to eliminate, is thirsty or at the cat.
RaidsGarbageComments: Getting better
CountersDoorsComments: the occasional steal from the counter, but rare
JumpsComments: Jumps if people lean forward.  We are training him on how to net get overly excited when someone comes to the door.
KidsComments: Wants to play with kids but is still unaware of how big he is.  He tends to knock them over.
WalkingComments: Biggest problem is the nose to the ground issue.  Walks great on sidewalks and the complex
GetBusyComments: I know his schedule and his looks so he is ok then.  Not very good with having to pee in new places
EliminateRouteComments: never been a problem
ChaseComment: Cat

NoiseComments: The only issue has been with thunder outside.  I think he has trouble determining where the sound is coming from, especially in the condo complex with the echos from the buildings.
StayComments: This skill we need to reinforce on a regular basis.  A few too many days without using this command and he wanders after 15 seconds.
NailsComments: No problems with putting my finders in his ears or using a tissue.  Have not tried q-tips yet.
GeneralComments: Seems to very well during switches or sits and adjusts to alternate methods in other peoples homes.    He settles very well in school during my classes.  He is best with a regular schedule of exercise.
DayInLife: I work as a professor so I plan to take the dog with me frequently.  I leave for work at 7am M-Th.  Fridays, Sat and Sun I am home.  I have three hour classes with 10/15 min breaks.  Mon and Tues nights I have class and will need to leave the pup for about 3/4 hours.  I have help during the first six weeks if i need to leave the pup longer.  After that I have less frequent help available, but should be able to keep the pup in my office by then (?).  I live in a townhouse.  There are many, many, many dogs in the complex.  I have several fenced in areas (tennis court, ball park) to allow running time/ball play.

GeneralComments: Luster still has her distracted times, but once she checks out an area, she is usually able to tune in pretty quickly.  She has some dog distraction.  We have had no further issues of aggression.  She still does not love body handling, but she is very good about it.  We are still doing a lot of quick handling and rewarding.

ChewingComments: occasionally still chews sticks
HousemannersComments: If we are on the couch she will sometimes put her paws up on us

OnFurnitureComments: see above regarding couch
RaidsGarbageComments: we have kept the garbage up.  but we do have it out from time to time and with us present has not gone in it.
