ChaseComment: wants to chase squirrels and other dogs
DownComments: She sometimes requires the command to be given twice
PillsComments: we have not had to give her pills, but she will eat anything you give her.
NailsComments: pulls away sometimes but mostly allows it without isue
DayInLife: I am not working now, so I am home during the days during the week as well as weekends. My typical week involves several periods of time commitment. I take classes Tues and Thurs evenings and Sunday afternoon.  I am typically away from the apartment 2-3 hours for these periods. I also exercise in the mornings, two to three times per week, although the days and times vary. I am usually exercising first thing in the morning, typically starting sometime between 7:15AM and 8:30AM. The duration is usually 30mins to an 1.5 hours, I also am out of the house mid-day on Tues and Thurs, usually for an 1-2 hours. Outside of those commitments, my remaining time is open and flexible. We have a dog already and we live near the park, so we are in the park at least twice daily for anywhere from half and hour to an hour with our dog; weekend days are typically longer. We live in a 3rd floor apartment and often take the stairs down and ride a small elevator up to our apartment. The apartment is one bedroom so we spend almost all of our time in the front room, which is fairly open and sizeable (for NYC). If not in the front room, we are in the ktichen, which is fairly small.    My wife and I expect to travel periodically to Boston, so we would be traveling in a car with the dog periodically as well.    The timing of my return to work is uncertain. If I were to return to the same field, which is yet to be determined, my evenings can be interrupted unexpectedly, although the frequency of these occassions is low, but have flexibility of time during the days.

ExerciseType: walking 1.5 mile per day,  play time with  family puppy fenced area back yard
DayInLife: My wife and I usually wake up at six o'clock. she takes a shower and I wake up our son for school and then I put our airedale out in an xpen area to get busy. I bring her inside the house feed her and get her fresh water. My wife is usually done with her shower by then and cooks breakfast for our son. I take my shower and check on the progress of our son. My wife and son eat breakfast together, she then gets dressed for work. I crab a cup of coffee and check our son's school essentials for that day. My wife leaves for work and I take our son to the bus stop where he is picked up by the town school bus. Sometimes our Airedale waits with us. I picked up the newspaper off the driveway and the airedale and I go back into the house. She will usually finish her breakfast while I read the paper and drink another coffee. After reading the paper I take away any unfinished food from the Airedale. Mid morning I check any emails or messages from our rental property tennants. If I have doctor's appointment to atytend they are usually scheduled late morning. I will in that case attend the appointments or respond to tenants requests. If the airedale is crated and sleeping I let her sleep. If she is awake we go for a neighborhood walk. When we get home she will want to lay at the front door looking at the traffic and passers by one the side walk. She usually falls asleep. I prepare our evening meal and may text or talk to our twin nineteen year old girls in college. Our son comes home from school at about 3:30. He has is snack and review any schoolwork or homework he may have. I finish up preparing super and my wife arrives home at 4:15. I set the table and we eat at about five PM. At this time my son will feed the Airedale. We finish super and clean up about six. We usually watch the news and some type of crime shows until later in the evening. During this time period our Airedale may want to go out several times even if she doesn't have to get busy. She just goes through this routine to get treats from us. Since she is a older dog  we give in a treat het, even though she hasn't done her business every time. My wife reads for a while then goes to bed at nine. I check our son's homework and he's in bed by ninethiry, lights out at te. I'll watch TV for a half hour and go to bed about ten thirty. I secure the bathroom and put the Airedale to bed if she is not already there on her pillow bed. Then I head for bed.

HealthComments: Has had two ear infections and a vomiting episode.
ChewingComments: Occasionally chews up cardboard when he can get his paws on it.
LeftUnattendedComments: I rarely lock him in the crate.
PlaybiteComments: He has recently started play biting people, mainly feet.
StealFoodComments: Won't steel food when people are around, but if left unattended he might steel food off of a surface.
OnFurnitureComments: Has jumped onto the couch when hyper and playing.
CountersDoorsComments: Never jumps on doors, but has occasionally jumped on counters to try to get food.
EliminateRouteComments: He has recently begun marking.
ComeOffLeashComments: Has difficulty responding to "come" when he is playing or highly distracted.
EarsComments: He lets me clean his ears with Q-tips, but once I bring out a liquid he runs away.
NailsComments: Has strong aversion to getting nails clipped. I accidentally cut the quick once when he was about three months old, but not since then. His aversion to getting his nails clipped started about four months ago.
GeneralComments: Moose walks well on lead when prompted to and with enthusiastic encouragement throughout the walk, but when the handler is silent he does not focus on them and will pull.  When he is excited and playful, he wants to play immediately and will paw your leg, sometimes biting  feet or pants.  He takes to new handlers very well and is eager and willing to work with a variety of handlers. He has been some new sitters' first sit and they have reported having a very pleasant time with him!   Most of the time he settles well and will sleep through college classes.  He is a gentle and submissive player with other dogs, always carrying a toy. He plays very well with the teeny puppies.
DayInLife: As a college student, my schedule changes with each season. However, I have scheduled my classes while keeping a potential puppy in mind! A typical school day would consist of a couple of hours of classes, at most two consecutive hours, so that I am allowed breaks in between classes for puppy time. However, I plan to work as well, so that might take up at most four hours one or two days a week. I will be living in a dorm room on campus. Periodically throughout the year I will be traveling home to NJ, and during these breaks from school my schedule will be more flexible and the puppy will have a house rather than a dorm room and hallway. I plan to associate with the NYC region during these times.   Because I live in a dorm with many neighbors, I would probably need a puppy that isn't very fond of yapping.    I look forward to the rest of my journey as a puppy raiser/sitter!!

DayInLife: My typical day during the school year (mid-Sept to mid-May) is that I wake at 6:00 a.m. and get my 2 daughters (ages 10 & 13) off to school.  I usually take a walk around 8:00 a.m. before heading to my job as a preschool teacher at a local Nature Center.  I am usually home by 1:00.  I sometimes take a walk before my kids get home from school at 3:00.  We do homework from 4:00-5:00 p.m. Dinner is usually around 6:00.  We usually take an after dinner walk or play outside around until 7:00.  Bedtime for my kids is by 9:00 and I am in bed by 10:00.  I am married, but my husband is gone most of the time for work, so it's just me and my girls during the week. We just lost our beloved 13 year old yellow lab (who was a service dog trained through the Delta Society) in October, but we somehow still stick to his schedule with the walks, etc.  Sometimes habits are hard to break! I don't work during the summer, but sometimes I do kids day camps here and there.  Our entire family is home for the weekends and I pretty much stick to my walk schedule because I love being outdoors!  We are very lucky to live in a wonderful neighborhood with plenty of dog owners.  We have the Cleveland MetroPark system, Lake Erie and a man made reservoir all within walking distance from our house! We do have 3 cats, but they are used to being around dogs because of ours and others that we dog sit regularly.  (Even as I am writing this, I have a black lab and 2 Bernese Mountain dogs laying at my feet!) We would love to become puppy raisers by the end of May or early June of this year (2012).  We would prefer a yellow lab, but the gender does not matter. Thank you for your consideration!

HealthComments: Still hoping all is well from Trackers recent health issues.  He went to GEB and had exploratory surgery and had everyone confused.
KidsComments: We get a bit excited sometimes and lick tons!
NoiseComments: He is very interested in noises though.
DayInLife: A typical weekday schedule:  6:30-7:00am Wakeup and take care of Cooper (forever dog) including get busy, play, and feeding.                     Get ready for work, play with Cooper a bit and let him get busy before crating.  Noon           Go home for lunch (mostly Cooper's & future GEB Pup) and a short walk & play time with pup  5:00pm        Go home for the evening (and now play & exercise with Cooper!)    Monday nights GEB Classes & currently Wednesday nights classes for Cooper (taught by Alyssa!)    Weekends are usually commitment free and flexible for my plans!  Typically I wake up between 9 and 10 to get Cooper to allow get busy and play time or even let him nap if he wants.  Commonly watching TV, watching a movie, going for walks or similar.  When busy I commonly try to get Cooper interested in his toys and to keep him stimulated.

ExerciseType: walking, play with released dog and ourselves
KennelCommandComments: Very Occasionally hesitates but if I wait he does kennel.

JumpsComments: Calms quickly but can get excited.

GeneralComments: Gaston is very social and well behaved with people - staying in Sunday worship for 1 hr. 30 minutes; coming forward with handler for communion and not trying to "steal" the bread and last week went with handler to receive offering row by row.  Will lay still in fast food restaurants.  Often in the office when visitors come and no longer needs to be crated in the office unless I leave him alone. Not a problem in the house at all.  Major difficulty is being around other dogs - improving but still needs work.  Does still pull at times when we begin walks.  Will now let the older dog finish his food without jumping in to steal it.

ExerciseType: training, playing, retrieving, playing in water, walking
KennelCommandComments: You need to be near the kennel.  If you are across the room from the kennel and say "kennel" she doesn't seem to understand where to go.
ChewingComments: She is teething at this time and will put her mouth on shoes or any other rubbery object.
HousemannersComments: She is improving.  Adora will occassionally still jump on counters and tables if she is excited.
LeftUnattendedComments: Only for very short amount of times
EliminationHouseComments: Still has an accident (urine only) every other day.  Usually when we can't get to the door fast enough.  Adora does to the door to indicate her need to go out.
PlaybiteComments: Once again, her mouth is on everything at the moment.
StealFoodComments: She will try to steal a bone off another dog of ours, but Sassy doesn't allow the behavior
OnFurnitureComments: She doesn't jump completely on the couch, but does rest her upper body when she wants attention
CountersDoorsComments: As I mentioned early, when excited she will still jump on counter or table
JumpsComments: It depends on how excited the person is.  If they are overly excited, she gets jumpy
WalkingComments: As long as she is by herself, Adora does well.  If there is another dog around, she is distracted
EliminateRouteComments: She will occasionally
NoiseComments: New noise will stop her in her tracks, but she doesn't shy away
StairsComments: She comes down the stairs fast and awkward
StayComments: for short periods
ComeOffLeashComments: As long as she has had time to smell the area first.  A random smell can sidetrack her
GeneralComments: Adora will have her first overnight next week.    Adora is smart and a quick learner.  She loves people and loves to snuggle.  She is growing quickly.  Adora is confident and well behaved in most situations.  She has been to wineries, museums, schools, parks, and stores and enters all new situations confidently.    Adora can be fearless.  She is confident enough to stand up to our Mastiff/Rottweiler and not back down.      She loves to "lead" our other dogs, taking them by the collar or leash and pulling.    She is still having accidents occassionally.  Adora is easily excitable.  Excited people make her extremely excited and she can be hard to pull away from the situation.    Adora is very food oriented, but picky.  The food rewards have to keep increasing.  She will not work for dog food.
DayInLife: House living, Second floor, not a too active family, still in school (late august-early june), most days it's wake up, shower, and plan the day but school days it wake up, shower, eat, go to school, come home, walk dogs, find activity,   you should know I am going to disney March 22-28, 2013 and plan on taking the puppy with me if it's approved

ChewingComments: Likes to "mouth" but not chew socks

EliminateRouteComments: sometimes needs to poop
ChaseComment: squirrels are fascinating

GeneralComments: Glenda has a very sweet disposition and is eager to please.  She has been working on "body handling"--making good progress!  Also on "duration"--she is now happy to seat at my feet whilst I work at the desk or cut up veggies in the kitchen.  Her loose leash walking skills continue to improve as well as her ability to "ignore" distractions (but she is still very curious about the world around her!).
DayInLife: We live in a family neighborhood, on a peninsula, about 1 mile from downtown Stamford.  The Shippan area has parks, beaches, sidewalks, lots of young children and dogs.  I am a retired attorney, my husband works more-than-full time, as he is the head of a small law firm.  We usually rise around 6:30AM, have breakfast, read a few newspapers, bathe & dress, take our released Guiding Eyes dog (Jolee) for a walk.  I go to a yoga class most mornings, return home after errands around 11AM and am home doing chores, gardening, corresponding, cooking, reading or walking Jo around the 'hood until 4PM, when I start cooking dinner.  After dinner, we either go for a walk, watch a movie or read.  On weekends, we visit and socialize with friends and family, do household chores, work in the garden or in the summer, take the boat out sailing. I also cook for my mother-in-law, when she is Up North in the summer--I take food in to her in NYC pretty much every Sunday and we visit for a couple of hours. I volunteer at God's Love We Deliver every Wednesday morning, but am home around lunchtime.  Our daughter, Rachel, is a college grad and lives in Russia, but will be coming back to the States this summer.  Most of the time, it's Phil and me and Jolee!  Hope this helps!  My schedule is really pretty flexible except for the Weds. morning gig.

ExerciseType: Walks and Play Sessions w. other GEB pups
ExericeAmount: Appx. 2 hours, usually more during school year
CrateQuietComments: Usually good, sometimes will whine if put in there while there are people in the room with him.
ChewingComments: Water Bottles & Moccasin type shoes if left unattended. Otherwise, he's great!
HousemannersComments: Jumps on couches, will off when told but tries again minutes later
EliminationHouseComments: Was having accidents earlier in the year but has been consistently fine for several months
PlaybiteComments: If overly excited may accidentally bite but only to grab a toy
StealFoodComments: Huge begger. Will sit and lick the air next to your plate. Won't steal but if left unattended, it's a strong possibility.
OnFurnitureComments: Will jump on couches and as of late, beds. Will off when told but tries again within minutes.
BarksExcessivelyComments: Will bark if I leave him, or if someone else has him and I'm closeby. Separation Anxiety.
JumpsComments: Has definitely improved but still needs work.
FriendlyWAnimalsComments: Always friendly, whether they like it or not. I don't think I have ever heard him growl. Excited play barking but no growling.
KidsComments: Only issue is he'll lick their face since they're usually level with his face.
StrangerComments: Very friendly, however will try to jump and lick their faces if not controlled
WalkingComments: Usually fine however have had several instances where he has suddenly bolted and almost knocked me over.
GetBusyComments: Takes a few minutes to sniff but will eventually go.
EliminateRouteComments: We usually go before the walk and after the walk is over, but if he really has to go he'll stop walking and give me a look. I'll make him sit and then walk him to the grass on my terms.
ChaseComment: Will definitely look but I can get his attention back
ComeOffLeashComments: If outside and distracted by something, will rarely come. I'll have to bribe him with treats.
NailsComments: Used to be perfect, then he moved his leg while I was clipping once and I quicked him. Now won't let me near him with the clippers whatsoever. I'm working on desensitizing him to the clippers again.
GeneralComments: If possible I would like to vest test Lucas, so if we could work on the components of a vest test that would be great.  Really would like to work on Lucas' separation anxiety from me as well as the jumping.  Also the nail clipping needs to be worked on. I've been desensitizing him to the clippers every day by touching his feet then treating him, but it's a slow process.

At times Sheena seems to have an acute visual and auditory sensitivity to her environment. Even on walks within the neighborhood she still continues to need to stop and watch people come out of there houses, stop and observe other dogs, etc.  Once she has taken it in, she's ready to move on.   She continues to have dog distraction within the classroom setting but when out working with other pups she seems to handle it fine.  Sheena can quickly go into the yellow zone during an outing and many repeat exposures have proven very beneficial for her.

GeneralComments: Sheena is an incredibly sweet, sensitive pup with a nice energy level. She's easy to work with and eager to please.  At times Sheena seems to have an acute visual and auditory sensitivity to her environment. Even on walks within the neighborhood she still continues to need to stop and watch people come out of there houses, stop and observe other dogs, etc.  Once she has taken it in, she's ready to move on.   She continues to have dog distraction within the classroom setting but when out working with other pups she seems to handle it fine.  Sheena can quickly go into the yellow zone during an outing and many repeat exposures have proven very beneficial for her.

DayInLife: I have just retiredfrom the fd. I get up at 6 am ,have coffe, walk my dog. I do some work around the house, go to the gym, grocery shop. In the fall i help coach the HS football team on a part time basis. I am awy for 3 hrs at the most while at practice. I occassionally have dinner at my brothers house in Mahopac with his family. They have a 4 yr old sheltie female. We vacation at my in-laws house on a lake in Maine a couple of times ayear. I find most of my free time around the house.

GeneralComments: Blanche has overall come a long way. She is a very mellow, calm dog, sometimes to a fault. She can be slow to do commands and a little difficult to motivate at times. We are working on keeping our outings exciting and upbeat so she doesn't mope. She is uncomfortable on grates but we have worked on it recently with a crate divider in our living room and that issue has been resolving. The barking at doors  is still an issue, but she understands that if she barks she has to go kennel - although now, occasionally, she'll go into her kennel TO bark when someone comes to the door. She isn't allowed to greet people who come in unless she is quiet. Go get a toy has helped with that.

GeneralComments: Nichole and I have been working hard with Camille at her weak points.  Camille's biggest problems are, pulling, chewing and attention barking.  We have been trying to switch up where Camille stays and has been helping Camille.  When going to class with Nichole she sometimes will bark or whine or attention but Nichole has been working on this and has been able to get her to settle a lot better.  The chewing we think is built up energy when I took Camille home In Binghamton she got to go on a lot of walks and have a lot of exercise and it seemed to have helped Camille out.  The pulling is a work in progress Camille loves to lead and gets over excited we have been taking the helpful advice we get in class and have been working on it, Camille is a fast learner im sure it will only be a matter of time before we can have this issue under way.

I was pleased with this.        He is very excited around people when them come to visit but will settle down.  I take him to the Mall walking and he is good.         He is strong and if he gets a start on the leash when excited I can not stop him but he will come back when I call.
DayInLife: I am a widow and live in a quiet cul-del-sac neighborhood.  My next door neighbor is very friendly and willing to join me in walks and play with the puppy.   I do some part time work on an assignment basis with Lake County Probate Court as an adoption assessor.   As an active volunteer in many areas, my puppy will, when age appropriate, be exposed to many different places i.e.: schools, nursing homes.       My son and his family live in the area so my puppy will be involved with other dogs and children.    My other children visit often and bring their children and dogs with them.   My house is a large 5 bedroom colonial so it is big enough to accommodate everyone.        I am 76 but exercise regularly, lifting weighs 3 times a week and doing various aerobic exercises.   I have no health problems and really never have had any health episodes.   I will be able to walk the pup regularly.

GeneralComments: Alfred continues to have problems interacting with other dogs. He lunges at dogs who pass him on walks and has bitten others in community run at class. Currently I have chosen to avoid these situations and am now concentrating on several areas where he may benefit from improvement: 1-getting/playing with toys; 2-calmly greeting guests at home; 3-sitting and waiting at doors, especially when leaving rooms and going outside to play; 4-coming when called when off-leash; 5-polite play with our dog. I am trying to be really consistant and he is responding well, especially waiting at doors, even when our dog charges through, and coming when called. I finally found a toy he likes and we have been practicing a lot of 'get a toy' and fetch.

DayInLife: My work schedule is Monday, Wednesday, Friday, from approx 9 am. to 4 pm..  My husband goes to work at 2 pm.  My daughter, (15 yrs old)who will be actively helping me raise the pup, gets home from school at 3:30 p.m.  Another daughter in college studying Zoo Science is very excited about this venture.  EVERYONE in the household will know the GEB rules and verbal/hand commands and when to use them in dealing with the pup.  As the pup gets older, it may be possible for him to come to work with me.  There are 3 cats in the house; they currently are afraid/unfriendly with dogs.  They have shown improvement during the one week while I was puppy-sitting with Karlene (GEB pup).  I have confidence that the cats will accept the dog within a reasonable time period.  Weekends could be anything from horse shows to family gatherings to nothing.  Should the pup need to come with us, he/she will be either safely in his/her crate in my van (back hatch open & weather permitting) or on leash with me.  The pup will NEVER be out of my site.  Our home has a relatively open floor plan, hardwood floors and linoleum; the cat area will be blocked off.  There will be a large fenced area for playtime with the dog, as well as "get busy" space.

EliminationCrateComments: No messes
CrateQuietComments: Wines quiet;ly when he needs to go to the bathroom
KennelCommandComments: Runs to where ever his kennel is and gets inside and lays down
ChewingComments: He knows to chew on his toys and not anything else
HousemannersComments: Good manners, occasionally gets barky because he is tired or wants something else.
LeftUnattendedComments: No problem leaving him in a room when you walk to another, he usually gets up and follows you around
EliminationHouseComments: No accidents in the house in along time
PlaybiteComments: When on his energy spirts he will try and nip your wrists to get your hand to come after him
StealFoodComments: Even if food drops to the floor (human or dog food) he will keep doing what he was doing or watch it.  He has never gotten up to go eat anything that has fallen
OnFurnitureComments: When he gets into his energy spirts he sometimes jumps up to the couch
BarksExcessivelyComments: He learned how to bark in January, we are still working on redirecting his attention when he gets barking.  If you ignorre him he will eventually stop barking and go find a toy to play with.
RaidsGarbageComments: For the most part he stays out of the trash.  He has stuck he head into the trash can in the office and pulled out a kleenex before to get your attention to play with him
CountersDoorsComments: Will sniff as he walks by but never jumps up or begs
JumpsComments: Depends on the day, if he has alot of energy he will want to jump up on the person coming to say hi.  We are working on this by ensuring that the person doesnt just walk up to derek and allows him to sit first.  He has been getting slightly better at this in the past few days.
FriendlyWAnimalsComments: He loves to play with other dogs but just doesnt get a chance to do so alot.
KidsComments: I have never seen him interact with children but he does stop and ears perk up when he hears children voices.  From his sit it sounds as if he played nicely with their kids the whole weekend.
StrangerComments: He loves meeting new people, very energitic and loving dog, gave him a 4 because of sometimes jumping up (noted in 57)
WalkingComments: He has been getting good with walking with out pulling. Sometimes it takes a few blocks before he stops pulling
GetBusyComments: If he has to go and you say get busy he will go.
EliminateRouteComments: In the past week he has been eliminating more on walks.  I am trying to help this by not pulling me to the grass but by me deciding where he goes after he has let me know he needs to.
ChaseComment: Unknown? He likes to watch animals but is never off leash to chase them if he was to
TrafficComments: Can walk close to cars driving down the road and he will stay connected with you.
NoiseComments: He is great with loud noises, most times he will look to see what it was and continue on what he was doing
StairsComments: This is a weird topic, we have a stair way in our townhouse that he loves to go up and down no problem.  When we get to a building that has an enclosed stairway it is hit or miss if he wants to go up them.  At my school he does not like the stairs, he will back up and lay down.  When he does this I do not pressure him into going up the stairs but if someone he knows walks infront of him and encourges him to come then he will do them quickly.  Not sure what he is afraid of here, when he was a little pup he loved going up and down the stairs at school with me no problem.  This also occurs in the parking garage, he will not go close to the stairs but some days he enjoys going up and down them.  A few days ago i brought him into a new space where there were stairs up or a door to the side, we were going to the door to the side but once he saw the stairs he did his backup laydown "i am not moving" Not sure how to help him on this besides giving him the time to check out the stairs on his own time with no pressure.
SitComments: Will sit most of the time with the verbal command, in busy situations or lots of activity you may need to tell him a few times along with the hand motion right infront of his nose
DownComments: Same as 80, he does great usually, in busy situations or lots of action going on he may need extra encourgement
StayComments: Been practicing this in busy situations and he has been getting alot better.  When distractions arise he may break his stay.  Have been working alot on short distance stays and have slowly been building up.
PillsComments: Havn't done this in the past few months but the chewable pills he enjoys
EarsComments: Doesn't mind you touching his ears
NailsComments: He enjoys watching the clipper but is still unsure of it when it makes the clipping sound.  Most of the time it will take 2 people, 1 to clip and 1 to distract him
GeneralComments: Derek looses connection when he sees other dogs/animals walking as well.  He will freeze and observe what they are doing.  If a dog looks like they are walking towards him, he may lurch forward as if he is going to go play with them.  Derek hasn't had any play dates recently and hasn't been around other dogs much recently as well.  He loves to play and plays nicely.

DayInLife: The Rickert Family    Mike works as an insurance adjuster. He has an office inour home and does travel some to do inspections within a couple of hours of Norwalk if necessary possibly 2-3 days a week. He can be gone from a couple of hours to all day. His schedule is very flexible and works around the kids and Lori when it is necessary.    Lori is a substitute teacher for Norwalk City schools. She either works half days or full days depending on what is needed and can be flexible depending on Mikes schedule and the kids. Usually at the beginning of the year I do not work more than 2-3 days per week if that and most of them are half days.    Collin is 15 and starting high school this year. He will be up by 6:30 (and Lori) and and be done by 2:30 so he will be in charge of early morning :)  Dylan is 11 and will start 5th grade. He leaves at 8am and gets home at 315 pm so he can do morning later and afternoon.  Both boys are in fall sorts but they do not happen until later in the evening and they are staggered so we will be running but that means we can be home with the puppy or he can go with in the car for pick or drop off. Most of their activities happen in the evening or on the weekends which will be incorporated ibnto oru lifestyle with the puppy. it will be a learninjg experience for all of us. !!! :)  I would say our family is pretty laid back we our spontaneous at times......if you need more info or have any questions please just ask us. THANKS !!!    Lori is a s ubs

FriendlyWAnimalsComments: she loves playing with other animals but can sometimes get so excited to meet a new "friend" that other animals are intimidated or frightened by her
KidsComments: very friendly with children but can sometimes get a little rough and jumps on them out of excitement
StrangerComments: she loves attention and will gladly take it from anyone
WalkingComments: she is very distractable and can get very excited by things going on around her. it is very difficult to keep her focus while walking and she pulls a lot.
GetBusyComments: sometimes takes a minute of so to find a spot, but will eliminate if you are patient with her
EliminateRouteComments: occasional elimination on walks/ without command
ChaseComment: she has never been given the opportunity to chase wild animals but she gets excited and pulls on her leash when she sees them. My parents have cats which she sometimes chases when we are staying with them
TrafficComments: we have not walk through any considerable traffic. she generally ignores moving vehicles completely but is very interested in parked cars, especially if running, when we walk close to them.
NoiseComments: noises bother her very little. The only noise i have seen her respond to with any fear were gun shots. She jumped and came closer to me and looked at me for reassuring. I pet her and talked to her and she calmed down quickly
StairsComments: no fear or hesitation on stairs. she sometimes pulls on them though
SitComments: sit is her favorite command, though she sometimes lazily slides into a down when asked to sit
StayComments: she will only stay if you remain within her view. if you leave her view she will get up and follow you
ComeOnLeashComments: usually unless she is very interested in something else
ComeOffLeashComments: even if I call her from another floor of the house she'll come running
PillsComments: she does not like taking pills at all and will not swallow them if put in food. I have to hold her mouth closed until she swallows them to get her to take them
EarsComments: she will lay nicely and let you clean her ears but will paw at them occasionally while you do it if you make a tickle or itchy spot
NailsComments: gets a bit impatient toward the end but has no problem with the nails being cut or her paws being handled
GeneralComments: 96. Classes are weekly and we have not missed any in the last 3 months but a class or two may have been canceled in that time. 97. Her behavior in class varies from week to week. Some weeks she does very well and is happy to work with myself or whomever is working with her. Other weeks she is much more interested in the other dogs or whatever else is around to divert her attention and has absolutely no interest in working with anyone. These weeks in is extremely difficult to bring her back and most of the class is spent just trying to get her to focus.
DayInLife: Weekends are pretty flexible and usually free. I have classes from 2:35-6:40 on Tuesdays and Thursdays but can find time between them to take the puppy out to get busy and just get out of the crate for a bit. I also have a class from 9am-11:40 on Wednesdays and Fridays and one other class from 5:25-8:05pm on Wednesdays. I currently work on Wednesdays from noon-3:30 and on Mondays from 10:45-7:30 though I am currently looking for someone to take over my second half of that shift so it will not interfere with the puppy classes. I have a secondary job but the hours vary and are flexible to my schedule. I go to Ithaca College and I live on campus in a single dorm room. I will be leaving the area for Christmas break which is roughly a month and over the summer (about 3 months). I live about 2 hours from Ithaca.

GeneralComments: Guava arrived Oct 27 (as of today Nov 23, 4 weeks).    I included notes from her previous raiser and RM Nicole as a baseline:    - Her name response is great!  - She has average energy and can get overwhelmed in too busy of an environment for her.  Raiser lives in a quieter area of Manhattan if that is possible and Guava does well there.  When there was a bike race in her familiar area she became overwhelmed and needed to take it slow.  - She is reported to have minor crating issues but the raiser lives in an apartment complex and has never had any complaints.   - She went to the beach on a long line and tended to pick on the younger shepherd that was with the group.  - She gets excited about people rather than dogs.  She can self modulate well but needs to work on greetings.   - There are two short videos of Guava playing with GEB pup Karat (11 wks old) and then GEB Mandrake (8 mos. Old).  Guava initially played well with Karat for about 5 minutes or so and then Guava started grabbing on KaratÆs neck, ears, etc and was being very rude. We separated the dogs but Guava kept going back at Karat.  I then had Guava play with an older dog (Mandrake) and they played very appropriately with a toy for about 10-15 minutes.  Not sure if your potential raiser has other dogs at home but I thought I would share that info in case it mattered.  - The biggest thing that I observed about Guava is her noise sensitivity.  As youÆll notice, where we were filming was a pretty busy area in Manhattan with lots of cars and general noise.  Guava seemed fine with this constant noise as she was able to work well with Julia but she was definitely very aware of all the sounds around her û her ears moved around a lot.  There were a few moments when she would hear a sudden loud noise (a motorcycle for example), which would cause her to startle/rush a bit but she seemed to have good recovery.     In comparison to her previous evaluation, not much has changed.  The following is what I am seeing now (one month later):  - no crate issues  - attention barking just for a few minutes when left alone where humans and dogs are insight. Then will settle quietly.  - makes "bunny ears" (ears straight back and laying against head) when alarmed by loud sudden noises.  Recovers quickly and will re-approach objects emitting noise  - No prior history was mention about body handling.  That is one big thing we noticed immediately when we first got her. She does not like to be restrained.  Specifically when rolled on her back, extreme stiffening of her body.  - But oddly enough, will allow you to handle and hold her toes during nail clipping.    - Is unforgiving for quite some time after being released from being restrained.  - have found food does not work as effectively since food gets her too aroused thus adding more stress  - have found successful progression with doing many frequent quick "catch-and-release" method of restraint  - very rude dog play with Brady and Anders, lots of neck biting.  But plays respectfully with older dogs like Leonardo, Ensign, Champ  - I take her to my Dulles Gateway puppy class and she interacted and played politely with the other puppies. She is able to work with any handler. She is an amazingly quick study!  - loves riding in crate in the car  - knows her behaviors  - on socialization outings, super well behaved and responsive to name and loose leash and settling  - good energy level.  Requires average level of exercise and low energy level indoors.

GeneralComments: Rasha is a great dog and very well behaved at home and work. She still has a lot of excitement in town and on training walks. She does eventually get in the think and learn, she is a smart dog and likes to please. She likes smelling and is very distracted by smells, animals and children, especially in groups. She is not well behaved in class, she gets overly excited and has a lot of trouble settling down.
DayInLife: I am a wife and mother of three grown boys. My husband and I are the only ones home and we both work locally. Our house is located on two acres and has a large yard. I work as a realtor in our towns center, a couple miles away from my house. I have flexible part time hours 7 days a week. I will be able to take the pup to work for short periods and walk her in town on the sidewalks frequently. In the summer we spend time at our house in Mystic, CT. There we will walk on a leash on sidewalks daily. I work from home often and go to my office for a just a few hours a day, average 3 hours. In the spring my work gets a bit busier but I can come home between and spend plenty of time exercising and training my pup. We are very excited to incorporate a guiding eyes pup in our life.

HealthComments: Had recent scratch in left eye - healed quickly.
CrateQuietComments: Occasional whining/barking when she needs to get busy.

LeftUnattendedComments: See house manners.

BarksExcessivelyComments: This has improved, but she occasionally barks when she wants attention.

StrangerComments: She's friendly with everybody.

ComeOffLeashComments: This has improved and she comes really well when engaged with us. This is more challenging with more distractions.

EarsComments: She is awesome and lets us clean her ears daily!
NailsComments: She lets us touch her paws, but she won't let us get near her with the clippers.
GeneralComments: Tricia is still really high energy. She is getting better at settling in the house, but still needs improvement in this area, along with house manners and nail clipping. She plays well with other dogs, but is dog-distracted on walks. There's never a dull moment with Tricia. :)

DayInLife: I am homeschooled, so I am pretty flexible. I have work to do during the day as well as some online classes a couple times a week. This fall I will take some classes at a community college, so that will take up some more time. I generally do my work, take my dog for a work, run some errands with my mom, etc. I have a piano lesson once a week. I volunteer at PSR on Sunday's and am starting to volunteer at a free medical clinic. I will probably volunteer at the medical clinic about once a week or so for now. My weekends vary. We go to church on Sundays and I volunteer at PSR afterwards. That's really the only weekend commitment we have. So, I am home pretty often. We have another dog in the house--female. We initially thought about preferring a male but now think maybe a female would be better.

KennelCommandComments: with food, doesn't always go in without some kibble thrown in
BarksExcessivelyComments: barks sometimes, we are working on this by leaving the room, etc
JumpsComments: good most of the time, if a person owns a dog she may try and jump a bit
FriendlyWAnimalsComments: overly friendly, we still keep her at a distant because she may pull and jump on other dogs sometimes.
WalkingComments: pulls and smells constantly.  We work on this all the time, and it gets better but is inconsistant
GetBusyComments: pee yes, poop sometims
StairsComments: has improved alot. Still working on her staying next to us when going up the stairs.  She can go ahead of us often when going upstairs, but is very good going downstairs.
ComeOnLeashComments: Usually, but if she smells something when on a walk it can take sometimes before she does this.
ComeOffLeashComments: inside.  We have never done this outside because we do not have a fenced in area to work on this with her.
EarsComments: very good. We say "ears" and she sits so we can clean them.
NailsComments: we can get her into an 'over' and hold her paws.  But after a bad clip one time andmaking her bleed, we have been afraid to try it again. Our fault, not hers!
GeneralComments: Thimbles house manners, aside from some barking and whining, are great.  (She can be laying on her bed and just start a low, sad sounding whining.  We don't know why this happens.  We tend to ignore it, but sometimes it can escalate to barking.  Sometimes if we pet her or lay down next to her, she stops).  Her loose leash walking is inconsistant.  She pulls and smells constantly.  We have been working on this since she was a puppy.  Its a case of 1 step forward, 2 steps back.  We think we must be missing something or not reading the situation apporpriately.  Last weeks dog behavior class helped alot.  We can read her body language and determine when she may be stressed, but we are not always sure what to do about it.
DayInLife: I start my day by waking up with the kids at 7am, have breakfast and see them off. My schedule is varied day to day. I work for myself in residential real estate and as a commercial actor doing voice overs. I recently lost over 100lbs and am much more active than before. I usually work on Sundays doing open houses or working with clients but I don't leave until 10:30 and am home by 5. During the week I can come and go as appts are scheduled or work from home. Most of the time I go to my office which is 20 blocks away. I would be able to bring a dog to work if I don't have showings. I don't travel for work outside of NYC but will go to visit my parents who live on an acre n CT about an hour away. We go away at the end of August to Cape Cod for two weeks and stay close while the kids are in camp traveling over the 4th to Tanglewood.

ExerciseType: daily inside house play and brief walks, 2x week vigorous outdoor play
EliminationCrateComments: no accidents, but blanket shreds and she sheds!
JumpsComments: occasionally shell get really excited when the person does; we try to stay away from those situatiuons
FriendlyWAnimalsComments: curious from a distance
DayInLife: Both Kirk and Kiley will have equal care for the pup. As time goes on, we will be flexible to see what changes we need to make to ensure the best possible upbringing for the pup that we can. As of right now we plan that Kirk will do midnight shifts, and first AM shift, then Kiley will take on before she leaves for work around 8 am. Dog walker/neighbor will let out, following guidelines we instruct with. At 2pm, Kiley will be back on lunch break to let out and train. At 4pm, Kirk will be back for the evening, Kiley will be back between 5 and 6. Either one of us might have a day/night off, but the other will be around. Come May, Kirk will be on flights for Air Force, but will usually know in advance when he will be out. Kiley will easily be able to make the accommodations, plus the pup will be older by then. Kiley may have the occasional day or night away, and Kirk can do the same. Weekends we'll both be around. Kiley will take the pup with her to as many places as possible, like her own kid. She will choose as many places, activities, and events that the pup can attend with her. Kirk and Kiley will expose the pup to as many various scenarios as possible.    No known allergies, injuries, physical situations, environmental concerns, etc. that could be a problem.

GeneralComments: Rumor is an amazing pup!  Once her "extenders" were removed from her teeth and she was able to chew on bones, have toys and play with other dogs, her stress-energy level completely disappeared and she has been very relaxed and mellow!  She no longer barks at other dogs or in her kennel, and her house manners are remarkable.  She has been a true joy to raise - despite the challenges that we faced with the treatment for her "base narrow canines," her sensitive tummy, her persistent barking and jumping, Rumor has truly matured into a wonderful, obedient, sweet girl.  The only negative about this whole experience is that I will miss her dreadfully when she leaves for training in 2 short weeks.  Thank you so much for giving me the opportunity to work with this special girl!

GeneralComments: Hugo is still somewhat puppy like in his demeanor and behaviors.  When he gets excited, takes him some time to shake it off and settle down.  Will still jump on me if something startles or agitates him outside, but this behavior has started to diminish.   The week he spent on a puppy sit with many other dogs and new social and environment exposures has resulted in some real evidence of maturation, and mellowing of the spontaneous explosions of puppyness.  We are starting to see what the adult dog Hugo will become - we think he will be wonderful.
DayInLife: We are a two-person household, no children, lots of family, friends, nieces and nephews, good neighbors.  Our home is calm and quiet; pretty orderly and clean.  We laugh a lot, and we are prepared for major puppy disruption!   We are both very recently retired, still adjusting to the blessing of free time!  Bernie still does part time consulting occasionally, from home.  I might look for something part time, close to home, but have no immediate plans.  We expect to be home, at least one of us, most times. We travel only occasionally, have lots of hobbies and interests.  Gardening, handcrafts, woodworking, church, community involvement, etc.   We usually get up early (even earlier with a pup!), and have a neighborhood where we can walk safely, which we do often.  There are no sidewalks, but most areas are very safe for walking. We do our usual chores through out the day, walk to get the mail from our post office, sometimes go out to eat, but also like to cook/bake and eat at home.   We have nice family gatherings from time to time, home and away (nearby).  We are fortunate to live a happy and peaceful life, and look forward to the opportunity to successfully raise an impressionable young dog and teach the basics it will need to provide such an important service later in it's life.   Stephanie Vaughey

She'll be with Avis Hull for a few days when I have cataract surgery.  Val particularly commented on her lovely house manners.  When she plays with Pixel, they can both get snarly faced, but Karise responds well to "toy".  Her training has been interrupted recently because she had a split heat and was out of action for six weeks.  We still had play dates with Pixel, but she stayed home the rest of the time.  We've started back up this past week, and she's doing well.  I'm concentrating on multiple small slices of various experiences.  We had our first extended walk in the woods today.  Alleluia!

HealthComments: Had 2 issues with small marblesize masses - both dissolved - no reoccurance since Fall 2013
BarksExcessivelyComments: Working on demand barking - techiniques have improved behavior
FriendlyWAnimalsComments: Takes long time ot settle around other dogs, easlily dog distracted.  Working on better behavior.
GeneralComments: Ludwig dos well with his commands.  His house manners are fabulous and he is very amenable to grooming.  I know he needs work with dog distraction and demand barking.  I am using techniques recommended from the last swap including immediate distraction using commands followed, if necessary, by a leash time out for 20-30 seconds behind a door with praise on release and he has shown improvement in a short period of time.  Dog distraction will require more cooridination of dog outings with others and as the weather breaks this will become easier for all to coordinate.  This winter has been brutal for all.
DayInLife: I am a single person who lives in my own home.  I have friends and family over to my house on a regular basis.  I will be raising the pup with my 13 year old niece and she has been very engaged in the learning process so we can be a consistent team for the pup.  She does not live with me but understands the responsibility of raising a pup for GEB.  I have a large backyard but no fence around the yard.  I have my own business so my schedule is mostly flexible.  The pup would have exposure to a variety of business environments traveling with me as I work.  Generally, I am up for work between 7:00-7:30am.  I arrive at work between 8:00am-9:00am.   Once a month I have a committee meeting from 8:00am-10:00 am.  I would take the pup to work and leave it crated during this meeting.  I also have a once a month evening meeting and the pup would be able to join me at those meetings.    Every other Saturday from September through February I volunteer for a business class from 8:00am-11:30am.  My niece would care for the pup at these times or the pup could come to class on occasion.  Other than that I have a normal life with friends and family going out at times.  My niece and I are committed to meeting the needs of the pup at all times.    Sometimes I work on the weekends but the pup will join me whenever and whereever possible. Please call me if you have specific questions regarding my schedule.  This is all I can thnk of right now.

GeneralComments: the biggest obstacle still is around other people and dogs.  He is still very excitable but getting much better about calming down in less time.  He is still showing some fears, mostly shadows or strange objects.  I see it mostly when he is free to roam in our fenced back yard.  He is still very much a puppy in his behavior yet his house manners are very good.  Now he does sleep outside his crate at night with free roam of the house without incident.  Although he will stay in a room by himself by choice, he more often will choose to be where people are.  He is not attached to one member of the family.  He is an extremely sweet, lovable dog but he is still having issues with his confidence.
DayInLife: I am 15 and go to school until 7:40am to 2:20pm. I have recently started my softball season to which I get home to about anywhere between 5:30-6:30pm. On Friday's at 6:30pm to 7:30pm I have dance. Other then those times I'm home. I have no injuries or any problems that would affect anything. I like to think of myself as a pretty laid back person and probably will have much time with puppy!

BarksExcessivelyComments: Sometimes barks when left alone and she doesn't know where you are
RaidsGarbageComments: Improving; stays out of kitchen -- still curious about short bathroom can
WalkingComments: Improving;  still pulls when distractions are around
StairsComments: Sometimes rushes last new steps to get to landings
ComeOffLeashComments: Sometimes doesn't come if she has a toy and things you are going to take it away
GeneralComments: Still has distraction issues with strange dogs while walking. Has improved greatly on pack walks but still struggles when a strange dog passes close by. Have been increasing distance and praising check-ins.
DayInLife: We live a fairly active lifestyle on a day to day basis. During the week JJ works in DC and typically leaves the house around 5:45a so he can take the puppy out to get busy early in the morning before he leaves for work. He returns home around 4:45p. Occasionally he also has the opportunity to work from home. The first half of this year he has been involved in a lot of travel for work but due to the program he will be home a lot more starting at the end of May. Rachel has a more flexible schedule and is able to work from home a majority of the time. She typically goes into her office either in DC or Alexandria, 2-3 days a week for 6-8 hours. She doesn’t leave until 7:30 so the puppy will be out again, fed, and let out a final time and crated before she leaves. When the puppy is ready, it will go to work with her on those days. Prior to that, our neighbor’s son, who will be home on vacation from college, lives ¾ mile away and will be available to let the puppy out and feed between 10:30-11:30. Rachel is usually home by 2:30. In the afternoons/evenings during the week we tend to stay low key with an occasional activity one or two nights a week. We will go to the gym or go on a run in the park. Although we will have to be more conscious of our timing, we do have a 5 year old German Shepherd (Harper) who we have make sure gets adequate exercise and try to incorporate her into our plans as much as possible (As we will with the puppy). On the weekends, we stay fairly busy however we are lucky to live in a very dog-friendly town where even pets are welcome out and in stores. We enjoy taking Harper with us hiking, to the park or to the beach. We do like to take weekend trips once or twice a month but when we do travel, it is normally no more than three hours away and we normally take Harper with us. We live in a single level ranch home with a finished basement (with carpeted stairs). We do have a fenced in back yard with a 6-foot wooden fence which will give Harper and the puppy room a safe area to run around and play.

EliminationHouseComments: rare accidents as long as I limit his water

ExerciseType: walking, running, playing fetch, playing tug
KennelCommandComments: Not always good from a distance; for example, if we're in a completely different room and I say "Go Kennel", he doesn't always go. If we're in sight of it, he always goes
PlaybiteComments: He sometimes gets a little "mouthy" when playing with some people (not with me)
JumpsComments: I can't give him a 5 because he has jumped twice.
FriendlyWAnimalsComments: Yes, he's friendly, but he's distracted by them
WalkingComments: At work, no problems at all.  Outside in a new place? Much more challenging. He has become interested in everything and is getting distracted by things that didn't use to distract him.
EliminateRouteComments: a couple of months ago, he started wanting to pee multiple times on his walks in the neighborhood.  We are currently telling him to get busy several times such that we are controlling it instead of him, but we need advice on how to deal with this
ChaseComment: If the animal is right in front of him, I think he would chase if he weren't on the leash.  If the animal isn't right in front of him, he watches it sometimes (but not always) but doesn't try to chase
TrafficComments: I think he's confident, but he is getting distracted by different noises now.
DownComments: Is sometimes slow to "down" in a new outdoor environment
StayComments: He's not perfect, but he doesn't break his stay very often
ComeOffLeashComments: It depends on circumstances.  Yesterday, he was upstairs in the far corner of the house when I called him to get dressed.  He flew down the hall and stairs and put his jacket on in about 2 seconds. Conversely, sometimes if he's outside and really sniffing something good, he is slow to come.
PillsComments: I think he would take them fine, but we have no experience other than Heartworm
EarsComments: Not really sure. I think he would do fine.
NailsComments: He hates having his nails clipped.
GeneralComments: He does spend time in other homes and locations. He is fairly well travelled and never has any difficulties. He also spends time at work away from me with a couple of select people and he always does well.   Biggest issue:  dog and smell distraction.  If there's a dog, he can't focus on anything else.  We can work a smell area until he starts ignoring it, but then when we encounter the next new thing, we have to go through the cycle again.  He is very willful in that circumstance--he will lunge as far as he can and it is very difficult to get him engaged and focused again. These distractions are more significant now than they were when he was  younger and more difficult to manage now that he is 77 lbs of muscle
DayInLife: work days:  we both have flexible work schedules and I plan to work 7-hour days this summer.  Children are grown, so we have no significant evening commitments. We live in a single family suburban home with a fenced yard.    wake up--take turns showering, getting breakfast, etc while the other interacts with the puppy  we plan for one of us to go into work early--say 0630or so and the other will leave for work at 0915 after a walk to the bus stop to see the kids and the bus. Pup into the kennel.  1200-1300  Gypsy home from work for lunch. Feed pup lunch, walk puppy, play, short training session etc. Pup into kennel for afternoon nap time.  1600  Ed home from work. Walk puppy in neighborhood, training session, etc. Ed goes about his business (such as working in yard), seeks out socialization opportunity  1800  Gypsy home from work. Dinner, walk, training, play, short outing or excursion for socialization activity, etc.    Weekends:  lots of time for socialization. We usually go for a long walk at least one day, frequently at the wildlife refuge.  We will spend lots of summer weekends on our land in WV, where there are lots of opportunities for exposure to new things like animals, farm implements and equipment, trucks, boats, and two friendly dogs we know. We like to hike, bike, kayak. We have a child carrier (enclosed trailer) that can safely accommodate a dog, our boat has space for a dog (and we have life jackets for the dog) and the water we go out on is calm and not deep.  This summer, we will make a point of making trips into the city.  Trips planned include a road trip to Connecticut staying with family, a family reunion camping trip to Solomon's Island, MD

ExerciseType: 1-2 long walks per day, playing in apartment, and puppy play dates as often as possible . When were in PA we will run him around the backyard every day 2x a day
CrateQuietComments: He whines when he needs to get busy. We've also notified that if we move the place of his crate too drastically he may whine/bark initially until settled in
ChewingComments: He has a fondness for socks but will "out" them as soon as asked.  He has never chewed anything else though and is not destructive.
HousemannersComments: He has seen my dog jump onto furniture and will occasionally put a paw up if you're on a bed but responds will when corrected. He also had a bad habit of eating cat food off of the floor. We spent some time working with him to correct that and in general now he will just sit in front of it.
LeftUnattendedComments: If busy with toys he is great alone but will eat things off of the floor so we haven't left him alone yet.  He's great alone in a crate or enclosed corral but now with free run of the house/apartment.
PlaybiteComments: When he is very energetic he will occasionally play bite. We've been working very hard on this.
StealFoodComments: This relates to the earlier housemanners question. Tobias (if left unattended) will occasionally eat the cat food or something off of the ground but we've been working on that.
OnFurnitureComments: He will not jump on furniture but if my dog at home jumps up he will occasionally put one paw up.
BarksExcessivelyComments: We've fixed his barking when unattended problem, but if we change the location of his crate drastically enough he will sometimes bark/whine
RaidsGarbageComments: He does not get into garbage (unless something is on the floor then he may try to get it)
JumpsComments: If we do a people greeting while he's very energetic  he will jump on he person, else he is very good.
WalkingComments: Tobias is extremely good with walking on a leash and has been surprisingly good at checking in from day one. Occasionally, if something flies by or there is food on the ground he will pull but he generally isn't that hard to redirect. We have notified that when Bram works with him and I'm tagging along Tobias will not be as connected with Bram and will look at me. If Bram is alone, Tobias does very well.
ChaseComment: Tobias will chase butterflies/moths and my one cat that is very afraid of dogs. He does not, however, chase my other cat who loves dogsled. Tobias will be very sweet and give him kisses.
TrafficComments: He is really good about crossing streets and only showed mild concern from a very large truck. After receiving treats and praise, he was fine.
DownComments: Sometimes he is very slow, but knows down very well.
GeneralComments: Tobias is really really good! He responds well to corrections in behavior and learns very quickly. He is extremely food motivated which is great for training, but makes food on the ground extremely alluring. He is dog-distracted and since he is used to have 1 or fewer dogs in class that is something we'll have to work on. He also will jump during people greetings so since coming back on campus we have been working extensively on that. We have taken him to a few stores/restaurants (with permission of the owners) and he has done magnificently! He will settle very well and is very good at doing commands there. He does occasionally play-bite but that is also something we've been working on and now in general he just licks. We do have a home-swap planned from the 29th-3rd while we are away. He will be with Zareen and Merrill.

ComeOffLeashComments: with gusto
GeneralComments: I am not sure who is going to read this or if my comments are appropriate for this purpose.  This is my first GEB experience.  I love animals and I have always had them but never have structured their environment in this fashion.  I am learning alot with Ames.  I am certain he is a very smart dog.  I am certain he has a super personality.  He loves to please and he loves to be connected.  He is a lover.  He always has a smile on his face and he gives love constantly.  I have noticed that he loves the outdoors.  He would stay outside all day in any weather if you let him.  He also loves to work.  When we are in class he is very happy and he does not like to end that experience.  He knows when it is over and his body language will change and he gets a sad look on his face.  He also loves to smell things and he has a very keen sense of smell.  Sometimes he is more distracted by smells than by other animate objects.  If Ames makes it through this program I would like to say now - in case I don't get the chance to later - I think he will be happiest with a person who is very affectionate and who has a true love for him and will hug him and talk to him and pet him constantly. Ames is just a lover.  Sometimes he will go up to Clementine when she is sleeping and he will lay next to her and put his arm around her and sleep.  He does best when he is touching and being touched.

HealthComments: Had an eye discharge that went away on its own.
StoolComments: A little soft about once a week.
ExerciseType: Walking and ball play on occasion
EliminationCrateComments: Never got busy in his crate
CrateQuietComments: Quiet at night but resists and barks when we are home.
KennelCommandComments: Good with me, not with my wife
ChewingComments: He chewed some furniture his first month, now he is on to any scraps found on the floor and shoes when he can get them
HousemannersComments: He barks and bites sometimes and is jumping up on the bed. We are working on settle.
LeftUnattendedComments: Assuming he has an appropriate toy or is tired.
EliminationHouseComments: If excited or not taken outside for 2.5 hours + he will pee in the house. He is going a couple of weeks without an accident.
PlaybiteComments: He still thinks we are tasty but is getting better. He bites to get our attention but can be easily distracted with a toy.
StealFoodComments: He will jump to get food from the table and will snatch anything that falls to the floor.
OnFurnitureComments: Jumps on furniture but only when we are on it.
BarksExcessivelyComments: He barks for attention (to play, go outside, or just when he is restless).
RaidsGarbageComments: He is good but if something is smelly he will get it and take it to his crate.
CountersDoorsComments: He surfs the counters if there is food around.
JumpsComments: He will jump on anyone.
FriendlyWAnimalsComments: Too friendly actually. He loses focus when a dog is near.
KidsComments: Too friendly, he loves kids and goes crazy when they are near.
StrangerComments: Very friendly. If they show an interest in him he is very excited to say hi.
WalkingComments: We are working on this but still have a ways to go. He still pulls me towards the good scents.
GetBusyComments: I don't think he truly understands the command but he goes quickly and where I want him to go.
EliminateRouteComments: If we go on a long walk or he gets really excited he will pee.
ChaseComment: If our cats are running he chases until they get on the bed.
TrafficComments: If there are a lot of cars and trucks going by he can lose focus but he is generally good.
NoiseComments: They will cause him to lose focus but I have never seen him afraid of a noise.
StairsComments: Sometimes he goes slowly down stairs but when prompted he goes up and down.
SitComments: Sometimes he half sits to cheat but he definitely knows the command.
DownComments: With a treat he is good. After about ten downs with a treat he will do it without but not before.
StayComments: He will stay until called but will lose attention after a minute if something else is going on.
ComeOnLeashComments: When I have a treat he will come.
ComeOffLeashComments: We are working on it but if I am too far away he ignores me. If the command is loud he will come.
PillsComments: Never given a pill.
EarsComments: No problems.
NailsComments: I can clip his nails but we need to work on his acceptance.
GeneralComments: I think he is doing good so far. He still has his challenges like jumping, barking, leash walking and biting but he is getting better all the time. He rarely pees in the house, has never soiled his crate, and has pretty much stopped chewing household appliances. He still enjoys an inappropriate chew toy like a paper towel or shoe when he can get one but he is doing this less and less. Loose leash walking is still a daily struggle, he understands the concept and is getting better but loses focus constantly given the amazing scents on NYC sidewalks. He has gotten a lot better around other dogs, children and things that move. I am able to control him more and keep him in or near the think and learn zone until the moving person is right upon him. He is much better in class as well though barking is still a struggle. He is great with sit, good with down, heel, get busy and close when I have a food lure. Without a food lure getting him to respond is very difficult. He is a great dog, a joy to be around and a wonderful companion.
DayInLife: We live on the first floor of a 100 year old 5 floor, 10 unit walk-up. We have no one below us and only one direct neighbor that is separated from us by a brick wall, though we can hear through it. Our super lives across the hall and she dog sits her sisters shitzhu about once a month for a couple of days. Above us is a 1.5 year old golden retriever. We have two cats, one fat and lazy and one a former stray that is very nervous. Our building and street are quiet but the surrounding neighborhood is busy.     As for lifestyle, I work at the Petco 2 blocks from our house, allowing me to come home during work to take the dog out. I work three different shifts and my schedule changes almost weekly. I work either 7-4pm, 11-8pm or 2-11pm. On a 7-4 shift I get up, feed the cats, get myself ready and then head to work. On an 11-8 shift I typically go grocery shopping and then head to work. On a 2-11 shift I run errands and clean the house, then head to work. I perform most of the domestic duties as my wife works full-time and is in school. With my free time I enjoy running in Central Park or on the East River. There are many parks and fun places for a dog to explore around our neighborhood. On the weekends we typically stay on the UES, taking a walk or seeing a movie. We go out to lunch or dinner somewhere and on Sundays we typically stay around the house as it is the only day we both generally have off together. We also really enjoy traveling. In the next year we will likely head to CA and FL. We would like to have a child at some point next year as well.

ComeOffLeashComments: with treats, other times varies
NailsComments: n/a because sidewalk wears them down
DayInLife: I work from home.  We live on the ground floor and basement of a 5 floor walk-up. My days are generally flexible, except for my share of getting the kids to school/activies. To the extent feasibale, we will integrate the pup into these errands.    We do long weekends and most school vacations at our new second home, in New Paltz.  We will bring the pup with us by car.    While our house is busy when the kids are home, we are not big exercisers or walkers, so we don't need a very active pup.  More docile may be better, but we leave it in your discretion.  I have raised only male animals thus far (two dogs and four cats) so I would prefer to try a female.  But the gender is less important than getting the best suited dog.    We hope to go somewhere warm for a week during a school break (most likely Feb) so we would want a sitter for that time.  We will know, and initiate the request in advance.    Thanks, we look forward to raising a great pup.

DayInLife: I work from home with my own business of typing up transcription on my computer. I have a very flexible day. I get up early to get everyone up and moving, so with a puppy, I plan on getting up even earlier to make sure I have time to take care of puppy's needs as well. After everyone is off to school or work, I usually start working. I make my own hours, so I will be able to take plenty of breaks to spend with puppy whenever I can. Once my children and my husband come home, they are all happy and willing to play with puppy and help with some of the training. We are all very excited to have this puppy in our lives. Weekends we love to get out and go hiking or do things as a family. We live in a neighborhood with sidewalks and we have a backyard where we can go out and play. There are lots of opportunities for different experiences in this area. We have a lot of plans for what kind of places to bring puppy over the next year and a half.

DayInLife: i will get the dog in the summer so this is my summer schedule---  -wake up at 5:30-6 to take dog to get busy and eat  -get myself ready  -go to work at 11am, take pup with me  -3pm take pup home and put in crate. i go walk dogs til 4  -exercise/train pup  -7pm dinner   -10-11pm go to bed    my school schedule---  -5:30 wake up take pup to get busy and eat  -6am get ready  -7:10 go to school and pup goes in crate  -3pm get home to take pup out(someone will come home to fed and let out pup a few times while i was at school)  -train/exercise pup  -7pm dinner  -9:30-10:30 go to bed    on the weekends we have a home in PA that we go to.  it is flexible and not far away so any activities that us and the pup will have to attend is no problem. the pup will come with us to our home. there we will be able to spend a lot of time with the pup exercising and training.      i have dog walking jobs all year and might have some babysitting during the school year after school that pup should be able to come with me. we live in a small town so the pup will have lots of socialization to many things.i have a family or four; my mom, dad and 10 year old sister. i am 15 years old. we have never had any dogs but as i said i have a few dog walking and sitting jobs.

ExerciseType: walking and playing in yard with family dog
CrateQuietComments: if there are a lot of people in the house & Cora is kenneled then she will demand bark
ChewingComments: She has made so much progress in this area and is easily redirected.  If she manages to sneak a child's toy then she will chew it if we don't notice her right away but she is not chewing on furniture or windowsills anymore
HousemannersComments: The counter surfing has improved, but she still attempts to pop up on counters if she thinks no one is paying attention. She also still take toys or shoes that are left unattended (very rarely destroying them though).  She does much better in other homes, far less likely to take things or jump on counters
LeftUnattendedComments: For 10-15 minutes but only in an area with restricted access - otherwise she would try to eat a plant or child's toy
StealFoodComments: If people are distracted or leave their food out then Cora will attempt to steal it. She does not, however, do this to me and my food
OnFurnitureComments: The only times I catch her on furniture are when she is playing with our family dog and follows our dog onto a couch.
BarksExcessivelyComments: Mild demand barking at times
RaidsGarbageComments: our trash cans mostly have lids and she makes no attempt to open them.  Open trash is more tempting to her when we come across it
CountersDoorsComments: if she thinks there is food and that no one is watching then she will attempt to get on a counter
JumpsComments: when in the green zone Cora does very well but needs to take some time to get there.  Once she has been around someone for awhile she does not attempt to jump on them at all
FriendlyWAnimalsComments: sometimes gets over excited when meeting a new animal
KidsComments: she loves children and sometimes wants to get too close to lick them
StrangerComments: sometimes gets over excited when meeting new people
WalkingComments: Once she is in the green zone she walks fairly well, but this can take some time
GetBusyComments: She is not as good defecating on command
ChaseComment: If she has enough distance from the other animal then it is not an issue
TrafficComments: If she is in the green zone then she is fine, but it takes some time to get there
NoiseComments: Very few noises cause her to startle, she can however get inhibited
StairsComments: Tends to try to race up and down stairs when shes not in the green zone
SitComments: If there are a lot of distractings it can take some time to get her to respond.  changing one of the three D's usually helps
DownComments: Sames as sit, once she s in the green zone she is much more responsive
StayComments: duration is getting better for this
ComeOffLeashComments: Does well with minimal distractions
NailsComments: once she is calm she does fantastic with nail trims
GeneralComments: Cora has a lot of energy and can be distracted easily at times, so getting into the green zone can take awhile.  But when she is there, she is fantastic.  Between the snow, illnesses and an unexpected death in my family there was a period of time when socialization was not as often as I would have liked But the progress she shows when we are on a regular schedule is so encouraging.  She has a sweet disposition and is a pleasure to work with.

HealthComments: Just getting an antibiotic for puppy zits! Perfect otherwise.
ExerciseType: Playing in fenced yard, tugging, playing with our other dog, walks
ChewingComments: Gradually improving but still a puppy.
BarksExcessivelyComments: Sometimes barks at our dog or cat. Is that inapprpriste?
WalkingComments: Good w no distraction. Still working on distractions.
DayInLife: Tina is a realtor and is self employed with a changeable, flexible schedule. Andrew works 8-5 about 20 mins from our home but has flexibility to come home from work early, leave late, etc. on a regular basis at his discretion. Generally the last person to leave our house for work leaves between 8 and 9am. One of us is always home by 5:30pm. Tina works from home frequently and has a large amount of flexibility to take care of the puppy's need to get busy every few hours. Andrew will also be able to come home from work when Tina is unable. It will be an adjustment for us but we are prepared for the puppy's needs. Our weekend schedule varies but we are usually in and out of the house all day (every few hours). We do travel every 1-2 months but often go on trips that would be dog friendly so we don't foresee that being an issue too often with needing to do excessive house swaps. We have 1 cat and 1 adult female labrador - age 7 - she is a rescue and we've had her for 3.5 years. Our lab really prefers the company of male dogs - we will be flexible with whatever works for GEB but if a male dog is an option, we think it will be a much smoother integration into our household. No life/job/baby changes planned. We live in a single family home in the suburbs. Our yard is not fenced but we walk our dog at least twice daily and have no issue with walking our pup frequently on a leash. It will never be left or put outside.
