DayInLife: Dave and I live in a single family home in Vienna with a fenced yard and "get busy" area for our 3 dogs - 2 German Shepherds and a Yorkie.  We also have a cat who has been around our dogs since she came to us as a kitten and even with claws, she NEVER swats the dogs.    Our daily routine:  Dave wakes between 5 and 6 a.m.  lets the dogs out, feeds them, lets them out again.  I usually wake at 5:45 am, go to the pool and swim, come home, dress and leave for work.  Dave will then take the 3 dogs and walk 4 miles. (We started walking 3 dogs when we had Belmont).  He is home with them most of the day except when he does errands; he grooms the shepherds a couple times a week and I groom the Yorkie once a month (bath and clipping).  He does a second walk later in the day depending on the temperature outside.  I come home from work and we are on the porch or relaxing inside and then eat dinner.  Before bed, the dogs go out again.  When we get the pup, I will adjust my routine to include a morning walk and an evening walk as well as "play" since Dave will not be able to walk 4 dogs.  I will also ensure the progressive socialization of the pup (had to do this with Tex); started with short walks in the cul de sac, then the next neighborhood, then the little shopping plaza up the street, etc.      Dave works for NVCC; he is an Associate Dean and Teacher; most of his work is virtual.  When regular semesters are in session, he goes into the campus for about 4 hours 2 - 3 times a week.  I live about 8 min. from my job and have flexibility with telework.  When we raised Belmont she went to work with me on the Metro a couple times a week (downtown D.C.).    I swim because of my lumbar discs; can't run anymore.  On the weekends I take the shepherds and play ball (which they love) to let them stretch their legs.  On Saturdays we often take the younger shepherd, Tex,  and the Yorkie (Huey) to Reston Town Center where James Oliver (DogU) has group socialization for many of his clients and their dogs.  We have been taking Tex out since he was a pup (almost 2 years now).    This has been a fabulous experience for the noise, kids, and crowd socialization.     We have 2 local grandkids (10 and 8) who have dogs and have been around our Belmont for the past 5 years.  They will spend the night a couple times a quarter.    Our schedules are very flexible and we both plan to take the Pup to work on various days after the little one earns his/her vest.    Weekends I take advantage of the time off to take the shepherds on a long walk on the bike path; they are champs and can handle the bikers, runners, and other dogs as well as strollers.    My personal work travel is minimal and very manageable; Dave does not travel.  Our personal travel; we will be going to Europe in Oct. for bike trip:)    I currently am an Adoption Coordinator for Lab Rescue and have been reducing my applicant pool so I am "freed" up when we get a pup.  My time will be dedicated to the pup.   It has been just 2 years since Tex joined our pack at age 3 months, so we are puppy refreshed:)    I hope this helps!  WOOF, Mary

DayInLife: I currently work two jobs.  One full time with a schedule of 33.5 hours per week 5 minutes from my home.  This allows me to come home for lunch daily.  The other is  part-time evenings and weekends consisting of approximately 15 hours.  The evening shift is 5-8 and the weekends are 8am-2pm.  Once again I am within 5-10 minutes from home.  They are very understanding and interested in my commitment to raising a GEB puppy and have already altered my schedule so I can attend puppy classes on Monday evenings.  I am very much a homebody and enjoy gardening, bike riding and walking, hiking in the summer and reading, cooking and baking in the winter, hence the 20lb gain from our past fabulous WNY winter.   My 20 year old daughter is home from school for the summer and works at our complex as a lifeguard.  She is attending a local college and is studying Animal Behavior and Ecology Conservation.  She is very excited about this opportunity to raise a puppy for a visually impaired person, a child or some other alternative career.  We have never had a puppy or dog as this is something I did not want to even attempt without having the proper training to be a successful and responsible dog guardian.  I thought this would be a fabulous experience for both of us and give us a taste of being responsible puppy/dog lovers and owners for the benefit of someone in need.  We are animal lovers but have always been cat people and let's be honest, it doesn't take much to be a good cat caretaker.  We currently have two house cats that do not go outside.  They are both spayed females.  Pixie is a year and a half and Belle is going to turn 4 on July 7th.  They have a love hate relationship and both sleep on purr pads on my bed (this is the love part) or in their cat tree.  They also love to watch the birds in our feeder from the sliding glass door in the living room.  We live in a two-story townhouse in a beautiful parklike setting.  We have lots of green space and plenty of opportunities for socialization.  We also live very close to a village for walking experiences.  My daughter and I walk on a regular basis and are both in perfect health.  We are hoping for a sweet female to complete our girl pad!  We can't wait to meet our new family member and are hopeful it will be soon after our "graduation" as I am off from my full time job for the summer!  Thank you for your time and we are looking forward to working to be the best puppy raisers ever!    Lisa and Emma Miller

DayInLife: Most of my day is flexible. I stay home with two daughters, Ava (15 yrs) and Ashley (11 yrs).  My husband is home a little more than 1/2 the month and travels the rest of it.  The girls are self-sufficient and help with chores.  I get up and make them breakfast/lunch for school, and they are off by 7:30-2:50 school days.  Once they leave I usually eat breakfast, check e-mail, pay bills, paperwork, gardening, pick up the house, grocery shop, exercise (walk, bike, weights at home or yoga), or work.  I own a small business (TootSweetSoapShack.com) making handcrafted goat's milk soap and cream, and sugar scrubs.  Making products usually takes about 90 min - 2 hours at a time start to finish, then wrap the products at a separate time.  I deliver my products locally to 3 small stores as needed, and wrap up local orders to leave on my porch.  I try to start dinner before the kids get home, we usually eat dinner after school before activities start.  Most of my older daughter's activities (Pole Vault Club, Aerial Silks, Dance Classes, Village Project Volunteer, Key Club Member, Horse Riding Sessions) are at the high school or in town.   My younger daughter Ashley is involved with Oberlin Choristers (Monday night practice and occasional recitals), Vocals at School of Rock in Rocky River (45 min lesson once a week and 1.5 hour band practice), guitar lesson at our house on Sundays, and occasional Art classes.  We participate in carpools, but should not be away from the house for more than 2 hours, and plan to bring the puppy with us whenever possible.  Both vehicles can accommodate a crate without a problem.  We will have house guests as our family lives in other parts of the country but visit frequently.   Our summer is pretty laid back with some traveling. My husband is a pilot for United Airlines, and plans to contact the chief pilot to find out about airplane travel with the puppy as we would like to bring it with us when it's old enough.  We were planning on going to Seattle to visit family for Christmas, but if the puppy isn't old enough to join us we will postpone until it is.  Next summer (July) we have an extended family reunion/heritage trip to Sweden and Prague with my husband's family for 10-12 days.  The primary caregiver will be me, with the help of my daughters when they are home. I have one concern that I discussed with Theresa Camloh and she thought it would be worked out:   1.  We have 3 rescue cats that I believe will be ok when we  bring a new puppy into the home after a transition period (one will be aloof, one will be best buds, and one may stay upstairs for the 18 months because she is afraid of her own shadow but desperately wants to be pet), but it may be difficult to bring a new puppy into our home quarterly because of the transition period of them accepting a new family member.     We are very excited to be part of the Guiding Eyes Program :)

StoolComments: Getting better. During her bouts with diarrhea her stools were nothing but water and she would have to go out every hour or two. Now, they seem to be better.
EliminationCrateComments: The entire time we have had issues with her diarrhea she never once went in her crate. She would bark to let us know she needed to go out. As much as I hated having to take her out every hour or two in the middle of the night I was thankful that she knew
HousemannersComments: The biggest problem is when she gets "hair on fire" crazy - both inside and outside. Sometimes she can be really good, but sometimes she is out of control and we have to put her in her kennel until she calms down. She can walk past the dish towel that is hanging on the oven numerous times, then something comes over her and she has to grab the towel on her way past. We heat our house with wood. 70% of the time she will walk past the wood and only give it a glance - sometimes all bets are off and she grabs a piece of wood and tears around the house like a crazy woman.
LeftUnattendedComments: She still gets into too much trouble if she is left alone in a room. She can't seem to settle down and entertain herself. She isn't really interested in toys or chew bones. I tried rubbing one chew bone with ham and she ignored it. She would rather roam around and sniff and mess with stuff. She doesn't even seem to care about her sterile bone which puts me at a loss for what to do since that was what I have always used in the past. Stuffed kongs or stuffed sterile bones - meh. Who cares?
EliminationHouseComments: Getting better. She is not where I think she should be at 4 months of age. Part of it may have been the diarrhea issues. She only pooped in the house once, but we have had problems with her piddling in the house. She would piddle in the house multiple times in a week. She seems to be improving this week, but I'm still unsure about this.
PlaybiteComments: She has gotten a lot better about not biting me, but she still has problems with biting other people.
OnFurnitureComments: Getting better. She used to put her feet on the furniture a few times a day. She now does it a few times a week.
BarksExcessivelyComments: I am starting to see the beginnings of this. Approximately a few times a week she will look at someone and just bark for no reason. I put her in her kennel when she "talks" like that.
RaidsGarbageComments: Starting to see problems with this. Does not get into kitchen garbage, but likes paper products from the other garbage cans.
CountersDoorsComments: She has not shown any signs of jumping on counter or doors.
JumpsComments: We have a big problem with this. We are working on this, but she basically can't greet anyone. She is getting better about watching people from across the street, but we can't be any closer than that without her getting too excited.
FriendlyWAnimalsComments: She does not show aggression towards other animals and she is happy / excited when she sees them, but she can't get near them because she gets too excited and can't control herself.
KidsComments: Same comment as above.
StrangerComments: Same comment as above.
WalkingComments: She is actually pretty good at this if we have been on a part of the path a few times and she is familiar with it. If we go to a section of the path we have never been to before it takes a lot of high value treats to get her to pay attention.
GetBusyComments: She's pretty good at piddling if you tell her to "get busy", but I'm not quite sure she understands that it means she is supposed to poop too if she has to. Again, it may have to do with the diarrhea issues since it was always a mad dash outside so she wouldn't go in the house.
EliminateRouteComments: Pretty good at not piddling on a walk, but needs to improve with not pooping on a walk. I'm never sure if she has to poop or not when I tell her to "get busy" and she sort of fiddles around after she piddles so I will start the walk thinking that she doesn't have to do anything else and then she will poop at the beginning of the walk.
ChaseComment: I'm not sure about this. We have seen deer and rabbits , but they have always been far enough away that she would be focused on them and very interested in them, but far enough away that she has never tried to chase them.
TrafficComments: Pretty good in moderate traffic with different kinds of vehicles and motorcycles. We have not been to a place with heavy traffic yet.
StairsComments: A little too confident. I've had to teach her  to step on every step and not jump down to the floor one or two steps before she gets to the bottom step.
SitComments: Pretty good for the most part. Need to practice more around distractions. Very good if the distractions are cars going past. She is okay if the people or bikes or kids are across the street -she will sit after she watches the distraction for a few seconds
DownComments: Same issues with distractions. She is getting better about doing it with minimal distractions.
PillsComments: She was on antibiotics for 5 days and did not have any issues with this.
EarsComments: She isn't too thrilled with this, but we can clean her ears in small segments. She doesn't bite or try to get away, but she will paw at my hand to try to get me to stop.
NailsComments: At this point we have not had any problems with this. She has had her nails clipped a few times since I only clip a little bit at a time.
AttendClassesComments: She attends class each week and she will attend her first social program this weekend. I plan on bringing her kennel because of her excitability issues.
GeneralComments: Overall, Emily is fun to be around and she is a really smart dog and a quick learner. The biggest issue is her inability to calm herself down when she gets excited or frustrated. She gets herself into a frenzy and you can tell she has no control. I've tried increasing the distance and distracting her, but all that seems to do is make it worse.  I've tried standing still and also trying to get her to walk in a different direction which doesn't seem to work either.  She becomes a growling, biting, run around out of control mess. I have to pick her up and put her in her kennel. This is fine if we are in the house, but when we are outside and I have to carry her 2 or 3 blocks to get home it becomes a problem.  She seems to come unhinged and she becomes what we call "hair on fire crazy".  We aren't quite sure what sets her off either. One time she became unhinged because she wanted to eat an acorn and I wouldn't let her. So, I had to pick her up and carry her the three blocks home because she wasn't listening. Every time I put her down I could tell she still wasn't in control of herself. Another time, the situation was pretty exciting - she saw a rushing creek for the first time so it was fast movement, loud noise, and water!  She wasn't sure about it at first so she kept running up to it and then running away. Each time she would get closer and not run away as far. She finally figured out it was water and she was thrilled to death and at the same time became unhinged. I ended up having to carry her the quarter of a mile home because, again, each time I put her on the ground she exhibited the same out of control behavior.  She bolts in every direction, growls, and bites at my clothes. Evidently three blocks away from an acorn or a quarter of a mile away from a creek is not enough distance to allow her to calm herself.   Loud noises and different surfaces underfoot do not seem to be a problem at this time. She walks on concrete, grass, gravel, tar and chipped roads, dirt roads, paving blocks, and paved surfaces without a problem.  The only noise I remember startling her was the fire trucks briefly testing their siren and horn one morning. We were about three blocks away from the fire station when, for about a second, they turned on the siren and honked their horn. Emily was startled by that and stood there for a second or two and then she was fine.  We continued on our walk as if nothing had happened. This was the first time she had ever heard that noise.   The diarrhea has been a huge issue and I think it has also somewhat impacted her training a little since I was afraid to give her too many treats and when we are rushing to get her outside so she doesn't have an accident in the house, the last thing I am thinking about is proper manners and walking appropriately on lead. I'm hoping that once we get her GI issues straightened out we can get better at the training.   I do think her behavior, when she is in class, has improved over the past few weeks. She doesn't seem to be as restless as she was in the beginning and she seems relatively calmer around the other dogs as long as they keep their distance. She still needs to improve a lot, but I think I see a difference in her as the weeks go by.  Tiny improvements each time we attend class. Grant it, to an outsider she probably still looks like a wild woman, but to me, I can tell she is a bit better than she was about paying attention to me and while she still gets distracted, she seems to be able to recover herself a little bit quicker each time.
DayInLife: My household is made up of just my husband and me.  We currently do not have any other pets.  During the week, we live in a small townhouse, but on the weekends we live in a slightly larger log home on 15 acres.  Neither home has a fence so we are used to constantly having the dogs we have owned in the past on leash.      The townhouse is three levels and the floor surfaces are vinyl tile, concrete, and carpet.  We have stairs that go down into the basement and up to the second floor.  Our townhouse backs up to a small shopping area that has a grocery store, two eating establishments, and other small retail establishments.  There is always some type of activity going on in the neighborhood either the yard crews are cutting the grass (noisy lawnmowers, leaf blowers), kids are playing in front of our house, the mailman is delivering the mail, etc.  We also live about 5 blocks from an elementary school and community pool - all of this is in our subdivision.  There are sidewalks and bike paths to walk the puppy along. We walk to the grocery store 2-3 times a week to go grocery shopping.  We have a fire department 3 blocks from our house that has fire trucks and an ambulance. We also live close to Frederick City and can go into the city in the evenings for social outings.  The city has a lot more cars and distractions then at either of our other two houses.      Out at the cabin, the puppy will get to experience, rocky roads, dirt paths, grassy paths, various wildlife (turkey, deer, bear, snakes, bobcat, grouse etc.), mud, and lots of water.  The log house is 2 hours from our townhouse so the puppy will get used to "riding" with us.  The floor surfaces inside the home are ceramic tile, carpet, and hardwood flooring.  We have sliding glass doors and the inevitable screen doors that all of our dogs have had to learn about.    I have family that live on the Eastern shore so the puppy will be exposed to the bay and ocean, Annapolis, sea gulls, sand, etc.      During the week, my husband works from home 5 days a week and I work at home 2 days a week.  My husband travels about 2-3 times a year for about a week at a time.  I travel anywhere from 0-6 times a year from 1-2 weeks each time.  The puppy will not be going on work travel since we will be in areas that do not allow animals.  My husband and I coordinate travel so one person will be home while the other person is traveling.  Once the puppy is housebroken and has a little more self-control he will be going to my office with me.  My office is an hour away from my house and I leave at 5 AM.  Work consists of sitting around reading at my desk, going to meetings, going to the Farmer's Market on Tuesdays, riding in elevators, walking up stairs, going through sliding glass doors, going to the cafeteria for lunch, going through security check points, walking on carpet, tile, marble, and concrete.  I work on a Federal Government Campus so we are fairly isolated and there is a lot of open space and trees where I work.  Inside the buildings, there is a lot of glass and open spaces.  My job may be changing soon which will mean less work traveling and more time actually going into the office instead of working from home.  It will just mean that the puppy makes the trek into my office more times per week then he would be doing now.      Any personal travel that my husband and I have done in the past we have always brought our dogs so vacation time is making sure the dogs can go along too.  The puppy will be used to hotels and long rides.    That's about it.  Our life is pretty ordinary, but we do have a lot of different things going on.

GeneralComments: Maury is a pleasure to have in the house. He has an enjoyable energy level and has fantastic house manners. Maury came to us as a home switch in mid July. He seemed to lack confidence and showed signs of stress in new situations. We have tried to give Maury a variety of socialization experiences and believe that he has gained some confidence. He seems to be a "happier" pup than he was (he has gained skills in playing appropriately with other pups, and loves to do so). He still however, sometimes shows signs of stress/lack of confidence when exposed to new or particularly challenging environments (drooling, yawning, and "flopping" onto the floor). Stairs, in particular, have been a challenge for Maury, but inconsistently so. We are unclear as to whether this is due to a lack of confidence or coordination or both. We have seen improvement in loose leash walking and connecting with his handler. We are enjoying our time with Maury very much.

GeneralComments: We have made great strides in the biting department - he came biting our hands and feet constantly.  Started barking out of frustration when redirected.  At this point much less biting and plays with his toys more.   When in the green zone he is excellent with commands and loose leash walking.  Excellent out in parking lots and garden center at Lowe's.  Footing - no problems.  Very confident puppy!
DayInLife: We live in a country setting on 22 acres of land. We have many family members that live with in a one mile radius and if needed could make a trip and allow the puppy to "get busy". Included in this is four retired parents. We leave for work by 7:30 on weekdays. Kathy works a mile from home and can take lunch at home. Kathy also can be home by 3:15 to drop Alli off from school to attend to the puppy. Our daughter Alli is soon to be 16 and is going to be an integral part of the puppy raising. Zach, our oldest leaves for college in the fall and is looking forward to helping when he is home. I work for Verizon and often pass through town and can stop for a quick check and bathroom time. There is always someone home from 3:30 in the afternoon till morning. Our weekends are extremely flexible with occasional trips to parade and fire dept functions. This will be an excellent opportunity for socialization when the puppy is ready. Kathy is a teacher and class adviser which will allow the pup to attend many different social environments through school. Wes is a county fire coordinator and would be able to take the pup to meetings and expose the pup to another experience. Our extended family also has many animals to expose the pup to. (cows,goats,rabbits,cat,chickens,horses) We have had three previous dogs as pets. A golden retriever,beagle and a dalmatian. The dalmatian was trained and proficient enough to march in the parades with Wes off leash and was a real crowd favorite. We have had a relationship with our Vet for over twenty years and find them very caring and willing to make emergency calls if necessary. We look forward to learning and being able to help teach a puppy to become someones guiding eyes.Thank you for your time.

GeneralComments: Gladys is a sweet, smart girl who stives to please. I have never seen aggressiion, though excitement is sometimes a challenge. On socializations, especially in crowded or busy places she can be extremely focused. In more casual settings she (I?) is/am more easily distracted.  I mentioned cat issues. My 'less friendly' cat sometimes hisses/growls when Gladys enters a room, which intrigues Gladys who wants to investigate. If the cat runs, Gladys may get excited and give chase. I'm usually able to anticipate, so it doesn't happen often. Then a couple nights ago Gladys laid calmly within a few feet while the cat came to me for attention, but its not a pattern of behavior I can count on yet. Gladys is friendly toward my other cat and learning to respect her space. Same with my personal dog. Gladys has improved when approaching stangers, and when she does get excited is more easily redirected. Sometimes Sunday afternoon classes are a challenge; I think becasue she has been crated all morning, and there is limited time to eat lunch and exercise her before class. This morning I saw her first ever hesitation in walking over a grate.

GeneralComments: Kimberly is a sweet puppy who responds quickly to her name and has a lot of eye contact.  She especially enjoys being with people and it's rewarding to experience her developing self control as she matures.  She is very active and busy first thing in the morning and if exercised and asked to work, moderates throughout the day.
DayInLife: Donna & Steve live in a two story house on 3 acres of property in Henrietta, NY.  No children. Our home sits in the middle of three acres outside of a housing track but on a somewhat busy road.  Plenty of side walks along the road and into the neighbor hoods/housing tracks, around us that work into an elementary school.  Most times the area is very quiet but the occasion loud picnic occurs.  Being in Henrietta has it good and bad.  Bad, it's a grid town and not a village to walk to different places.  Good, there are still plenty of businesses, plazas & mall, Town Hall, library, and grocery stores to sit and watch activities and still short distance drives.    We have raised 8 puppies for Guiding Eyes, last two being Halsa (7HH10) and her mom Shelby.  Puppy number 5, Verna, was a medical release who we adopted and is still with us today at the age  of 12.     We both work Monday - Friday.  Donna works 8:30am - 4:30pm; Steve varies from 4:30am - 2:00pm.  Donna works in an office at the University of Rochester where Halsa spent many days a week like her mom Shelby.  Steve is a route driver for a coffee company so no opportunity to have the puppy with him at work.  Our weekends are generally open to doing things around the house to family/friend events that may come up.  Sunday morning is church which will be an opportunity to socialize.    Both of us enjoy running races, 5K's, 10k's, 1/2 and full marathons during the year, more Steve than Donna.  Depending on locations and size of race, these have been good outings based on the puppy's age.  Lots to see but plenty of space to back away when needed.      We are looking forward to raising another puppy and hopefully one of Halsa's puppies to say we raised a mom, daughter and grand daughter.    Cheers -  Donna & Steve Derks

DayInLife: My 13 year old son Pete and myself will be the puppies primary raisers. We live with my husband Paul and daughter Mary who will be going off to college in the fall. The four of us live in the suburbs in a ranch style home on 3/4 acre land. The back yard has some fencing but is not completely closed off. My husband and I have always had dogs, but when our son Pete was born we discovered he had asthma. This is why we did not adopt again when our dogs passed away. Pete has since outgrown his asthma and we are more than ready to begin raising a dog again. I am a physical therapist and presently work on a per diem basis. I am also taking online classes to earn my Masters in Orientation and Mobility, therefore I am often home studying.  Pete finishes school June 19th and will be a freshman in the fall. He plays baseball 3-4 times per week throughout the summer, but otherwise is usually home. After June 19th, someone will always be home.  I am taking 2 online classes this summer therefore we are unable to go on a long vacation, however we hope to take a day/overnight trips occasionally. Because we have not had a dog in years, we would love a mild mannered puppy (if possible) to begin our puppy raising experience. Sex does not matter unless you think one or the other is easier for a beginner. We truly cant wait to begin!

GeneralComments: Neil is doing well. His behaviors appear to be appropriate for his age. He is eager to please and has great name response. He is able to be redirected easily. At the Manassas Jubilee, he showed NO signs of distress or anxiety. He does sniff a lot and will pick up things in his mouth. 80% of the time, he responded to "out" quickly and had MANY opportunities to practice this. I was able to quickly gain his attention when distracted by other dogs with body blocking. By the end of the day (approximately 2 hours at the Jubilee), he would immediately look at me when he saw another dog. He is distracted by leaves but not as much as my previous pups.

GeneralComments: So gave him a 5 about furniture, just looked up to see him swipe a pillow off the couch. He didn't want to give it up. His outs have become a little resistant and I do not want to reward them because I do think it would be a game he would like. My concerns are the previous, leash pulling, eating acorns, eating anything as we try to take a walk anywhere (people litter soooo much). His greets look like this: He's overly jumpy excited, I get him to sit, I say "go say hi", he rushes at the person and seems to be getting out of the jumping but decides to pull their shoelaces within 2 secs, maybe even a tooth in the pants leg. I call him back and he does come and sit.
DayInLife: Overall, I have a flexible schedule. My work week is Monday thru Friday, however I work for myself and make my own hours. The work environment is very calm in that I am a Licensed Massage Therapist and Yoga Therapist. The office is about 15 min from my house and is located on the second floor of a very old factory building, think Erector Sets the toy from years and years ago! It has wooden floors and big windows that are up higher, a very forgiving environment with lots of stairs and hallways. I can easily have a kennel there and my clients are looking forward to meeting our new friend. I plan to have enough time inbetween appointments to give the pup my complete attention, which is just a matter of how I choose to book the appointments. I can also have the pup at home and break up the day from morning and afternoon by being home for several hours. Most probably a bit of both. Two Wednesdays a month I am away from home from 8:45 until 5:00 (including travel time) working in a corporate setting. On these 2 days my daughter (Alison 31) has agreed to spend time with our little girl or guy. Joan Moore, also a puppy raiser, has also agreed to me dropping the pup off at her house for some pup playtime. I don't work on weekends. The home life looks like this: 2 female sister cats who are 2.5 years old and do not go outside. They have never scratched or bitten me or anyone else, and are very timid although curious and friendly. They are up to date on their shots and I use Revolution on them even though they are inside, just to be safe. My partner is John Terry who is an absolute lover of all animals and most importantly very well trained by me! (Hehehe) Meaning, he understands that I am the main trainer for the pup and he is willing to be on the same page with me in all the activities concerning the pup. We live in a small cape home (1,200 sq feet) which is already animal safe because of our cats. We do not have sidewalks, and the road we live on is relatively busy, however, there are side roads which are not. I am also willing to drive to where there are sidewalks to get a diversified experience. I believe that we are relatively well setup for this experience. I can only say relatively because it hasn't happened yet! But wherever we may be lacking we are willing to do what we need to do to improve the accommodations. I am a bit nervous! It's a tremendous responsibility, however, I also know that I communicate better with all animals than people, so I feel confident to learn the language. I have had 2 dogs before in my life, they were my best friends and will always be a part of who I am. In retrospect, I am surprised they were as well behaved as they were considering I knew nothing! An additional thought I would like to add is my request for a black dog. I live in black leggings for my work and the maintenance of the removal of yellow hair would be something that I really would rather not have to devote time to. I do hope that doesn't sound offensive in any way, but if I know me, this pup is going to very close to me most of the time and I plan on being hairy. I also believe, but perhaps not accurately, that the female black labs tend to be a little smaller, which given the ways in which I depend on the well being of my fingers, hands and arms, might make more sense for me. All THAT being said, I soooo do not wish to create criteria that puts me right out of the program, so it's just my humble opinion. Oh, and I bend, crawl, jump, bark and roll over. Wait, I won't bark.  I hope I have created a picture that is clear, and user friendly for all of us. Thank you for this wonderful opportunity, I have already learned so very much and it's hardly begun. Peace

DayInLife: I am newly retired.  I live in a single family house in Oxford, CT.  The only other one in my household is my son, who is 29, and lives downstairs.  He understands that in order to be fair to the puppy and not confuse him/her,  he needs to follow the Guiding Eyes rules.( He loves dogs and will spoil them if allowed)  :)     We have two other dogs in the house - my son's dog - Dixie - a 10 yr. old blue tick coon hound spayed female and a 1 1/2 yr old Chihuahua/Papillion (?) mix - Peanut - also a spayed female.  Peanut is just graduating from a pet therapy program and I will be doing some hospital and nursing home visits with her.  I also have two horses on my property.   My backyard is fenced in with stockade fencing so the dogs can't get out but I am use to watching them while they are out playing.      My schedule is very flexible.  I like to walk and keep active.  I have had many dogs over my lifetime.  I use to foster dogs, take them to obedience classes and then find them very suitable homes.  I have done a lot of dog sports over the years - agility, fly ball, frisbee, sheep herding and showing dogs in both breed and obedience.      I am open to any puppy.  I have had mostly females in the past but I have had 2 males.  I don't know of any intact females or males in my neighborhood but you don't always know that until you have a dog come into heat :)     I am very excited to raise a puppy for the Guiding Eyes.

GeneralComments: When I got him he was a whirlwind, we've put a lot of emphasis on calming him down/settling as well as trying to get him to entertain himself and direct his chewing onto his toys -I'm proud to say that's going fantastically. He's just reached the point where he's calm and attentive in the house about 85% of the time, but he's still not at the point where he can settle well outside of the house (in class, at sedate locations, we've tried to keep the distractions minimal but it's still to much for him to really settle down. He's fine with most distractions if we're actively working with him (heel/sit/down/stand/stay/come/ect).   Also, he's very attentive for a good period of time up to 45mins max, but after that he gets extremely frustrated and agitated, stops listening, starts biting and whining (this is really only an issue in class)  Other than this, he's great.

DayInLife: Participants-Bruce, Maggie (our 7 yr old golden retriever), and Linda    Monday-Friday  5am-Bruce wakes to go to work and showers  5:30am Bruce proceeds downstairs and feeds Maggie  6am Linda wakes and Bruce leaves for work  Linda has tea and reads paper  6:30am Linda showers and dresses  7am Linda leaves to go to the mall to walk  8am Linda goes to the gym  8:45am Linda returns home  8:45-9:30 various chores, lets Maggie outside  9:30am Bruce returns home  depending on the day, activities, weather we usually take a walk together sometime before noon  12:30-1:30 watch Young and the Restless  1pm Bruce goes back to work  1:30-3:30 various chores, computer, depending on what needs to be done  3:30-4:30 prepare supper for Maggie and then for Linda and Bruce  4:45pm Bruce returns home  Evening may involve meetings, bowling for Bruce, shopping, church activities, friends or family  also usually some TV time.    Weekends- Saturday Bruce golfs in the morning, afternoon is usually spent together, maybe taking a ride or a walk.  Sunday, church from 10-11 with possible meeting after.  Then time again together  depending on what is going on.    We are both fairly active despite arthritic knees that act up here and there.  We live in a Cape, 2 stories on a quiet street.  We have a fenced in back yard that is also quiet and backs up to woods. Linda is retired and Bruce is retired but drives a school bus (hence the comings and goings during the day).  Maggie is a beautiful, loving dog who is looking forward to having a little sister!

DayInLife: I live in a suburban neighborhood, walking distance to Northampton Center. I have a private but not fenced back yard. I have an eight year old beagle mix. I live with my husband, who works full time and frequently travels, and two teenaged sons. I am home most days until January and then I work part time as a ski instructor, on the days that I will be out of the house for more than four hours I will have a schedule for one of my sons or a dog walker to take the puppy out for play and food and potty.  I may be able to take the dog to work with me and have her stay in the teachers lounge while I am out skiing. I typically teach for an hour or two and then have an hour break and then teach for another hour or two and so on so that I can spend time in between lessons walking her around the resort, and getting her used to lots of people. I will have to work that out with my employer. That part time job lasts typically until the end of February. When I will be home full time again. I am a runner, hiker and backwoods skier, and plan to have the dog accompany me as soon as she is old enough. My car is large enough to hold a crate, and my other dog frequently rides with me while I am out doing errands, but more often I walk to town for shopping and dining and entertainment. I look forward to having the puppy accompany me there.

GeneralComments: Clive came to me a little over two months ago.  He has adjusted well to the new house although he was very activated for a few days as he settled.  He has improved significantly with settling in the house and in public.  He can successfully go to a restaurant for 1-2 hours with support - usually settles towards the end (takes a nap).  Because of my work and volunteer work, Clive attends alot of public functions and travels with me 1-2 hours in the car most days.  He is generally good at playdates but can pick out a pup/dog that he wants to 'hump'. He is improving with the cats.  Once moment he is laying next to them and the next moment he could be barking at them.  When he barks, I will separate/barracade him from cats and he gets the message.  Clive has strong foundation skills, is a pleasure to walk on leash, although when he's "had enough" he will start to chew on the leash.  I will then stop, unclip his leash and with his collar, do a guided down and wait for him to settle.  This usually works.  He is a very loving pup who wants to be with me at all times.  He loves to go for rides in the car and to go to work.  One of his favorite things to do is go to the mall.  He likes to run in the yard but not much of a fetcher.  When he's playing, he's not very good about come and out.  We've been working on "Out" and "Take It" and this seems to have help him learn to "Out" things in his mouth.  He is a sweet, happy,willing dog and doesn't seem to let anything 'bother' him.

GeneralComments: Gala has a gentle temperament. She is not overly bold, but is very confident once she's found her center and calms herself quickly when encountering new experiences. She's so food motivated that it sometimes gets her too activated for training. When food is too much of a distraction she's done very well with verbal praise, physical contact and my body language as alternative rewards. She has not understood gentle corrections to things like putting her feet on my lap. I'm working on making a bigger show of being upset with her. She bonded with me very quickly and checks-in frequently in all environments. Gala's a charmer!

DayInLife: I am currently working from home.  I have started a florist business.  I am taking this opportunity to be a puppy raiser.  Previously, I was away from home for 9 hours each day.  My 17 year old daughter stays at home with me.  She has had brain tumors and has some special needs.  We will be co- raising the puppy.  My son is almost 15, he attends school each day.  He is not sold on having a puppy.  He has not had good dog experiences.  I would not be surprised if he falls in love with the puppy.  My fiancé lives in Fenwick Island, Delaware.  He is also not sold on having a puppy, cramping his style.  We go to his home most weekends.  He is in our home most of the time also.  We are getting married in January.  We will probably need a puppy sitter.  We haven't made any wedding plans, yet.  I know this is not going to be easy.  I just feel called to do this.  At least just once.

ExerciseType: walks, training, actively plays with other dogs outside at home, interacts with family members with ball or tug toy
ExericeAmount: 80-120 minutes a day.  We aim for several 20 to 40 minutes of play time a day
CrateQuietComments: She was great until this last week when she transitioned back to work.  A new habit is to bark when there is talking or someone is on the phone.  This was not the case before. if she is tired and goes to sleep she is VERY happy in her crate.
ChewingComments: She often needs to be redirected to not chew on furniture or the corner of wind sills.  She is actively teething and losing teeth, so she just needs to be monitored.
LeftUnattendedComments: If Jess is not in her crate, she cannot be left unattended. She is extremely adventurous and knows how to know down or move through gates. She will also chew on legs of chairs or inappropriate things without monitoring.  We believe this will stop once she has stopped teething.
EliminationHouseComments: She has never pooped in the house, but she still needs to go out to pee frequently and is not reliable yet.
PlaybiteComments: She is a biter when you are playing with her.  You have to have a toy nearby.  Jess really uses her mouth to communicate love and frustration. When you are petition her, she wants to just put her mouth around your wrist or hold your clothing. We redirect by substituting a toy and praising with "what a nice toy."  When she gets overly excited or frustrated she wants to bite.  This is resolved by putting her in her kennel until she has settled down or usually it is a sign that she needs rest.
OnFurnitureComments: She sometimes gets excited and puts her front paws on the couch.  Our other dogs do not get on the furniture so we are hoping this is just an "out of control" puppy behavior that we are slowly breaking.
BarksExcessivelyComments: Just recently she has started barking in the kennel and sometimes at our other dogs when they are settled in their beds during evening time in the house.
RaidsGarbageComments: She has not access to garbage so it is not a problem.
CountersDoorsComments: She does NOT jump on counter but will jump at doors if she wants to get through.
JumpsComments: For the most part she is good, but not dependable. If people approach her excited, which we try to deter, she might put her front paws on them. She will jump or leap for her treats if we do not get low enough for her. Hopefully as she gets taller that won't be an issue.
FriendlyWAnimalsComments: Jess loves other dogs, but can play a little rough.  She can be submissive but will also show signs of wanting to be the alpha female. We have chickens and she is not very interested in them and does not lunge at them or chase them.
KidsComments: She LOVES children!
WalkingComments: She is happy on her lead and will walk with a slack lead when training in the middle of the road with low distractions.  Otherwise she does pull. This is a huge focus of our time with our mentor.
GetBusyComments: She is very good at this!
ChaseComment: She wants to chase our other dogs but has not showed interest in squirrels or our chickens.
StayComments: We just started working on this. She is good for about 10 feet and 20 seconds.
ComeOffLeashComments: She comes in the house when off lead and you call her. We have had her off lead in an enclosed area only a few times and she is OK about coming.
PillsComments: The only pill she has taken is heart worm.
AttendClassesComments: We have only missed one optional social.
GeneralComments: Jess is a very adventurous and bold puppy.  She is smart and learns quickly.  However, she can also be stubborn and have her own agenda.  She needs high interest treats when working outside with distractions.  Her new habit (last five days) of barking has become problematic at work and in the house, so we need guidance on that.  Jess is very in tune to her people and loves to get praise and attention, sometimes that is more motivating to her than food.  She has lots of energy so finding appropriate ways for her to release that is a challenge.  Jess's personality and energy make her a great candidate for a guide dog, she just needs LOTS of practice and some maturing.

DayInLife: I work from home 5 days a week and don't have to travel for work too often. This will give me the ability to let the pup out when needed, integrate training throughout the day, and make myself the reward. I also have flexibility to start work between 7 and 9 and end between 3:30 and 5. This gives me more flexibility to do walks or socialization in the AM or PM depending on weather and how much light is in the sky. We don't have children so the pup will be the main target of our love and direction and we will be able to bring him/ her to socialize in a variety of situations and will be able to focus on the pup to integrate training throughout the day. We own our home and have a grassy front and back yard as well as a patio and plenty of places to walk the pup. Weekend schedule is pretty flexible and we don't really have a set schedule for the weekend.

DayInLife: We (Jim and Susan) both work in a private high school, which has given us permission to bring the pup to school.  Jim teaches (12-18 students per class,with free periods) and is a dean, and Susan works with the administration (and has a quiet office).  Our 2 children (10 and 12) attend the lower school.  We leave home at 7 am, work 8 - 4:00, and head home at 5:30 when Jim is done coaching soccer (fall) and lacrosse (spring).  We are an active family - Jim is an avid runner, we hike and enjoy long walks, and live in a vibrant small town with a great downtown - lots of shops, farmers' markets, etc.  Our home is near the local high school - we can hear the marching band practice and the cheers from the Friday night football games, but our neighborhood is quiet and pleasant.  In addition to the childdren wee do have a cat that was raised with our other dog who has since passed.  Nemo has met many dogs, and really seems to like dogs; he is not shy or hesitant at all.

I am interrupting play frequently, and not letting the energy level get up there, but it is challenging.  I'm looking forward to you seeing him, Jane, and getting your opinion on how he's doing!

ExericeAmount: Varies from 5 to 60 min/day depending on my schedule

KidsComments: I haven't been able to expose her to as many children as I would like because of bad weather, winter months and schedule has not permitted me to get Gladys into any school classrooms or library story hours yet. I do not have any children myself. She was fine at a friends' home w/ 4 kids ranging from 7 to 15 yrs old. Has sat outside playground watching children play but none came to greet us. Gladys looked calm and relaxed - no barking or hackling. Friendly with any children she has met on the street.
WalkingComments: LLW is, of course, a work in progress - does best when no dog distraction like in class!!
EliminateRouteComments: Only once has she defecated while on a walk in town - normal formed stool, but in retrospect, I did not give her adequate time to get bust before working her.
ChaseComment: Is quite interested in crows on the ground if they are around when we walk, and I believe would chase birds, rabbits and squirrels if she had the opportunity. Can definitely redirect while on a walk. Likes to move my cat around my place a bit, but cat also interacts and "teases" a bit.
TrafficComments: We are just starting to do busier streets with traffic coming from behind. I have gone very slowly to really help her build her confidence in all settings we have gone to - so far she seems to look pretty confident. Did compress once when a noisy bus went by.
NoiseComments: will sometimes startle or compress when sudden loud traffic noise - seems to recover well.
StayComments: Working on building distance, duration when dog distraction around.
EarsComments: I stick my fingers in her ears - she has never needed to have her ears cleaned.
GeneralComments: Gladys has made vast improvement in many areas. 1) A diet change has resulted in a healthy weight gain and 1-2 normal bowel movements/day compared to several soft ones/day when she 1st arrived.  2) She is now housetrained and goes to the door or comes to me or paces around when she needs to go out & get busy - she would sometimes urinate and defecate indoors when she 1st arrived and was often too distracted outdoors to relax &get busy on request. She has always kept her crate clean.  3) Gladys responds well to clear expectations - will work for food, toys, play, life rewards. While she has shown a quick and sometimes marked startle response, she is extremely resilient - has never "shut down," and has always been willing to "go check it out." And repeatedly approach from different directions, etc. When she 1st came to me, my assessment was that she had high visual, auditory, and olefactory distraction - probably contributing to the difficulty Lucille had in getting her house-trained. She does well with slow and careful exposures, and I have found short outings and watching her body language carefully is important - she will start to pant, occasionally yawn, sniff more, move more quickly and lose focus and connection if she is unsure of herself. Some of her social outings have included 3 different post offices, CVS drugsore in quiet times, a church service concert and coffee hour (many people greetings) afterwards, library, 1/4 mile track in Yorktown, settling at staff meetings and committee meetings, quiet residential neighborhoods in White Plains, bigger street in White Plains on Sunday morning - minimal traffic, Yorktown, Shrub Oak, Mt. Kisco, Katonah, Briarcliff Manor, Brewster, New Paltz, shopping center parking lots and walking in front of store fronts, automatic doors. I think she needs time to take new things in with ALL of her senses, and I tried to keep outings limited to 20 minutes or less so that she would get new exposures without feeling overwhelmed. I think she is still a fairly immature 9 month old, but has made great progress. She does very well with support - how she will do when she doesn't have that support, I don't know, because she still seems pretty young to me. She is a very sweet, very pleasant pup, loves to run and play, but has also done very well "hanging out " when I am at work and did fine with almost no exercise for several days in a row. She continues to improve re dog distraction, and will offer auto checkins some of the time if the dog-dog distance is appropriate. High value treats get her interest readily. There is probably more I could write but I am sure I have gone on long enough, other than to add that she needs a very patient raiser.

HealthComments: 1 outer ear inflammation and 1 ear infection
StoolComments: In an attempt to have him not eliminate while on walks, under Carrie's direction, I have gradually  switched him from two meals a day to one meal a  day in an attempt to get him to empty his bowels all at once.  The switch was completed 6-8 weeks ago. His first stool of the day is firm, but it is not always first thing in the morning. If the second stool is within a two hour period, it starts out a little soft and progresses to applesauce consistency. Usually once he has progressed to applesuace consistency, he is done for the day, although there have been at least 3 occasions when he still had a little more left in him later in the day. He had been having trouble with getting too excited when he would see or hear another dog close by and would poop. That seems to be under control unless it is his first poop of the day.  Frequently when his stool is applesauce consistency, he stands in position as if there is more to come, he changes positions at least three times and drops of liquid can be seen at the end.

He has had play dates and been able to play with other dogs ok. Sometimes he thinks that Amity is a chew toy. Amity doesn't seem to mind. When I go to check on them when he is chewing on her, they act like two teenagers that have been caught.
KidsComments: Loves children, especially babies. I have to really watch him when we are near babies as he wants to check them out .  I usually hold him pretty tightly when toddlers and pre-schoolers want to pet him, so that he doesn't try to jump on them. He has been really good. It's just that he is so big and I don't want to traumatize the kids or the babies parents.
WalkingComments: Sometimes takes a little while to get connected.
GetBusyComments: Usually not a problem at all out in the community. Did have troulbe with getting him to go on command at home, but that is improving.
EliminateRouteComments: Doing much better. Have a designated spot in the neigherhood that we also use besides our yard. When we are on outings, I usually have him get busy as soon as we get there., but he will sometimes try to mark by lifting his leg or will just mark while he is walking.
ChaseComment: I think that if he were off leash he would chase after any animal. He has been able to sit for a short time and watch some goats and chickens.
TrafficComments: We were in Frederick last week and he didn't have trouble with the traffic or the very loud siren of an ambulance or the moderate amount of people. Hasn't been in a very large city yet.
SitComments: sometimes a little slow
ComeOffLeashComments: In the house, he does great. Outside he can be distracted by other dogs and people.
NailsComments: He had been really good and now he won't let me use the clippers. I can file his nails without any problem.
GeneralComments: Sometimes takes a while to settle down in class. Is very distracted by other dogs in and out of class. He tends to see the dogs before I do and wants to go and play.

HealthComments: 1 outer ear inflammation and 1 ear infection
StoolComments: In an attempt to have him not eliminate while on walks, under Carrie's direction, I have gradually  switched him from two meals a day to one meal a  day in an attempt to get him to empty his bowels all at once.  The switch was completed 6-8 weeks ago. His first stool of the day is firm, but it is not always first thing in the morning. If the second stool is within a two hour period, it starts out a little soft and progresses to applesauce consistency. Usually once he has progressed to applesuace consistency, he is done for the day, although there have been at least 3 occasions when he still had a little more left in him later in the day. He had been having trouble with getting too excited when he would see or hear another dog close by and would poop. That seems to be under control unless it is his first poop of the day.  Frequently when his stool is applesauce consistency, he stands in position as if there is more to come, he changes positions at least three times and drops of liquid can be seen at the end.

We live on 2+ acres in a beautiful community with families who are out and walking their dogs.  We have two female dogs of our own. GeneralComments: Marcus is a sensitve fellow who does best with clear communication. He tends to get aroused by things moving in his environment. He will whine when activated, but once he settles into work the whining dissipates. He does best when he knows what is expected and he is settled into a routine. I think I should use Go Place for meals but have not worked on making him go there and stay there.  Need help with this.  Also, he will vocalize and pester me/my husband/our son when we sit down to relax unless he is also ready to relax.  I need help with this.
LeftUnattendedComments: I do this now for more extended times than ever before.  Sometimes I just peek into the room where he is to make sure all is well.  It usually is.
PlaybiteComments: But getting much better and very gentle now.
StealFoodComments: If this means would he steal something out of my hand or lap the he gets a 5.  He expect he would steal food if left unattended and within his reach.
BarksExcessivelyComments: When he is bored and wants to play. See 40 above.
RaidsGarbageComments: Our really "good"garbage is concealed and most other trash receptacles have lids.  However, he largely ignores the open cans, and responds well to OUT when he does snag something.
CountersDoorsComments: Never been an issue
JumpsComments: Rarely, and it is improving.  Happens mostly when he is really excited or a family member arrives home and doesn't greet him as fully as he (Laramie) would like.I need help with this.
WalkingComments: I think he does well with this.  However, he is easily distracted by tidbits on the ground that he would like to eat, other dogs and people.  He is very strong!  Will appreciate your thoughts on how he is doing.
GetBusyComments: See 70 Below.  He will always pee on command, but unless he is desperate to poop he will wait if he thinks we might go for a walk.  I try to time walks and play for just after he poops, but this doesn't always work.
EliminateRouteComments: I always take him to GB before going to walk.  He almost always pees.  If the walk is a lengthy one (30+) minutes he will sometimes pull to the side and pee.  I don't think he HAS to...his bladder is certainly not full.  Pooping is more of an issue.  I try to time free play and walks after he has pooped, but he prefers to go "on his own" so I am having some trouble with this.  What do you suggest.
ChaseComment: Not when on leash.  Will occasionally pursue a bird when just enjoying free play.  Does love to chase butterflies when free.
StayComments: Still building time and distraction resistance.
ComeOffLeashComments: Improving.  But success depends on level of distraction
NailsComments: He has really calmed down for all types of body handling.
DayInLife: I am currently not working at all because my work is seasonal.  In mid-march I will have the choice to return to work on a part time basis--fewer than 20 hours a week on a schedule that will place the pup's needs first.  I do not have to work but at present have kept the option to return there open.  Neil and I live in a single family home on a 1/4 acre lot in a quiet but friendly neighborhood.  We are both in good health, enjoy the outdoors and are active and happy people.  I anticipate a typical day with a new pup will likely  start out when we normally get up in the morning---about 6:30 and proceed something like this:  6:30-Get Busy  6:40-Feed Pup  (I put on clothes) & Get Busy  6:50-Feed me  7:10 Get Busy  7:15-7:45 Reward with play  7:50-8:10 Start morning chores (breakfast dishes, make bed, etc) together.  8:10 Get Busy  8:15-8:45 Finish morning chores  8:45 Get Busy  (Are we Getting Busy too frequently?)  8:50-9:10 Work on specific behavior--eg class work.  9:10 Get Busy   9:15-9:30 Reward with play.  9:30-11:00  Kennel up with toys for nap.  I go to gym.  11:00-Get busy. Feed Pup. Get Busy.  The remainder of the day is generally open and my schedule is flexible.  If a return to work the pup will never need to stay in the crate for more hours than he can do comfortably  based on his age.   We have 2 children.  The oldest is 23 and lives and works in Baltimore.  The youngest is 20 and is a Junior in college.  He will be home for vacations and for the summer.  He is enthusiastic and supportive of this opportunity.  He loves animals, especially dogs, and is fully aware that there are critical skills and socialization "rules" for us to follow.  I look forward to your input regarding how I can best adjust my schedule to make the most of puppy training for the pup and for me!    What?  No question about Zu Zu's petals?

HealthComments: Problem with food seems to be resolved, probable allergy to an antibiotic
ExerciseType: Walking around city, running in park, playing in park
EliminateRouteComments: When she needs to go, she'll tug towards the street
GeneralComments: Liberty is a wonderful, intelligent, attentive and sweet dog.
DayInLife: I live in a two-bedroom apartment, on the second floor, with my girlfriend Lakshmi, her two-year old son Kieran, and two very well-behaved cats.  I work in marketing for IBM and generally work remotely.    Our day begins around 8pm when Kieran gets up.  Lakshmi is normally gone to work at the hospital by this time so I get Kieran ready for the day (changing him, using the bathroom, getting dressed, and preparing breakfast).  Kieran knows a puppy is coming to live with us in January and is very excited to help with the training.  Kieran is very active and talkative and will need to be trained on how to approach the puppy (as well as vice-versa!)  Kieran’s nanny comes at 9am and stays until 7pm, at which point Lakshmi is home from work.    During the week, I tend to work from a few different places.  I often start working at home and sometimes work from home all day!  Other days I go to an office in midtown near Bryant Park.  I am now driving to Westchester once a week to work in an office there but I expect that to be over by February or March at the latest.  The puppy is welcome at all these work places regardless.    During the day I normally go to the gym or for a run for an hour and the puppy would be left at home in the crate, until the pup is old enough to join me for sustained outdoor exercise.    In the evenings I tend to be out and about doing a variety of different things – playing on a sports team, meeting a friend for a coffee or drink or dinner, going to lectures or meetups on topics I’m interested in, and other social activities.  I’m planning on integrating the puppy as much as possible into these activities.  I also hope that since I will be spending the day with the puppy that the pup will enjoy taking naps in the crate in the early evenings.  Overall though, I understand the pup is my first priority and I don’t have any activities that simply can’t be skipped.    I will also take the dog to visit my parents in Yonkers, where they have an enclosed yard perfect for playing and training.  They have three miniature schanzuers who are on the wild side.  It will definitely be good training on how to deal with less well-behaved dogs!  I have lots of friends in my UES neighborhood and in the building who have dogs.  They have all offered to have the pup over and introduce him to their pets.  We also have an enclosed playground outside the building where the dogs can play in a safe space.    I also enjoy traveling and plan on taking the puppy with me.  Normally I tend to travel abroad but while I’m raising the puppy I hope to learn more about places that are closer to home!  The pup will come with me in the car and we already have a one or two week trip planned to North Carolina via Washington, DC in late April.  My friends are looking forward to meeting the pup and I’m sure it’ll be a good experience for everyone.

DayInLife: I will be traveling out of town June 19 to June 26. After that I will be home for most of the summer. We have an unneutered male great dane living next door who can come in our yard so it might be wise to go with a male puppy, though I would be happy to have a male or female. I am not currently employed so my daily schedule is flexible and changes day to day.   I come and go frequently, but I do not need to leave a puppy for long periods of time. We live in the town of Vienna where there are sidewalks in all the neighborhoods, and lots of people and other dogs walk frequently past our house.  My husband and I are usually around on the week-ends and take lots of hikes in the woods and  walks in our neighborhood.  We are both active and like to be outdoors as much as possible. We have no children at home anymore. I have lots of experience with dogs and I can appreciate how good the training techniques are that GEB is teaching us. I believe that positive reinforcement is the only way to teach a dog, since they always want to please their owner more than anything.

GeneralComments: Adrienne is a sweet and well behaved GSD.  She loves to be with her person but is willing to work with other people.  She does best when I am not too close.  She has made huge strides with her comfort in riding in cars/vans.  She rides beautifully on planes, shuttle and bus.  She has also made nice strides with her "neediness" and no longer comes to me for reassurance (nudge under my arm to be petted).  Our biggest issue is concern with dogs that come into her space quickly and rudely.  After she has "met" a dog even if they are excited initially, she is fine. i have not put her in pup play since because I couldn't be sure that I could call her out if she went out of the T&L zone.  She has done well with all family dogs on swaps too.  She loves to swim, play fetch, puzzle toys and nylabones or stuffed bones.  She is calm when out in public and in crowds.  She is great company.

GeneralComments: Sitters and other people have commented that Riley is very well behaved and is very good in the house. I have been taking her to many different places and into restaurants. She has done well walking on a loose leash and sitting when people ask to pet her when we are at stores. She is very good with kids and even stayed in her settle while some little kids tugged her ears and touched her face. She even sat quietly while a little boy, who had Downsyndrome, petted her.  In restaurants she is sometimes distracted by new smells or crumbs on the floor but she does settle nicely. Also, she will settle nicely at church.  She is getting better on her stair tracking and door manners. She knows all of her commands but we are still working on being able do them in high distracting areas.

BarksExcessivelyComments: He still sometimes barks when I walk out the door, but he has gotten a lot better. Sometimes will start to bark in the kennel as well.

When on walks he becomes very excited and will tend to pull a little towards them to try and get closer to them. He is not allowed to greet another dog unless he sits and is in control, and even then he isn't always allowed to say hello to them. Sometimes I will have him sit until they are done walking by, and at that point he will look back behind us to look at the dog.
KidsComments: He can get very excited to see little kids that are his size but he is good around them.
StrangerComments: He can be overly friendly and becomes very excited to see new people. When on walks he will sometimes pull towards the person because he is excited to see them, and he will turn around to look back at them when I have him keep walking. We are working on it. He doesn't really do that with people when we are out at the store, he generally minds his own business unless someone smells good to him or they talk to him.

GeneralComments: Bethanne is a very cute, lovable, high energy puppy that everyone seems to like on sight. She is also very smart. In many respects, I believe that Bethanne is the smartest puppy that we have raised.  Even with all of her initial issues, she has continued to demonstrate that she can learn.  Please note that the introduction of a prong collar has made a significant difference in dealing with her issues, such as, pulling. Bethanne is a well behaved puppy with the prong collar, not so well behaved without it. I work her about 50% of the time with the prong collar, 25% using just her flat collar and 25% using the prong collar, without attaching the leash to it. The leash is attached to her flat collar.  I think that she has made progress with us. However, there is still much to learn.  John and Bethanne :)

GeneralComments: Nanette has been steadily improving on her pulling on leash skills. She checks in with me more often than the first week she was here and seems more settled in at home. She has joined me on many adventures such as going on the metro to a busy Saturday visit to two separate Smithsonian museums. She is excellent on the metro and will wiggle herself directly under my chair and basically fall asleep until it's time to go. She has gone to a noisey pub, it took her 10-15min to settle down but she was quiet and under the table for 1.5 hours. We headed out in time for elimination. She rides beautifully in the car. We went to a dance concert and, again,l it took her 10-15min to settle but once she did she was fine for about 45min. We did not stay in the theater for the second half of the show as she gave a slight yelp of boredom. But we did stay in the lobby contented to wait for our party to exit the theater. Afterwards she settles directly in the car and slept until we got back home. Every outing seemed to have worn her out but once she gets home she is very excited to play with her doggy housemate. Once it is time to go to bed she will settle right down and kennel wonderfully.

GeneralComments: Houston has dramatically improved over the past quarter, especially with dog distraction and being able to settle for longer periods of time. His personality has greatly "mellowed-out" and he is a delight to spend time with.  He does continue to need to be "busy" at all times - but in a more mellow way - he finds things to keep himself active like chewing a toy.
DayInLife: OK. Our lifestyle: Tony (my husband) runs the Jamestown 4-H Center. We live about 30 minutes away and will occasionally spend days there and have the opportunity to interact with all kinds of people and participate in a lot of activities. I am home with our four children that we homeschool. Our children's ages are 8yrs, 7yrs, 5yrs, and 3yrs.  Since we homeschool we are home a lot. We have a nice sized, fenced-in backyard that the kids spend a lot of time in. Three of our children LOVE dogs. We had our own dogs, but in the past year have had to put both of them down. Our kids are the kind who will lay on the floor petting and loving on the dog. I would prefer a dog with a more calm temperament.  We live on the end of a cul-de-sac in a small town. It's fairly quiet with little to no traffic.. Several of our neighbors have dogs.   Weekends we go to church on Sunday and do AWANA. It's probably the day we are out the most.  During the weekday afternoons we tend to be running around to piano lessons, woodworking class, homeschool group, bible study. We would like to think that we could bring the pup (once they get a little older to many of these things) I have already received some permissions.    We have been in this area for 4.5yrs and don't have any plans on moving any time soon. We have family in NJ and try to travel there about once every 8 weeks or so. We also have a pop-up camper and try to go camping at least one weekend each month. We are hoping that it is OK to take our pup with us for these trips?  Our dogs have always just traveled with us everywhere.  I guess we would also request a pup that doesn't mind being in the car because we are about 30 mins from just about everything, and it will be over an hour drive to get to our GEB class each week.  We have been prepping our kids for some time about getting a GEB pup.    We began about 10 months ago with reading some books; like Follow My Leader and Through Otis' Eyes. Watching documentaries, etc...  As far as exercising; I will be walking our dog each morning, playing in the yard with the kids (like hide & seek and fetch), and my husband usually does shorter evening walks and running/biking on the weekends.  If we can avoid a dog with a strong prey drive/ a chaser, that would help me with the kids in the yard as they tend to run around a ton.  That's all I can think of. We are planning on getting our own pup when our GEB pup is about a year old if everything is working out. We are looking at female Golden Retrievers. For our GEB pup we were going to ask if we could have a female shepherd or a female yellow lab. Of course we would be happy to raise any pup that you think is the best match for our family.

GeneralComments: Brandy is slower to respond to some of her commands when she is in her balance harness, especially heel and close.  She seems not to know how to "negotiate" the two leads.  But she is improving as we continue to work with her.  She readily does "close" and "heel" at home in her harness, but in a different environment it takes her more time.
DayInLife: We live in Raleigh about a mile or so from North Hills and Crabtree Valley.  Our home is on a quiet cul-de-sac with sidewalks.  Most of the houses are on 1/3-1/2 acre lots.  Our backyard is fenced in with lots of birds and squirrels.  We are just steps from the Raleigh Greenway, which provides miles of paved walking trails.      Our lifestyle is rather laid back.  Gail is a retired English teacher.  She works 9-2 Monday-Thursday at a church downtown.  She is 10 minutes from home.  She exercises regularly at the gym.  However, with a puppy she would make her gym membership inactive and change her exercise program to walking (and working/playing) with the dog in the afternoons.  There is also adequate time for the pup before we leave for work.  Gail also enjoys working outside.     David works full-time at the Secretary of State’s office downtown.  He is usually away from home on weekdays from 7:30-5:30.  He is very active on the weekends and on afternoons playing disc golf.      Together we have four sons.  None live at home.  There are no grandchildren…only the children in the neighborhood.    We are usually home on the weekends.  We are hardly ever away overnight.  If we are away, it is for short periods only…going to church, visiting Grandmother, for instance.  We are home almost every evening with the exception of choir rehearsal (Gail) or occasion meeting or movie.       All the years we had dogs, we thought, “When the dogs are gone, we’ll be able to do [this or that] or travel.”  However, over the past 2 years we have noticed that our lifestyle did not change.  We just love to be around home.      Our health is good and we are active.  The opportunity to raise a Guiding Eye pup will be good for us and good for the pup.  We want the activity and joy that a dog brings to a home, but we do not want the extreme sadness that goes along with raising a dog to old age only to grieve when it dies as our beagles did.  But we believe that we can be really good “foster parents.”  Yes, seeing the pup leave us will be hard, but this dog’s purpose is not to be our life-long companion.  This dog has a greater purpose, a higher calling.      The son of one of our friends lost his sight as a teenager to a brain tumor several years ago.  He has become amazingly independent.   He leaves next week for New Jersey to meet his new dog and to learn how his life will change with his new companion.  We are so thrilled for him.  His family and friends are so grateful to the people who made this possible for him.      We believe that we can offer a pup a good home and a good foundation in order to help someone who deserves a more independent life.

He is a pleasure to take to work and well liked by staff who reward his visits with treats. He can get a little anxious when he is separated from his raiser, even with someone he knows, but can be redirected with a to, task, or treat.   He is eager to please and will do what he is asked whether it is to jump onto a low wall or climb a ramp.  Sometimes he can be a little too excitable in attempting to comply with his standard (sit, stay, heel, etc.) requests by offering behavior different than that requested in his desire to earn the treat reward; he can be calmed down with a patient attitude and redirection.  Pablo has a very sensitive stomach and did not thrive on IAMS (dandruff, licking paws, diarrhea) and had a long transition to his new food. He is more likely to have soft stools when given a treat that another Lab eats without any effect.    He is a beautiful dog, runs like the wind, swims without fear, loves us completely, and we are going to miss him terribly when his time comes.
